# _Failing to process some of them because DeepPilot has an issue with fetching or submitting the term predictions and we've already published the Kafka event to DeepView for them._

DeepRecon supports aliases of labels, however, they were really slowing down the queries used to populate the actionable data page. They weren’t actually being used anywhere, so for [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BACK-970|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BACK-970|smart-link] I removed them from the results for the actionable data page. They can still be created and manipulated, they just won’t show up correctly in any query that uses the {{current_label_view}} view. We could restructure the way label aliases are stored so that they run faster and can be reincorporated into the query, or we could move them altogether, but we need to do one of those things.

The reason they were slow is that the label table has an {{is_alias_of_id}} column that indicates which, if any, other label the given label is an alias for. So we would do a join on the label table using the label id, then do another join on the label table with the {{is_alias_of_id}} column. If we wanted to keep the alias functionality we should maybe add an {{alias_label_id}} column to the {{label_association}} and {{label_challenge_to_label_association}} tables so that they can store both the base label and the aliased label ids on the record and speed up the join.

If we decide to remove the functionality, we should remove all associated columns and tables, or at least disable the APIs so that the label aliases aren’t left in a semi-functional state.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Make a rough estimate of how long each approach will take, then consult with product to decide which way to go
* If we decide to remove/disable the label alias functionality:
** APIs for creating/retrieving/updating label aliases should be removed
** Label Aliases should not be returned in the response objects for any APIs
** If we decide to remove the functionality, then associated tables/columns should also be removed
* If we decide to restructure the data so that label aliases can be reincorporated into the {{current_label_view}} view:
** New columns/indexes are added to required tables to speed up label alias access
** The {{current_label_view}} view has been updated to return this information
*** Look at the {{000081_add_outstanding_to_current_label_view}} delta in [deeprecon__models|https://github.com/deepseeai/deeprecon__models/blob/main/promethia_models/migrations/postgres/000081_add_outstanding_to_current_label_view.up.sql] to see how the information should be returned
** Run “explain plan” on the view query before and after the label aliases are added back into it, ensure that the cost isn’t increased substantially

column1: Move Automations API into Extractor Service
column43:
We want to start moving our applications into a “modular monolith” architecture. This means taking some of our existing services and consolidating them into one repository. 

A good place to start would be to put the Automations API into the Extractor Service repository. This would make it so all our interactions with Outlook are happening in one place, and would allow us to synchronize state changes made by the Automations API with the Extractor Service more reliably.

To achieve this, we need to take the existing Automations API code and put it into a module in the Extractor Service. We potentially need to modify the Docker build script so that the Automations API is built into the Extractor Service Docker Image. When we deploy the Extractor Service, we need to make the Automations API endpoints accessible through the Extractor Service’s API. The Automations database should be migrated into the Extractor Service’s database under its own schema.

*Acceptance Criteria*

* The Automations code is moved into a module in the Extractor Service.
* We can build a Docker image for the Extractor Service with the Automations module.
* The Automations API endpoints are exposed through the Extractor Service’s API.
* The Automations database is migrated into a schema in the Extractor Service’s database.

column1: Provide method to map a Colony Bank loan id to an Allegro loan number
column43:
Colony Bank has a loan id included in their Credit Approval document that they use to uniquely identify the deal. Unfortunately, Allegro has a different loan number that uniquely identifies the deal within their system. The Colony Bank loan id is present within the Allegro system, but the only way to identify an Allegro deal with that id is to do an advanced search within the Allegro UI. We need to write some code to take the Colony Bank load id, and use it in the advanced search to find the deal within Allegro. This could be done as a separate API call, or we could incorporate it directly into the API call to trigger the Allegro extraction.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A method is provided to extract the deal from Allegro using the Colony Bank loan id

column1: Make allegro extraction utility callable via API
column43:
Currently the [Allegro extraction code|https://github.com/deepseeai/allegro-form-extraction] is callable as a CLI tool, we need to make it callable via an API. This will require adding or updating an API, there is apparently already an API defined, but it may be outdated and it might make more sense to start from scratch, but if what’s there can be used and will work, then we should use it.

We need to evaluate whether the endpoint should be async or synchronous. The process requires MFA which may take a while, and it may not make sense to have the API endpoint wait. If we decide to make the endpoint async, we will need some way for it to provide the extracted data back to the caller. The easiest way may be to provide an upload url as part of the API call.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The allegro extraction utility can be called via API
* The extracted data is returned to the caller
** If the Allegro extraction won’t take a  long time (> 10 seconds), then we can make the call synchronous, in which case it should return the extracted json in the API response
** If we need to make the API async, then we will also need to provide a way for the caller to get the extracted data. The caller could provide an upload url, or the the API could provide a url at which the document will be made available, or something else.

column1: Create individual automation action types for set custom column action type
column43:
Currently we have the {{SET_CUSTOM_COLUMN_VALUE}} action type. Originally we had intended to allow the user to enter any arbitrary column name they wanted. However we later decided to only allow them to set the value on a specific set of custom columns.

It would simplify things to create a specific action for each custom column. This story is for doing that.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Each of the current possible values for the {{SET_CUSTOM_COLUMN_VALUE}} action type have had a new action created for them
* The {{SET_CUSTOM_COLUMN_VALUE}} action type no longer requires an enum, it should allow an arbitrary value to be entered

column1: Extracted archive documents sometimes fail to upload
column43:
When we receive an archive file from JPM the extractor service extracts the documents, provisions them, then uploads them to s3. Sometimes s3 returns an error like this:

{noformat}com.amazonaws.SdkClientException: Unable to execute HTTP request: prod-jpm-33c72d94-539d-4268-b120-7b3f57626cab-pipeline-output.s3.amazonaws.com
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient$RequestExecutor.handleRetryableException(AmazonHttpClient.java:1219)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient$RequestExecutor.executeHelper(AmazonHttpClient.java:1165)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient$RequestExecutor.doExecute(AmazonHttpClient.java:814)
...
Caused by: java.net.UnknownHostException: prod-jpm-33c72d94-539d-4268-b120-7b3f57626cab-pipeline-output.s3.amazonaws.com
	at java.base/java.net.InetAddress$CachedAddresses.get(InetAddress.java:801)
	at java.base/java.net.InetAddress.getAllByName0(InetAddress.java:1533)
	at java.base/java.net.InetAddress.getAllByName(InetAddress.java:1385)
	at java.base/java.net.InetAddress.getAllByName(InetAddress.java:1306)
	at com.amazonaws.SystemDefaultDnsResolver.resolve(SystemDefaultDnsResolver.java:27)
	at com.amazonaws.http.DelegatingDnsResolver.resolve(DelegatingDnsResolver.java:38){noformat}

It doesn’t happen often, but when it does happen it prevents the work item from being processed. We need to either figure out why this is happening, or ensure that when it does happen, we are able to recover and retry the document. I favor the recovery option, just because that will cover other types of failures as well.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* When an archive document fails to extract, it will get retried later

During the uploading and extraction process we put the documents in a number of different folders, and we even end up with multiple copies of the same file in different spots in the s3 buckets. There are both temporary and permanent files generated during document processing, and the two types of files are intermingled together, making it more difficult to clean up the temporary files and leading to us paying to store a lot of files we don’t need.

We don’t need to necessarily update how the document processing works, but we should use a single folder outside the document processing folders to store permanent files, such as the original uploaded documents, converted pdfs, ui pdfs, and json transcripts of xml documents.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A new s3 folder has been created to store permanent files required for each document
* The extractor service has been modified to use the new folder for all permanent file storage
* Existing files have been moved into the permanent storage folder
* Existing documents have been updated to point to the permanent folder location
* Only one copy of each file is stored permanently. If the original file is a pdf, then we don’t need to store the original and a ui_pdf, they can both point to the same file. If the file was converted from a pdf, we need to store the original, and the converted pdf, but we don’t need to store an additional ui_pdf
** Note: due to the difficulty of migrating the old files to the new location, I think it’s okay if we have to have multiple copies of old migrated files in order to avoid doing a lot of extra processing.

column1: Convert Outlook updates to use the message bus
column43:
We currently have several services all calling the Outlook API to make updates to emails. This leads to duplicate updates, missed updates, and general confusion. We should consolidate the calls to a single service, and have the other services submit updates to outlook by sending messages to the service that is handling the outlook connection.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A single service handles calling the graph api to update outlook messages
* Other services submit outlook message updates through the message bus

column1: Table extraction row numbers are off when we skip rows
column43:
Sometimes excel documents and other tables that are light extracted have a couple of rows that don’t contain actual data and need to be skipped. When that happens the extraction context is incorrect. The extraction context row number should be the rows absolute position in the document, but instead we store the relative position since the beginning of the extraction. For example, if the actual data starts on the fifth row of the spreadsheet, then we store {{1}} for the first row of data, but we should store {{4}} (0 based row numbers).

Here’s an example of the problem:
[https://app.us.deepsee.ai/dtcc/markets/projects/c6b100ad-9b8c-4645-a46f-3d3c8ffba157/content-maps/3d446990-2158-44b5-adb5-46eeee0b8c84/document/8398766a-a450-4160-a391-e39d51a58284|https://app.us.deepsee.ai/dtcc/markets/projects/c6b100ad-9b8c-4645-a46f-3d3c8ffba157/content-maps/3d446990-2158-44b5-adb5-46eeee0b8c84/document/8398766a-a450-4160-a391-e39d51a58284]

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Row and column numbers stored in the extraction context refer to the absolute position of the cell from which the value was extracted, with the top-left most cell being 0,0

column1: Deep Pilot - Link Testing Content Map to corresponding test run
column43:
As a user of Deep Pilot when creating multiple test cases, I want to be able to see what work item ID my test content maps belong to.

Currently, when I create a test case and run it multiple times, it creates a separate test work item. When I open the content map from the test work item, I cannot link it back to the work item (test run) it belongs to. I want to be able to distinguish them to see which has better extraction, etc.

Acceptance criteria:

* Show the link to the test work item on the test content map page
* Clicking the link opens the corresponding work item from the correct test run
* The work item should be labeled with the number of test run/checklist version - done in scope of [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/UI-471|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/UI-471|smart-link] 
* The Breadcrumb includes the test case name

We already have some great datadog dashboards!  In addition, it could be helpful to have basic stats on core processes running for some time on a best-effort realistic dataset (emails/documents) to assess stability, regressions and help inform resource allocation.

Acceptance criteria (each concern below by each core process inside light extraction, heavy extraction, predictions, Feel evaluation, automation, calls to python services):

# +Core runtime profile+ (Test & Metrics): Create a repeatable java performance/profile test with minimal dependencies on other services which can be run from a main method or test harness for a specified duration / iterations and number of threads to profile under load.
# +Observability / runtime process stats+: Log as json the following per hour - # requests, avg # of work units in queue, # processed, # failed, # failed retries, # deadletters, avg work unit size (#pages/MB). Json logs allow us to extract stats. For hosted processes, datadog can dashboard and alert from json logs with minimal fuss. Given a log dump from an on-premise customer, we can extract stats for forensics. Explore additional open telemetry stats in a future effort. See [https://sre.google/sre-book/monitoring-distributed-systems/#xref_monitoring_golden-signals|https://sre.google/sre-book/monitoring-distributed-systems/#xref_monitoring_golden-signals|smart-link]  per Jeff.

Findings:

* See [BACK-999|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BACK-999]: for metrics related to the ms-graph-api (outlook emails)

column1: Convert inter-service api calls to use a message bus (kafka?)
column43:
Many of the problems we see in processing documents come up because one service makes a call to another service to perform an action, and the second service is unavailable for some reason. We could greatly reduce these errors by instead using a message bus to communicate these sorts of messages between services. For example, rather than the automation service calling the extractor service to perform an action, it could publish a message to the message bus, and if it was down, then the extractor service would receive the message when it came back up, and perform the action. This would also let us fan-out state updates to the different services more easily, and allow us to maintain a single source of truth.

We have a lot of calls going between the services, so it will be a big job to convert everything over. Rather than doing it all at once, we should convert one or two endpoints to use a message bus instead, then convert the other endpoints bit-by-bit as we have time.

We already have the infrastructure set up for Kafka, so it might make sense to use that, but whoever implements this can consider other solutions and discuss them with the team.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A message bus is put in place for communication between the back end services
* One or more interactions between the services have been converted from API calls to messages

column1: Queue Email Processing Attempts Through Kafka
Add APIs to Retry Failed Automation Executions and Actions
column43:
As a DeepSee user, I would like the ability to track and re-submit any failed automation executions or automation action executions. 

Dead letter topics are provided for both the actions and automation triggers. We need to add listeners to consume from these topics and flush the results to the database. We should model the database tables to manage these to support both successful and failed attempts, but only track failures for the initial implementation. There probably won’t be value in storing the raw message payload for successful attempts, so we should create an additional table to join that has the message payload to be resubmitted for failures. We should maintain context on the ordering of messages for each execution so that they may be submitted in the same order for retry that they were originally. APIs will need to be provided for both cases to expose the information on the failed automations or actions in general and in context of the execution or message that they were attempted for. Another API should be provided to resubmit all failed attempts for an execution or message along with one to resubmit individual messages. Resubmission should work by publishing the failed message back to the original Kafka topic it was dead-lettered from.



*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Dead letter messages for automations and actions are flushed to the database
* APIs are provided to expose those failed messages to end users and re-submit them
* Ordering is preserved in the context of an execution

*Future Considerations:*

* Design in a way that the APIs and backing database entities can be extended to include successful processing as well
* Some messages may not be processed due to a fatal exception (for example, a malformed message payload). Let’s ensure that we can extend the functionality to prevent the ability to retry these.

+Problem we’re solving+: Commit engineering cycles to harden our platform (aka preventative actions).
+Rationale+: Mitigate the risk of instability undermining our hard work and opportunity. The market isn’t forgiving.
+Objective+: Engineers capture and POC actionable ideas to harden and improve our platform.
+Out of Scope+: Platform / product and customer features. Spending a lot of time going down rabbit holes.

Please provide a brief charter statement in each ticket with the following:
(S) *See*: Hypothesis, measures (what we know), difficulty (NP-complete?), new-to (world, market, company), waste
(T) *Think*: Grab a few folks and capture ideas for tooling, automation, simplification
(E) *Experiment*: Quick POC (< 2 wk) to vet feasibility
(P) *Prove*: Request for comments (rfc) to socialize the concept, then create a reference implementation
(S) *Sustain*: Document the ROI, dashboard to track the improvement

column250:
06/May/25 9:51 AM;712020:e3ff8b27-058e-446f-a5c5-3adc663bc195;We had a quick call with Aubrey who shared the following related to PII: Globally, identifiers considered PII can be broadly categorized into two types:
*Direct Identifiers:* These are pieces of information that can identify an individual on their own. Common examples include:

* Full name
* Unique identification numbers (e.g., Social Security Number, passport number, driver's license number, taxpayer identification number)
* Biometric data (e.g., fingerprints, retinal scans, facial geometry)
* Financial account numbers (e.g., bank account number, credit card number)

*Indirect Identifiers:* These are pieces of information that may not identify an individual on their own but can do so when combined with other data. The context in which data is used is crucial in determining if indirect identifiers constitute PII. Examples often cited include:

* Date and place of birth
* Mother's maiden name
* Address information (e.g., street address, email address)
* Telephone number
* Employment information
* Geographical details (e.g., ZIP code, city, state, country)
* Online identifiers (e.g., IP address, cookie identifiers, device IDs)
* Personal characteristics (e.g., race, ethnicity, religion, gender)
* Vehicle registration number

*Sensitive PII:* Certain categories of PII are considered more sensitive due to the potential for greater harm if compromised. These often receive heightened protection under various regulations. Examples include:

* Medical records and health information
* Genetic data
* Biometric data used for unique identification
* Information revealing racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, religious or philosophical beliefs, or trade union membership
* Data concerning a person's sex life or sexual orientation

It's important to note that the definition and specific examples of PII can vary depending on the applicable privacy laws and regulations in different jurisdictions. For instance, the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) has a broad definition of "personal data" that encompasses a wide range of online identifiers, while definitions in other regions may be narrower.Furthermore, the increasing ability to combine seemingly innocuous data points to identify individuals means that what might not have been considered PII in the past could be classified as such today. Therefore, a risk-based approach is often necessary to assess whether a particular piece or combination of information constitutes PII in a given context. (edited)

column1: Improve Source Relevance and Section Filtering in DeepGPT
column43:
*Goal:* Ensure that DeepGPT does not include irrelevant or misleading sources in multi-source responses and filters out unrelated references.

As a user, I want DeepGPT responses to include only contextually relevant sources and policy sections, so the answers are focused, reliable, and not confusing.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Chat filters out policy documents or sections that do not align with the user query
* Returned sections and page numbers are precise and related to the question

*Goal:* Fix errors where chat pulls answers from the wrong section, wrong page, or says info doesn’t exist, despite it being present in a known location.

As a user, I want DeepGPT to pull answers from the correct section and page of the uploaded policy document, so I receive responses that are accurate and grounded in the right content

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Chat references correct document sections and page numbers based on question content
* Avoid fallback to unrelated sections (e.g., responsibilities instead of purchasing)
* External attachments (e.g., charts) are used when available

column1: Improve Section-Level Summarization Accuracy in chat with Policies
column43:
As a user, I want DeepGPT to accurately summarize specific sections of uploaded policy documents, so that I can rely on summaries for key terms and procedures.

Goal: the summary is complete, truthful to the source, and does not skip key details.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Summaries should match the language, scope, and meaning of the referenced section
* Must include all required roles or approvals when multiple are defined (e.g., BSA and Board)
* Avoid skipping or rewording that changes the policy meaning

We have PDFs from sunwest on policies, we want a chat interface that will allow them to ask questions grounded in this dataset.

The UI will have a fixed chat interface, as users chat, if there are citable resources to cite with the answer, when a user clicks on the link it’ll pull open the policy with a bounding box highlighted.

When a user clicks on another citation, it’ll open that document. Only need to show one document at a time.

column1: Sources incorrectly removed from consideration for subgroup matching
column43:
When we do the final subgroup context filtering when processing a checklist, to determine if a subgroup match is valid, we ensure that all required sources are included in the match. However, while we’re still generating matches, if a subgroup is included in any matches (e.g. two out of three of the sources match), even if not all required sources are included, we remove that subgroup and source from future consideration. This means that if we are matching on multiple key-terms, and two of the groups match on the first key term, then those groups won’t be considered for the second key term, even though it isn’t technically a valid match.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A match must be completely valid, meaning all required sources are present, before the sources included in the match are removed from future consideration
* The test for this scenario in the {{SubgroupContextGeneratorTest}} class has been uncommented and passes

h3. Goal

Enable users to manually trigger automations on selected single (or bulk) emails for better control over email processing.

h3. Why to implement:

* New Automation was created after the emails were received in DeepRecon and needs to be applied to selected email(s)
* Re-run automation that failed on email import / completion
* Users want to validate automation outcomes on a specific email
* Gives the users control, that way increases their confidence and trust in the system



h3. Key Deliverables

* Ability to select one email (later when bulk actions are built - more emails) from the grid
* “Run Automation” button in UI
*  Process automation on the backend 
* Record of manual execution
* Log of manual automation runs for audit/debugging
* Confirmation on success/error on fail
* Messages processed accordingly, corresponding records updated

column1: Create API to Tombstone Term Aliases
column43:

* As a DeepSee user I am able to retrieve a list of tombstoned aliases.
* As a DeepSee user, if I attempt to create an alias with the same name as a currently tombstoned alias, then I am alerted of the duplicate and am recommended to un-tombstone the existing alias.
* When a term alias is tombstoned, then I no longer see it in the library with non-tombstoned aliases.
* When a term alias is tombstoned, then it will not be used when processing term extractions.

column43:
When we update a message in Recon, we send a call to Pilot to update the predictions and update the email in the Outlook API. The calls between Pilot and Recon are pretty messy right now and could be cleaned up to be more consistent and robust.

When Recon calls Pilot for a message update, it puts a property into the request telling Pilot that it’s from Recon so that Pilot doesn’t try to update Recon and we get stuck in an infinite update loop. The reason Pilot calls Recon is because updates in Outlook come through Pilot, but we also have to update Recon.

Somehow we need to straighten these calls out. Updates from Outlook will be picked up by Pilot which needs to update Recon, without Recon trying to update Pilot. Updates in the DeepSee UI will be picked up by Recon, which needs to update Pilot and Outlook. So by “straighten out”, we need to architect these calls in a way that doesn’t run the risk of circular updates and is also easier to maintain and extend. I’m wondering if we should just create separate APIs for all these cases instead of trying to reuse the same endpoints.

column1: Allow left-joins in DeepView data model field queries
column43:
DeepView data models can be queried directly for field values using the {{fields}} keyword, see here for more information:
[https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2163867649/Predefined+Dashboard+Breakdown#Query-Function|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2163867649/Predefined+Dashboard+Breakdown#Query-Function|smart-link] 

This is pretty handy, but when it joins two data models together, it does so using a right-join, which means that if the joined data model doesn’t have any data, then nothing will be returned. An example of this is this automations query:

{noformat}https://api.dev.deepsee.ai/deepview/data/projects/c1ea2c7c-393e-4be1-80c5-1b5925267dae/automation-executions?fields=message.messageId,automation.name,status,error,executionTimestamp,actionType,actionValue&filters=message.messageId:eq:224185{noformat}

This will return information about automation executions for a particular message. If the automation was skipped because another automation completed successfully, that information will be available in the {{preemptingAutomation}} field, so if you wanted the name of the automation that caused the automation you’re querying to be skipped, then you could add {{preemptingAutomation.name}} to the field list. However, since it’s a right-join, if the automation wasn’t skipped because of another automation, then it won’t have a value for {{preemptingAutomation}} and won’t be returned. So you would first need to perform a query for all the automation executions, then another one to get the names of the automations that caused an automation to be skipped.

If we added the option for a field to be left-joined, then the query could return null for those automation-executions that didn’t have a {{preemptingAutomation}}.

[https://api.eu.deepsee.ai/accenture-barclays/deeprecon-v1/projects/fc62db8a-4419-4115-85f9-80dbf6719592/terms/aliases?includeAliasUsageStats=true|https://api.eu.deepsee.ai/accenture-barclays/deeprecon-v1/projects/fc62db8a-4419-4115-85f9-80dbf6719592/terms/aliases?includeAliasUsageStats=true]

As a user of DeepSee Email process automation agents, we need to be able to read outgoing messages as well and get intelligence about what is happening there as well so that we not only map what is incoming and determining the job to be done, but also focusing on how the issues are being resolved.



Can we connect these to the incoming emails to help determine better responses and to track the questions that we had and then tie any responses from the counterparty.



This could also be shown as a separate filter as inbox like we show multiple email inboxes now to affect the dashboard feed as well.  



Useful dashboards could be useful to show how many emails are sent to each counterparty (both external and internal) and for what to allow more root cause analysis.

To support truly Agentic AI workflows, the output of what they create needs to be able to be easily configured to quickly integrate into multiple systems.  This will let Agents move quickly and support the maximum amount of use cases as possible.



The top ways that we will need to support agent output fit into three categories

# CSV/XLS
# JSON/XML
# Summary or question to send to another customer agent or to DeepGPT to craft into a email response



For 1 and 2, I think it’s simple ability to Select fields that the agent extracts or validates through process model logic, and then use ETL to organize them in these formats per the receiving agent’s requirements.  In an ideal situation, we could see what the initlal output is, and then compare that with an example output that the receiving system expects.  Then our feature suggests a mapping of its fields to what is expected.  Then the user can reveiw it and correct or approve it.



This can be an agent or a UI that is like the testing suite.



For #3, we need to think about training a crew, to read the output that the agent generates.  This can summarize it into either a blurb on what is found or a list of open questions.  It can then change that summary into the required format of the next agent or DeepGPT that wll require to help it perform its next function in the Agentic Workflow.

[https://lucid.app/lucidchart/f8af38ad-242e-48f7-bfe2-7d97b6f60fdc/edit?viewport_loc=18%2C-36%2C4657%2C2505%2C0_0&invitationId=inv_86566aab-f8f9-4c34-b28b-734969484783|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/f8af38ad-242e-48f7-bfe2-7d97b6f60fdc/edit?viewport_loc=18%2C-36%2C4657%2C2505%2C0_0&invitationId=inv_86566aab-f8f9-4c34-b28b-734969484783|smart-link]

column1: Ability to query, extract, and use a file or terms from a system that can be used by our automation engines to reconcile and validate against otherdocuments.
column43:
As a user of DeepSee Knowledge Process Agents, sometimes the required structured data is not available ahead of time when a work item is created eventhough it is requried.  



We need the ability to query systems based on a few questions that can be extracted from some of the documents that are provided. An example could be a trade ID, or trade data, account, security, and quantity.



These terms would be formed into a query to send to the system to get the required structured data.  This could pull an entire record or just the required fields, we should think about both ways to ensure flexibility and even consider if we have to query multiple systems to pull multiple files for a single work item.



This query could happen at the beginning of a work item, or it could be similar to how the email work items are occurring today for DTCC where you can crete a few automated items to show what the agent is doing to get the required data that is needed to complete the required process agent task.

column1: same email to multiple inboxes should make multiple message IDs in recon/pilot
column43:
The requirements for making automations for the same email in multiple inboxes included that the user should be able to automate the same email *differently* depending on which inbox received it.

Right now, we are treating ‘receiving_inbox’ as an array of values for the email. This makes it so that the email will trigger all automations for any of the receiving inboxes. We need separate deepsee message IDs and documentIds per email per inbox so that they can be automated differently. The only difference on the message records would be the receiving_inbox. But they could also have different values for follow-up status, priority, action required, folder, etc.

column1: Update DTCC use case to use updateStageStatus endpoint
column43:
When the intent agent calls the updateStageStatus endpoint, it needs to provide information about which checklists to create and what sources to assign the documents to. If we added a {{metadata}} type property to the endpoint that accepted a generic json object, then clients that call the endpoint could provide any information required for the next stage of execution processing.

We also need to update the execution manager so that it can handle the DTCC use case both how it’s currently working, and through a flow depending on the updateStageStatus endpoint.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The updateStageStatus endpoint has a {{metadata}} property that can be used to pass in arbitrary data required for execution processing
* The endpoint should create a new execution_processing_event, and the {{metadata}} should be stored in the {{context}} column
* The DTCC use case should be updated to work either how it currently works, or if the updateStageStatus endpoint is called

column1: Update intent-agent to accept extracted documents
column43:
In order to consolidate and simplify our document processing pipelines, and to ensure that new features are available for all processing pipelines, we should have the extractor service extract all the documents, create doc_file records for them, then send the document_ids and bytes to the intent-agent to figure out what to do with them.

We need to add an endpoint to the intent-agent that will accept a collection of document objects, each with at least the filename, document_id and document bytes. It would then process these documents as it currently does, but it wouldn’t need to worry about extracting multiple tabs from excel files, password protection, extracting zip files, etc.

In addition, the intent-agent should call the extractor-service updateStageStatus endpoint, rather than calling the execution provisioning endpoint.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The intent-agent can accept and process a collection of documents that have been extracted from an email, or even uploaded individually
* The intent-agent calls the updateStageStatus endpoint instead of the execution provisioning endpoint

column1: Have extractor-service send extracted documents to intent-agent
column43:
In order to consolidate and simplify our document processing pipelines, and to ensure that new features are available for all processing pipelines, we should have the extractor service extract all the documents, create doc_file records for them, then send the document_ids and bytes to the intent-agent to figure out what to do with them.

We need to update the extractor-service to be able to handle password protected files where the password is available in the body of the email or the filename. We also need to have it extract individual tabs from excel files. It should create doc_file records for the extracted files, then send them to the intent-agent for processing.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The execution manager extracts attachments, individual xls file tabs, and creates {{doc_files}} records for them
* The execution manager can handle password protected files
* The execution manager sends the documents to the intent-agent for processing

column1: Demo: Wrapper for Light Ontology Agent
column43:
We have an executive demo with one of our customers. Part of this demo includes showing our vision for DeepGPT Q&A.

The purpose of this story is to create a wrapper for a Bedrock Agent that provides necessary context when a question is asked.

The agent simulates a TypeDB Reasoner, and this wrapper provides data to the Reasoner in a RAG like fashion.

Acceptance Criteria:
* Wrapper service is deployed in Demo and Accessible.

h2. Description

h2. *Context:*

 

To simplify the design we have decoupled the ml_workflows from the database.
When we train a model, we we pass the labels to the ml_workflows in text form ( i.e “Prematching.Cash Mismatch“ ).
This is the newest label for a given {{inquiry}} . In case if the {{inquiry}} was originally labeled with a {{label}} that was later marked as {{alias of}} other {{label}}, then ml_workflow will receive the {{aliased label}} ( the one that is the target in the {{alias_of}} ).

The model trained with this approach has no idea about the label_id’s, and returns text ( i.e “Prematching.Cash MIsmatch“ ) as a predicted label

h2. *Why we need this spike:*

For a given renaming scenario:

# User used label “Prematching.Cash Mismatch“
# Model was trained
# User renamed “Prematching.Cash Mismatch“ to “Prematching.Mismatch Cash“
# For a given text the model will still return “Prematching.Cash Mismatch“, where it should return the renamed label “Prematching.Mismatch Cash“

ℹ️ The same would happen if the user renamed the label to fix a typo

h2. *Considered options:*

h3. 1. Retrain the model after every change ( rename or delete in labels )

Pros:

* consistency

Cons:

* time and resource-consuming

h3. 2. Handling the changes in labels with aliases for rename and soft deletes for removal



In this option, we would hide labels instead of deleting them.

For every rename operation, we would have to create a new label and make the old name, and alias of the just created label.


Pros:

* the impact of removal ( soft delete ) and rename is much smaller
* the ml part is still decoupled from the database



Cons:

* after fixing typo we would end up with aliases that are useless
* we have to remember to show only the {{aliased labels}} and the labels that do not have aliases in the UI and in the classification api
* rename may be tricky to handle in the UI
** Let’s say that I received from backend {“id“: 1, “Prematching.Cash Mismatch“}
** I renamed a label in the UI. I send to the backend “Prematching.Mismatch Cash“ for the id 1
** Because it is not a simple rename the backend would have to
*** create new label “Prematching.Mismatch Cash“
*** mark the existing Prematching.Cash Mismatch as alias of “Prematching.Mismatch Cash”
** The backend would have to return a body that would allow UI to understand that the {“id“: 1, “Prematching.Cash Mismatch“} should be removed from the labels visible in UI
and {“id“: 999, “Prematching.Mismatch Cash“} should be added to the labels visible in UI
*** ℹ️ Here the UI could just query all the labels with {{only_not_aliases}} set to True
* consequences of hiding aliases
** What should happen if aliased label is not visible in UI and user will try to create a label that is alias of other label
*** Should we ask him to use the aliased label?
*** Should we ‘break' the aliasing and make it a separate label again ( set {{is_alias_of}} to NULL) ?

h3. 3. Couple the ml workflow with label IDs:

In this approach, we would create a snapshot of all {{aliased labels}} and {{labels that are not aliases}} as a dataframe with {{label_id,label_text}} columns, and we would pass it to ml workflows as an additional parameter.

The pipeline that trains the model would then map the label_text to label_id, and the model would predict the {{label_id}} instead of {{label_text}} for a given {{inquiry}} .

Thanks to that, if the user would rename a label (i.e. he would fix a typo ) it would not matter either for the model or for the backend. The predicted {{label_id}} would be connected in the backend with the correct text from database. Of course if the label with {{label_id}} would be marked as {{is_alias_of}} in meantime then we would show the {{aliased_label}}

(i) We should still consider using soft deletes ( hiding ) instead of removing a label, but the rename would be much simpler

 

Pros:

* much simpler and more intuitive handling of the labels in the rest of the system
* small additional mapping contained in one place
* the produced model is more robust for the changes in the system

Cons:

* we would need to keep the history of renaming a label a in a separate table
* coupling of ml pipeline with db that we tried to avoid after re-architecting
* it would require doing the id → text mapping to verify if the model returns the correct labels

h2. *Expected outcome of the spike:*

* Decision which solution should be implemented
* Tasks/Stories for the Implementation

column1: Split the reconMessageId out of doc_files.external_id
column43:
For a while we were storing the message_id from DeepRecon in the {{external_id}} column in the DocFiles table, we then started also storing the internetMessageId from outlook in that column, since we really only needed to know one or the other. However, we needed to start storing both values for some aspects of automations and DeepView, so we added a {{recon_message_id}} column to the table to track that. There are some places where we’re still storing the recon id in the {{external_id}} column, and we should update all of those to point to the {{recon_message_id}} column instead. We should also update the {{createContentMapPredictions}} and {{updateContentMapPredictions}} endpoints to create a new {{doc_file}} record if one doesn’t already exist, and to store the recon_message_id in the appropriate column. Additionally, the getDocument endpoint checks the passed in document reference against the {{document_id}} column and the {{external_id}} column, we should also have it check the {{recon_message_id}} column.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A migrations script has been written populate the {{recon_message_id}} column with the value from the {{external_id}} column where the {{recon_message_id}} is null and the {{external_id}} column is not null and the {{external_id}} column can be cast to an integer.
* The getDocument endpoint checks the {{recon_message_id}} column if the passed in document reference isn’t a valid UUID and it wasn’t found in the {{external_id}} column
* The {{createContentMapPredictions}} and {{updateContentMapPredictions}} endpoints to create a new {{doc_file}} record if one doesn’t already exist
* Anywhere else that the {{external_id}} column is being used as the deeprecon id is updated to reference the {{recon_message_id}} column

column1: Use userIds to connect to Outlook rather than email addresses
column43:
In outlook, a user has a {{mail}} property, and a {{principleName}} property, typically the two are the same, but they aren’t required to be the same. We run into problems if they are different, because DeepView stores all of its data under the actual email of the user, and the {{principleName}} is what is needed to connect to the Microsoft Graph API. You can also use the user {{id}} to connect to the Graph API, we need to start using that instead.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A new column is added to the {{outlook_inboxes}} table to track the {{id}} of the user for the inbox
** We don’t necessarily need to use the id, we could use the {{principleName}}, and we may want to make the new database column a string so that we could use either
* All interactions with the Graph API use the {{id}} or {{principleName}} rather than the {{email_address}}

column1: Automate API doc production in the deeprecon__api repository
column43:
In the {{deeprecon__api}} repository, we build out our internal API documentation using the {{promethia_api/openapi/openapi.json}} file. Unfortunately, this file was manually added by me and is not currently set up to automatically update when the API spec changes.

The purpose of this ticket is to automate the creation of that API spec file. Ideally it would be best if that spec file could be generated at build time and not need to be tracked in git.

h2. Acceptance Criteria

* Update the CI/CD flow for the {{deeprecon__api}} repository so that when a change to API docs is detected, it is able to generate the latest API spec file(s) before executing the shared update-api-schema action that pushes the changes to our documentation sites.

As a user I want a ML model to learn what the correct priority is for my emails based on my automations and my feedback, so that when new emails come in that don’t completely match the automations, the model can still predict what the priority will be.

Priorities:

* Critical
* High
* Medium
* Low
* No Action

When the priority is “No Action” then the “Action Required” field should be marked as N. When there is a priority, then the “Action Required” field should be marked as Y.

The training data should be based on the emails in Actionable Data - the priority added by automations and updated by users.

Prioritization Model Documentation:
[https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/MR/pages/2616098821/DeepRecon+-+Prioritization+Model|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/MR/pages/2616098821/DeepRecon+-+Prioritization+Model|smart-link]

column1: DeepView filters fail with special characters
Figure out how to handle long-running database migration scripts
column43:
We recently had a database migration script that updated all of the term_prediction records. Accenture has ~39 million term prediction records, so the update script timed out and was marked as a failure. Because of that the schema_migrations version was marked as dirty, the deployment was marked as a failure, and it wasn’t able to recover on its own. I avoided this in JPM by running the script manually beforehand, but I didn’t realize how many predictions were in Accenture, so I didn’t do it there as well.

We need to figure out how to handle these cases in the future. There will be times that we’ll need to execute long-running queries against the database as part of a deployment and as we have more customers, particularly self-hosted customers, we’re not going to be able to manually run these queries before the deployment goes out.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* When we have a long-running query go out as part of a deployment, it needs to be able to run for a long while without timing out, the rest of the deployment should wait for the query to finish
* If a deployment fails we shouldn’t have to go into the database and manually set the version to not be dirty, it should be able to retry on its own

# User can train a model that recognizes nested subgroups (one level of nesting) and correctly (with training) predicts relationships within the subgroup.

column1: Create Serving Runtimes for Inference and Association models
column43:
As a DeepSee customer, I need to be able to manage the training of my own models. I need to be able to trigger the training, test the resulting model, and control when the model is promoted to production use for different projects in the system.

DeepSee’s previous approach to serving model versions required that we had a unique endpoint for each model version that was always running. This accrued a lot of costs, especially when we were running in SageMaker.

To resolve this issue, the infrastructure team has identified that we will be using Model Mesh from Kserve. Instead of building and deploying images for each model version, we will build and deploy Serving Runtimes that will work for multiple versions of the model. When a model is requested – if there is not already a Serving Runtime that is running it – then the weights will be dynamically loaded into a Serving Runtime for that model.

In order to make this work the following outcomes are needed:

Acceptance Criteria:

* Model Mesh is a productionalized part of our infrastructure deployment.
* Initial Serving Runtimes are created (Not sure if we need one that can support both Inference and Association, or if we need a separate runtime for each).

column1: Filter process models returned by the Automations API
column43:
We don’t currently have a good way to determine which process model gets used when importing emails through Outlook polling. What we’re doing is looking for a checklist that has a source with ‘email’ as the normalized names, then of those checklists it picks the one with the most sources. This causes problems when the user selects a checklist for an automation that won’t get used. We eventually plan to determine this based on the email category, but that’s going to be some work. To prevent users from creating automations for process models that won’t be run, we need to filter the process models that are returned to the UI from the automations {{getProjectProcesses}} endpoint.

The automations API calls the extractor service to get a list of checklists, it should then filter those based on the logic above. When it’s done there should only be one checklist left, which should be returned. This isn’t a great fix, but it’s quick and it’s temporary until we’re able to support logic to determine which checklist to use.

You can find the logic that the extractor service uses to choose which checklist to use here:
[https://github.com/deepseeai/extractor-service/blob/08f30f4c7a090be08bf95f241b0ce2cdf1d4d1ba/service/src/main/java/ai/deepsee/deeprecon/extractor/outlook/polling/service/OutlookMessageProcessingService.java#L255|https://github.com/deepseeai/extractor-service/blob/08f30f4c7a090be08bf95f241b0ce2cdf1d4d1ba/service/src/main/java/ai/deepsee/deeprecon/extractor/outlook/polling/service/OutlookMessageProcessingService.java#L255] 

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The AutomationsAPI {{getProjectProcesses}} endpoint returns only one checklist
* It uses the same logic as the extractor service to determine which checklist to return

column1: Create Schema to support customer management of Project Scoped Authorization
column43:
To support customer management of Project Scoped Authorization we need to be able to store a list of DeepSee roles, a list of customer defined idpRoles, and associations between the idpRoles/user emails and the DeepSee roles. See [this document|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/tree/main/aws/lambdas/pretoken-generator] for additional details.

It doesn’t have to be done this way, but here’s a rough outline for how I’m thinking it would work:

# We create a new table for storing DeepSee roles, this would be populated with the initial data. It would include a name and a field indicating whether it is a role that the customer can link their roles to. We have some internal roles, such as {{MLP}} and {{System Integration}} that users should not be able to link their roles to.
# We create a new table for storing customer defined idp roles. Users would be able to create new idp roles or disable existing ones. We would want to include audit columns here so we know who changed what.
# We create a new table for associating a DeepSee role, a project, and either an idp role or a user. We could do that by having two different columns, one would store a reference to the customer idp table, the other would store a reference to the {{user_info}} table. One of the columns would always be null. This association table would need to have audit columns as well.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The schema has been updated to support the requirements of the APIs listed here: [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BACK-549|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BACK-549|smart-link]

column1: Project Scoped Authorization for Self Hosted Customers
column43:
As a Self Hosted customer of DeepSee, I want to be able to create my own projects, and manage who has access to them.

DeepSee’s current customers are not able to create their own projects. When we create a new project for them, we also update the manual configurations in the [pretoken generator lambda|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/tree/main/aws/lambdas/pretoken-generator] to control access to that project. This means each project Id needs to be hardcoded into the lambda before we can provide access to that project.

The outcome of this epic is to allow the pretoken generator lambda to know about projects dynamically. This may slow down the process of creating the token, but we should make sure we are not slowing it down by seconds.

Acceptance Criteria

* Database schema exists to store associations between user emails or customer idpRoles to DeepSee roles for different projects.
* APIs exist to allow the UI to provide those roles
* APIs exist to allow the UI to create associations between the users/idpRoles and the DeepSee roles
* Provide the query needed to Infra to build scopes in the pretoken generator lambda

h5. Severity

* The exposure of the access token allows attackers to potentially perform Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, resulting in token theft and account takeover. Attackers can also impersonate users, gain unauthorized access, and perform actions on their behalf.

h5. Suggested Fix

* The JWT needs to be stored inside an HTTPOnly cookie, a special kind of cookie that’s only sent in HTTP requests to the server, and it’s never accessible (both for reading or writing) from JavaScript running in the browser.

column1: 24Q4-PenTest: TLS Misconfiguration - Weak Ciphers in Use
column43:
h5. Severity

* An attacker can attempt to steal sensitive information transmitted between a client and the host.
* An attacker can attempt to modify sensitive information transmitted between a client and the host.

h5. Suggested Fix

* Disable weak ciphers like RC4, DES, and 3DES, and configure hosts to use strong ciphers like AES with a minimum of 128-bit key length, prioritizing forward secrecy suites like ECDHE or DHE.

h5. Severity

* When this file is accessed a "heavy" MySQL query is performed, so it could be used by the attackers to cause a denial of service vulnerability. Also, by default, the {{wp-cron.php}} is called on every page load (anytime a user requests any WordPress page), which on high-traffic sites can cause problems (DoS).

h5. Suggested Fix

It is recommended that the application should disable {{Wp-Cron}} and create a real cronjob inside the host that performs the needed actions in a regular interval (without causing issues).

h5. Severity

* An attacker could attempt to forge a valid token or steal the existing token that could be used to perform authenticated actions on behalf of the victim user.

h5. Suggested Fix

* Ensure that security tokens expire when a user logs out. Generate new tokens each time a user logs into an account. This ensures previous security tokens cannot be reused in requests that the application accepts.

h5. Severity

* An attacker could utilise the configuration and import map information to understand various mapping and libraries or configurations used by the application which could be useful in further attack vectors.

h5. Suggested Fix

* Restrict endpoints for unauthenticated and public access.

h5. Severity

* An unauthenticated attacker may attempt to maximize the size accepted and processed by this endpoint and further exhaust resources unnecessarily resulting in a denial of service attack.
* This issue is easy to discover and is always reproducible.

h5. Suggested Fix

WordPress did not patch this vulnerability because they view it as an extensive resource exhaustion attack, and as such should be mitigated by a network firewall/web application firewall.

h5. Severity

* The WordPress xmlrpc.php file can allow a malicious actor to perform DDoS and brute force attacks.

h5. Suggested Fix

* Remove the xmlrpc.php file from the server or use a WordPress plugin to disable it.

h5. Severity

* This issue can be used to trigger actions without the victim's consent. While the action itself can be harmful, it requires some degree of interaction with the victim.

h5. Suggested Fix

# Use the {{X-Frame-Options}} header to assist in protecting the web applications against Clickjacking attacks. The {{X-Frame-Options}} header takes three values:
#* {{Deny}} (no rendering of application in frames).
#* {{Allow-from}} (rendering allowed from specified domains).
#* {{same-origin}} (rendering allowed from the same domain).
# Use a securely configured {{Content-Security-Policy}} (CSP) {{frame-ancestors}} directive response header that instructs the web browser to disallow framing from other domains.
# Use the {{sameSite}} cookie attribute so that session cookies are not included when a vulnerable application is loaded in an iframe.

h5. Severity

* Setting up the aforementioned HTTP security headers will improve the application security posture by mitigating various security issues such as Cross-Site Scripting , Clickjacking and Man-in-the-middle attacks.

h5. Suggested Fix

# Implement the recommended HTTP security response headers based on need and application requirements. Set attributes and values as securely as possible based on application requirements.

h5. Severity

* An attacker could attempt to utilise this misconfiguration by bypassing the origin-based restrictions in various attack vectors.

h5. Suggested Fix

* Implement a strong CORS policy.
* Validate origins from cross-domain requests.
* Whitelist all trusted sites using the {{Access-Control-Allow-Origin}} header.
* Do not set the {{Access-Control-Allow-Origin}} header to Null.
* Avoid using {{*}} wildcard in the {{Access-Control-Allow-Origin}} header, which allows requests from any origin.
* Do not use the Origin header for authentication and access control, as it can be modified by an attacker.

h5. Severity

* An attacker can collect a set of valid user emails by interacting with the auth mechanism of the application. Knowledge of presence valid email/login in the application may lead to performing brute force attacks or lead to targeted attacks (like phishing).

h5. Suggested Fix

* Configure the web application so that it does not reveal information about whether accounts are valid. Return generic error messages that respond to all requests with a message saying that account reset instructions were sent by email, regardless of whether that account exists.

h5. Severity

* An attacker can collect a set of valid user emails by interacting with the auth mechanism of the application. Knowledge of presence valid email/login in the application may lead to performing brute force attacks or lead to targeted attacks (like phishing).

h5. Suggested Fix

* Configure the web application so that it does not reveal information about whether accounts are valid. Return generic error messages that respond to all requests with a message saying that account reset instructions were sent by email, regardless of whether that account exists.

As a way to further train our LLM-based extraction models, I want to take advantage of the Patronus AI Data set.



[https://huggingface.co/datasets/PatronusAI/financebench|https://huggingface.co/datasets/PatronusAI/financebench|smart-link] 



This data set has a large collection of earning statements, 10-Ks, and 8-Ks.  It also has a set of questions and answers from that data set.



We need to extract the information from these documents, and then store it into our knowledge base.  



With the data organized and stored in the knowledge base, then we should be able to measure our performance of asking the same questions of DeepGPT and testing its response against the correct answers.  



Based on what is incorrect, we can refine both the extraction and RAG elements of this tool, and we can also refine the accuracy of extraction using both LLM and BROS.

As a DeepSee Engineer providing support for our self hosted customers, I need insights on the state of their environment.

We discussed writing a script or creating a job that a self hosted customer can run that would collect data on the state of the deployment. This can help us troubleshoot the environment.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Self Hosted customer’s have a way of providing DeepSee with an overview of the state of their deployment, containing information that can help 4-5 level support.
* Output of this script cannot contain private information about the customer’s deployment. When possible, try to send back flags or statuses about values, rather then the values themselves.

As a self hosted customer of DeepSee, I need help troubleshooting my deployment. In addition to having the option to get guidance from DeepSee, it would be helpful to have some troubleshooting guidance that I can review.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Create a troubleshooting space in our customer facing documentation with guidance on how to troubleshoot common issues, specifically issues that can be resolved by the customer.
* Include guidance on what to include if the customer believes the issue is on DeepSee’s side.

Whenever a customer experiences an issue with DeepSee, they will never assume the problem is on their side. Even when the problem is on their side, they will still perceive it as being our fault for letting it happen. This will result in continued requests from customers, and put us in situations where we either need to troubleshoot the customer’s issue on their environment, or take the opposite extreme of saying “works on my machine.”

This epic captures work we can do to mitigate the effect of customer support requests, making it easier for us to identify if the cause of the problem is on our side or on the customer’s side. This can include:

* Adding a troubleshooting guide to our Customer Documentation for Self Hosted customers.
* Creating a script that will collect meaningful (but not private) data that can help us direct customers to the correct logs.

Acceptance Criteria:

* TBD, we need a specific, measurable, finite success criteria for this story. The above notes are a good starting point, but how much work do we need to assume we are successful.

Currently all logs should be going to DataDog in addition to metrics. However, logs from workers spawned from our Python services are not working. This is because the otel connector is not getting injected into these spawned workers.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Logs for our Python services are viewable in DataDog, enabling easier and faster troubleshooting.

In order to meet an SLO of <1% errors, I need to be able to identify errors so I can fix them.

Currently we are using DataDog to collect our logs and metrics. We need to ensure that all meaningful data is consolidated in DataDog so we have a centralized place to troubleshoot our endeavors.

Acceptance Criteria:

* We identify the data we need to collect in a centralized monitoring solution (Currently DataDog).
* We organize troubleshooting data in a meaningful way. Preferably this is documented so that it’s easier to peruse and to maintain consistency as other services are added to our platform.
* All necessary data is being collected in our monitoring solution.
** Logs from all services
** All inter and intra API calls (latency, error rate, count, etc).

column43:
As a user on a self hosted deployment of DeepSee, I want to be able to support multiple projects. Each project will need to be able to categorize emails differently, which means that each project will need to have it’s own categorization model.

Acceptance Criteria:

* DeepRecon can manage a different Categorization Model per project. Each model should continue to have it’s own versions, and track which one is in production.
* DeepRecon is capable of running the Guided Learning process for multiple projects at the same time. It can also train multiple categorization models simultaneously if needed.

Note: The purpose of Modelchains is to track which version of a model (i.e. Inference and Association) is being used by which project. However, at some point it is likely that we will have different Inference and Association models for each project. In other words, if we can update modelchains so that it supports managing models per project (vs just model version per project), we will be that much closer to consolidating functionality, and if model chains prove not to work, then it will be easier to migrate Recon and Pilot projects to something else if they are both using the same entities underneath.

As a User of a self hosted deployment of DeepSee I want to be able to create my own projects in the UI do not need to ask an engineer to write a database script.

This requires API endpoints to support projects which satisfy the following requirements:

* I need to be able to create a Project by giving it a name and choosing a solution it implements.
* Using a wizard like process, the UI needs to know what data to collect based on the components of a solution (i.e. inboxes during project creation. Automations need to be added before polling. Categorization should be trained before polling).
* Projects should have the following statuses:
** INACTIVE: A project exists, but it is not processing documents because configuration has not been completed (in the future this may also include allowing a project to be “paused”).
** ACTIVE: The project has all required configurations and is actively accepting documents to process.
** ARCHIVED: The project has been deleted for all intents and purposes and only exists in the database for auditing purposes.
* Projects should be queryable based on their solutions and status. This will be needed for the Home Page.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The UI has all APIs needed to support their project creation screens.

There currently doesn’t appear to be a pipeline to build the DeepPilot client used by the automations service.

There is a step in the build that will build and publish the client library, but currently it has to be run manually, you can see the step [here|https://github.com/deepseeai/extractor-service/blob/main/.github/workflows/build.yaml#L138-L144]. The reason we did it that way is that we couldn’t find a good way to only build and publish if the current version hadn’t already been built and published. If it tries to publish the library when it’s already been published then the build will fail. We had the same problem for the automations client, but ended up with a better solution. What we do there is check to see if the last commit included changes to the client code, if it did, then we try to build and publish the client, and the build will continue even if the client library has already been published. So you can build it manually, or it will be built automatically when it’s merged. We should update the extractor-service to do the same thing. You can see where we’re doing it for automations here: [https://github.com/deepseeai/automations-api/blob/c8010ae70aca728644507d4d0725f283bc102598/.github/workflows/build.yaml#L103-L121|https://github.com/deepseeai/automations-api/blob/c8010ae70aca728644507d4d0725f283bc102598/.github/workflows/build.yaml#L103-L121]

column1: Modify helm charts to allow for scaling of 0 in DR cluster
column43: The DR K8s services don't need to be running unless there is a DR event. Adding a value to the helm charts to indicate that the services should be scaled to 0 would help reduce costs.

Currently we only allow of enabling or disabling all onboarding scripts in any given helm chart. It would be useful to allow more fine\-grained control of which onboarding scripts are enable/disabled e.g. for the DR cluster, the kafka onboarding script should run since the topics need to be created; however, the psql onboarding shouldn't since the DR psql cluster is read\-only and it won't be able to run.

column1: Create method for secret replication to DR cluster
column43: Tenant secrets should be replicated to the DR cluster on a scheduled basis so they can be accessed by the apps in the DR cluster in the event of a failover. This would include database secrets and any other secrets that would be the same between regions \(This does not include Cognito oauth secrets since the Cognito instances are independent of each other\)

We are currently using CNPG's replication functionality for our DR postgres cluster. In the event of a failover, the replica cluster is promoted to a standalone instance completely independent of the cluster it was replicated from. We need to come up with a process to get any data modifications made to the DR cluster back to the primary cluster before we fail back to the primary.

This will allow Sales and Product to begin presenting demos to potential DeepGPT customers.

This will also create an initial integration point for current applications and a place to bolt on future DeepGPT features.

The DeepGPT Steel Thread will include:

* A knowledge graph in as a temporary placeholder for the knowledge base. This will be used to reason over implicit data about an email, issue, actor, etc.

This service can receive a question, the credentials of the user (so we can eventually determine what the user can and cannot access), and any other context that may be relevant to the question (i.e. The question is “Are there any other issues associated with this email?” then we will also need to send in the email the user is looking at)
* A generative AI model that is used for reasoning and answer generation.

column43:
h2. 🧐 *Why do we do it (context):*

DeepSee’s AI SaaS platform operates with sensitive customer data from ingest to outcome. It is targeted at line of business (LOB) managers who are seeking to exploit the promise of AI to create efficiencies (speed) while reducing risk (errors) through use of process augmentation. 

Our target customer has multiple lines of business, which need to be fire-walled from each other, with visibility limited to defined individuals in that LOB. Further, even within a LOB, they can operate on a ‘task-assigned’ basis with strict separation of duties within a Template. Certain individuals or groups will have access to allowed ‘views’ in DeepRecon. Views are the UI interfaces for human-in-the-loop operations.

The target customer operates in highly regulated verticals and will require the ability to audit activity across all LOBs for compliance and configuration management.

h2. 🤔 *What we need to do (outcome):*

*Note 1:* What is described here is a security overlay within the DeepRecon App. Customers are still authenticated at the edge proxy (SAML or OIDC) using customer IdAM for identity-proofing and controlled access. Customer grants their users access to DeepSee, we control/limit access within DeepSee.

Hierarchically, a DeepSee customer is always organized as follows:

* Company - Only one per corporate entity
* Project- A company will configure one or more projects (effectively the LOB)
* Template- A project will contain one or more templates (effectively a configured process augmentation)

To allow a multi-LOB customer to manage their regulatory and compliance requirements independently, we design with the following concepts in mind:

* We consider that each LOB within a corporate entity is essentially a ‘sub-tenant’ of that organization, with each effectively having their own administrative domain and authorized user access.
** Creation and modification of users and groups are always logged and reported.
* The hyper-convergence components, enabled via integration with internal and external systems for inputs and outputs, will to be monitored and access to configuration changes must be limited to only designated individuals.
** Instantiation and modification of integration connectors/interfaces are logged and reported.
* Ideally the user access ‘permissions’ (e.g., CRUDA) are instantiated directly at the data-level
** Includes configurations, rules, terms, etc.
* This should apply to any repository and/or contents related to the customer data
** Includes DataLab, databases, cloud storage, integration connectors, etc.

!DeepRecon Access Control - Page 5.png|width=729,height=611!

*Note 2:*  This PR attempts to define a logical method to restrict access through the UI. It does not address a similar method to control access via API. We should consider this eventuality in the overall design and application of this requirement. Putting control directly on the data should simplify regulatory and compliance management for both the customer and DeepSee.

h3. 🛑 *When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

h3. “Task-based Access Control”

High-level concept of operations from system administration workflow.

h4. Three classes of Users

* SaaS Admin - Top-level Admin whom defines Projects and Project Admins, identity provider(s) and global (external) connectors
* Project Admin - Defines templates groups and permissions, environments and project-level connectors (in-network)
* Template User - Users performing tasks and accessing Template components with typically review views and permissions

h4. A group per View in DeepRecon

Each view is filtered based on permissions listed below. As such, each view is effectively a group. Users are assigned to one more groups. Each group can one more permissions.

h4. Classes of Users

# Processor
# Process Designer
# Process Manager
# Process Auditor
# Administrator

h4. Available permissions per access group

* C - Create
* R - Read
* U - Update (Edit)
* D - Delete
* A - Approve

h4. Defined Permissions

* Work Items
* Content Maps
* Process Models
* Validation Lists
* Terms Library
* Term Groups & Sub-Groups
* Project Templates (e.g., can create new)
* System Integrations (e.g., IdAM, connectors)

h4. Resulting Truth Table

!Screen Shot 2022-10-02 at 10.32.24 AM-20221002-143234.png|width=100%!

* Y/Yes = Permitted
* N/No = Not permitted
* N/A = Not option/configurable

h4. Initial onboarding configuration/process

!DeepRecon Access Control - Internal Process (Customer Provision).png|width=513,height=585!

h4. Customer Group and User configuration/process

!DeepRecon Access Control - Customer Process (Admin).png|width=513,height=630!



Note: Permissions granted for different user roles are per-project specific.

column1: BE - 5.2 Process Logic to set priority on email
column43:
Context: Broadridge wants to be able to assign priority on an email based on rules they write.  This will allow them to organize their emails and focus on the most critical emails first.  

Priority will have one of four values and will default as blank. 

# Critical
# High
# Medium
# Low



Rules will be set using the following inputs

# To
# From
# Subject

These rules will determine if the Priority  Field in Outlook should be set to one of the four values defined above

This field will also be appended to the meta data of the email for use by DeepView in visualizations.



Acceptance Criteria: 

* User can create rules to assign the priority field with one of the four values of Critical, High, Medium, and Low 
* Some emails  will have a second rule to move the email to another folder.
* An API Call is made with. the outcome of the rules to set the field in the outlook mailbox to the correct value
* A custom category with the same name is added to the email
** !image-20240109-184206.png|width=1578,height=250!

* For additional context of other fields that will be set in Outlook please reference this chart.
*

|DS-Priority|4 - Critical, High, Medium, or Low|Blank|Y|Y| |PR-1287|5.2|
