column1: BE - Infrastructure and Application Monitoring and Logging
column43:
To ensure effective operation, maintenance, and optimization of our infrastructure, we require a solution to aggregate system logs, application metrics, and traces. This is critical for supporting our customers and gaining insights into system costs and performance metrics.

We have chosen Datadog as the platform for aggregating and visualizing system metrics, and we will utilize OpenTelemetry (OTEL) to send metrics to Datadog. This Epic encompasses the tasks necessary to integrate applicable logs, metrics, traces, and other telemetry data into Datadog.

h3. +*Financial Impact:*+

* Improving operational efficiency through centralized monitoring and analysis of system performance, potentially reducing downtime and associated costs.
* Enhancing customer satisfaction by proactively addressing issues and optimizing system performance, potentially reducing churn and increasing revenue.
* Providing valuable insights into system costs and resource utilization, enabling better resource allocation and cost optimization strategies, potentially leading to significant cost savings over time.

h3. +*Definition of Done:*+

* OpenTelemetry (OTEL) is configured and successfully sending logs and traces for both development and production environments to Datadog.
* Applications are configured to send all logs to {{stdout}} for aggregation by OTEL to send to Datadog.
* Alerts are configured based on predefined thresholds to notify relevant stakeholders of any critical issues or anomalies detected by the system.

As a DeepRecon user I want a dashboard that displays the status of my inbox. As a user or a manager I can use this dashboard to identify the most critical counterparties and categories to work on.

The initial approach is going to implement the fastest path to completion as defined in the Short Term tab in the attached Lucidchart Diagram.

Acceptance Criteria:

* There exists a status page in the DeepRecon Dashboards that displays the state of the project’s inbox.

column1: BE - Create labeling service reviewing data and providing human validation
column43:
We need a service for labeling data that allows us to quickly measure the impact of a proposed model or feature. For example, python engineer A builds a script to identify table headers, or how does he/she know if the script is successful? With this labeling service, he or she will be able to pull a sample of the target data and load it into the labeling interface, where he or she (or someone else) can review these sample records and identify whether or not the header columns and rows were identified correctly. The results should be saved to S3.
There are two candidates currently for this service: SageMaker Labeling Jobs and LabelStudio. The former is part of SageMaker and likely requires minimal set-up. The latter is a third party service which is free (it has a paid mode as well) and will require a little more set-up, especially to deploy it as a service, which would likely need to be done via Elastic Container Service (ECS). Review the SageMaker option first, and if that doesn't work, look into LabelStudio as a solution. Try several example scenarios and log how well SageMaker accomplishes our objective of giving us an easy solution for validating data and saving it back to S3.

Demonstrate Generative AI functionality in our demo environment.

This will allow Sales and Product to begin presenting demos to potential DeepGPT customers.

This will also create an initial integration point for current applications and a place to bolt on future DeepGPT features.

The DeepGPT Steel Thread will include:

* A knowledge graph in as a temporary placeholder for the knowledge base. This will be used to reason over implicit data about an email, issue, actor, etc.
* A DeepGPT service that is accessible via an API. This service can receive a question, the credentials of the user (so we can eventually determine what the user can and cannot access), and any other context that may be relevant to the question (i.e. The question is “Are there any other issues associated with this email?” then we will also need to send in the email the user is looking at)
* A generative AI model that is used for reasoning and answer generation.

*Context:*  We need to ensure that heavy extraction is efficient and quick.  One of the concerns is that we won’t be able to process heavy extraction quick enough to meet customer demands.  

We need to look at each step in our heavy extraction process and understand the average time to complete.  Then focus on the steps that take the longest.

*Criteria:*

column1: BE - Provide DeepSee Artifacts to Self Hosted Customers
column43:
As a Self Hosted DeepSee Customer, I want to manage the deployment of the DeepSee platform into my own system. I want to be confident that the resources I deploy are secure, and I want to manage them myself.

The artifacts that I will need include:

* The docker images containing the services and jobs needed to run the DeepSee Platform.
** Docker images and code need to be able to pass Security and Vulnerability Scans.
* Helm Charts
* Terraform

Each of these should only be accessible to licensed users and should have any available security and vulnerability scanning.

column1: UI - Technical Enablement and Technical Debt Bucket for Process Automation Back End Team
column43:
This epic is a catch all bucket for Technical Debt and Technical Enablement stories for Process Automation Back End. The stories added to this bucket may be small stories, or may need to be broken out into their own epics. The purpose of this bucket is to ensure these stories are captured so that as Engineering is enabled to work on these stories they can be pulled from this bucket.

Technical Debt is a term used to describe the shortcuts made by engineering during the development process that slow down engineering's ability to maintain, troubleshoot, extend, or add features to a product, system, or process over time. It is named such because – like financial debt – it tends to compound over time, making it harder to improve the code base the longer the debt is “worked around” by the engineers.

If Technical Debt is like financial debt, then Technical Enablement is like an investment. Technical Enablement is a term used to describe work performed by engineering that will speed up their development process.

Technical Debt and Technical Enablement are generally categorized together as the value they provide to the customer is indirect. The outcome of Technical Debt and Technical Enablement is faster and higher quality delivery times to the customer.

column1: UI - Create labeling service reviewing data and providing human validation
column43:
We need a service for labeling data that allows us to quickly measure the impact of a proposed model or feature. For example, python engineer A builds a script to identify table headers, or how does he/she know if the script is successful? With this labeling service, he or she will be able to pull a sample of the target data and load it into the labeling interface, where he or she (or someone else) can review these sample records and identify whether or not the header columns and rows were identified correctly. The results should be saved to S3.
There are two candidates currently for this service: SageMaker Labeling Jobs and LabelStudio. The former is part of SageMaker and likely requires minimal set-up. The latter is a third party service which is free (it has a paid mode as well) and will require a little more set-up, especially to deploy it as a service, which would likely need to be done via Elastic Container Service (ECS). Review the SageMaker option first, and if that doesn't work, look into LabelStudio as a solution. Try several example scenarios and log how well SageMaker accomplishes our objective of giving us an easy solution for validating data and saving it back to S3.

column1: [API] Update the documentation site CI/CD pipeline to consume published APIs
column43:
The documentation site [repo|https://github.com/deepseeai/Customer-Docs] has a basic CI/CD workflow that currently has a hard-coded public API spec inside it. The purpose of this ticket is to remove the hardcoded API spec and replace it with a dynamic workflow that pulls in the latest published API specs from across our organization.

This ticket depends on [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-884|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-884|smart-link] which will determine how we determine the repository names that contain API specs (either via a manual list or some dynamic build-time approach). Using this list of repository names, the workflow should download the published API specs for each. At this time, we would only need the {{public.yml}} files from each package since this is our public facing documentation.

Once all of the {{public.yml}} files are downloaded, they should be placed in a place where the site build can detect them and include them in the UI.

h1. Acceptance Criteria

* The documentation site CI/CD workflow no longer uses hardcoded API files and instead requests published API files at build time.
* The resulting build should only expose public API endpoints which specifically means API endpoints that have the {{public}} tag applied to them.
* The documentation site CI/CD workflow adds a {{workflow_call}} trigger which allows it to be called by other workflows in our organization.
** This trigger will be used whenever an API spec change is pushed to the {{main}} branch of any repository that hosts an API spec.

column1: [API] Determine if there is an automated way to detect repositories with API specs
column43:
Due to the distributed nature of our API specs, it is important for the documentation site to know which repositories it needs to query when it is building the API documentation. The fallback plan is to manually maintain a simple list of strings corresponding to the repositories that contain an API spec which it will iterate over when it executes its build and deploy workflow.

The purpose of this spike is to spend a little time looking into the possibility of automatically determining which repositories have API specs at build time for the documentation site. If that were to be possible, we would not need to manually maintain a list of repository names which removes potential human error.

h1. Acceptance Criteria

* Determine if there is any way the documentation site could automatically determine which repositories have API specs in our organization.
** If a new repository is added with an {{api-specification}} directory, that repository name should be included the next time the documentation site is built
** If an existing repository with an {{api-specification}} directory is deleted, that repository name should NOT be in included the next time the documentation site is built.
* If a good way to accomplish this is discovered, create a story ticket to implement the solution.
* If a good way to accomplish this is NOT discovered, create a story ticket to implement the manual solution which is to manually store a list of repository names.

column1: [API] Centralize shared API testing code in one spot to avoid repetition
column43:
We have various API specs in different repositories throughout our organization, and in every case we have some repetition when it comes to the API testing code.

Every API spec has the following two files located in the {{api-specification}} directory:

* {{SpecificationStructureTest.java}}
* {{SpecificationTest.java}}

In each API spec, the contents of these two files are exactly the same - they dynamically run generic API validation tests. We need to find a way to centralize the contents of these two files and share them with each API spec in our organization. Centralizing these files will make it so any updates made to either of them will always impact every API spec.

h1. Acceptance Criteria

* The two files mentioned above are no longer copied in each API spec across our organization but instead are referenced from a single location and integrated into our testing framework such that all API specs automatically inherit them.

column1: Update how lookup tables are used in FEEL expressions
column43:
Currently we use the following syntax to access look tables in a FEEL expression:

{noformat}lookups.`and-table`[item.`a` = true and item.`b` = true].`out`[1]{noformat}

The problem with this is that FEEL executes this by looping through all of the rows in the lookup table and comparing the values to the row. This can take a long time for large lookup tables, and especially if the output from one lookup table is used as input for another, like this:

{noformat}lookups.`outer-table`[item.`a` = true and item.`b` = lookups.`inner-table`[item.`c` = `source-1`.`term-1` and item.`d` = `source-1`.`term-2`]]{noformat}

In this case the inner-table gets looped through for each row in the outer table, and whatever calculations happen for the inner-table get executed every time. So for example, if you had 25 rows in the inner table, and 40 rows in the outer table, then the inner table would get looped through 40 times, and the terms would be looked up 1000 times. This has caused some calculations to take hours to complete, which holds up work item processing and bogs the service down.

We need to update how lookup tables are accessed. One potential avenue would be to put the lookup tables into the feel context as a map instead of a list, then they would be accessed like this:

{noformat}lookups.`and-table`[true][true].`out`{noformat}

This would speed things up, but it wouldn’t be quite as flexible as what we’re currently doing. Whatever approach we decide on, it might be valuable to define a custom feel function that the UI would call instead of having them access the table directly. That way we could change the underlying implementation of the lookup tables without the UI having to change anything. It might look something like this:

{noformat}lookups(tableName, mapWithValuesToLookup){noformat}

However we decide to move forward, we need to ensure that we don’t break existing calculations. So lookup tables should continue to be available in their current form in the FEEL context. When all the checklists have been updated to using the new way of accessing the lookup tables, then we can look at removing the existing lookup table references.

Additional documentation:
[https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2064416800/Lookup+Tables+in+FEEL#Expression|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2064416800/Lookup+Tables+in+FEEL#Expression|smart-link] 

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Lookup tables don’t loop through every row every time they are used
* Nesting lookup tables doesn’t result in a multiplicative increase in processing time
* The old way of accessing lookup tables continues to be available until all checklists have been updated
* Bonus: Instead of accessing the lookup tables directly, the UI uses a custom {{lookups}} function of some kind so that we can change the underlying implementation without having to update the UI or any of the checklists.

column1: Make zip file processing more robust
column43:
There are several points of failure when we process zip files from the dealfeed. Even after the document is successfully provisioned in Pilot and uploaded to s3, it can fail when the ml pipeline calls the [executeInferencePipeline|https://verbose-adventure-l5gz5kq.pages.github.io/#/private/executeInferencePipeline] endpoint, it can fail during extraction, it can fail during pdf conversion. There’s no reporting or notification when one of these steps fail, and there’s no way to easily find out which step failed, and if the service is shut down during the process, for example because of a memory problem, it won’t attempt to pick back up where it left off like it does for other aspects of document processing. We need to add some safeguards to make it easier to know which steps failed and have the service attempt to recover from a failure, and we need to add some reporting so that we can be made aware when a step fails.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* If the extractor service terminates while processing a zip file, it will attempt to pick back up where it left off when it comes back up
* If a zip file is unable to be processed, then an error is logged in the database and the application logs
* A datadog alert is set up to let us know when a zip file fails to be processed

column1: Check modelchain version before extracting documents
column43:
Sometimes a document fails to be processed for some reason and we don’t discover it and try to reprocess it until a while later. When this happens it’s possible for the modelchain version that was active when the document was uploaded to be decommissioned. If we send a document to be extracted with a decommissioned modelchain version, then it will always fail because the endpoint won’t be available.

When a document is sent to extraction we need to check that the modelchain version we are sending with it is valid. We could do this a number of ways, we could check that the version is not one that was active and made inactive. Or we could add a {{tombstone}} or {{decommissioned}} column to the database to track that the model is no longer available. If the model is invalid we should respond, either by logging an error, or by updating the modelchain version to the currently published one.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* When sending a document for heavy extraction, unless a specific version is requested (like for a test case), we should use the currently published model
* Remove the code that sets the modelchain version when we initially create the execution
* We should keep a record of which versions of the modelchain were used in an attempt to extract the document and record whether the attempt was successful

column1: [BE] Convert Task Completion Report Script to Java
column43:
Currently in the extractor service we have a Python script that handles the creation of the {{task-completion-report.xlsx}} file part of the output data for a completed work item. We need to convert this Python script into a Java class so that we don’t have to support Python or maintain the script’s dependencies in the extractor service.

*Acceptance Criteria*:

* The Python script in {{scripts/json-to-xlsx/app.py}} is converted into a Java class.
* The extractor service no longer has Python or Python packages in its dependencies.

column1: Make the dealfeed lambda fail more gracefully
column43:
The JPM legacy dealfeed lambda calls Pilot to provision deals that come from the JPM sftp site. The problem is that if Pilot is having problems and the call fails, then the deal is essentially lost. By default, the lambda is retried twice before a failure is recorded. We should increase the number of retries, and possibly increase the time delay between subsequent retries. Additionally, it’s possible to send a notification to an SQS queue or SNS topic when all attempts have failed. It would be good to set this to happen so that we know when an error has occurred.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The number of times the JPM legacy dealfeed lambda retries a message is increased
* We are somehow alerted when a deal fails

column1: Better handling of very large documents
column43:
A 77 page document came through the JPM dealfeed and caused problems for the ML Pipeline. The document was so large that the model took a very long time processing it, which means it wasn’t available to process other documents and they timed out. The document itself eventually timed out as well. We need to update the pipeline so that large documents like this don’t cause problems for other documents. Ideally we would want to be able to process large documents like this, but the priority is ensuring that they won’t cause other documents to fail.

The document that caused the problems was {{993164d2-b060-478e-b4b8-0a1359dab736}}. When it was processed it caused ~35 other documents to fail.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Very large documents don’t block up the pipeline and cause other documents to fail
** We would prefer to be able to process them without holding up the pipeline, but if that isn’t possible we should terminate the pipeline before it gets to the model when we detect a very large document

Tests that fail intermittently are only slightly better than no tests at all.

At best, an engineer needs to rerun tests again, either locally or through automation, making the average time from issue completion to production take longer, and requiring more of the engineers attention during processes that should be fully automated.

On a bad day, engineers will trigger tests repeatedly, not realizing the test is not actually an intermittent issue and they’ve just wasted a bunch of time thinking it was.

Worst case, tests become so unreliable that they start being ignored and all the time put into creating, maintaining, and running them becomes a waste, because people will typically start over rather that fix a bunch of broken tests.

[docs.deepsee.ai|http://docs.deepsee.ai] needs to be behind auth of some sort as we don’t want it open to anyone on the internet.



Here are some ideas to implement this:

# When you navigate to [docs.deepsee.ai|http://docs.deepsee.ai] you are presented with a window that asks for your email, the user enters their email and our system sends a code to them, they use this code to login and get full access. Behind the scenes we need to have a way to ‘whitelist’ approved domains so that we don’t send a code to anyone with an email. I don’t have this list of domains right now but if it’s in the codebase I can update it later, for now just whitelist [deepsee.ai|http://deepsee.ai] for us (deepsee users) to be able to login and prove this solution.
# Classic username and password, so users create an account with an email for their username and they set their password. This approach would still require us to whitelist approved domains (see above).
# Auth through idp, this one is more longer term vision but the end goal would be so that users can send us an .xml and we use something like cognito to handle auth. This xml is typically called saml.idp.metadata.xml or idp.xml and it contains info to facilitate auth which cognito uses. So with this approach it would be ideal but more work but more along the lines of keeping this in mind as an option.

Documentation tools such as Confluence are great. However, in software development they have some drawbacks:

* The ease of making documents, spaces, etc, makes it easy to create a lot of information, which can be hard to tell which is relevant and which is noise.
* It can be difficult to know if a page or space is an active or abandoned proposal, or an adopted or encouraged practice.
* Because there are no review processes built into Confluence, it can lead to:
** People not updating the document because they are unsure if the information they have is accurate, and they don’t want to mess anything up.
** People will update confluence too freely, sometimes reducing the accuracy or value of a document with irrelevant information.

These concerns can be mitigated through version controlled documentation. This enables developers to safely create and suggest changes, and requires some level of review or approval from engineers before these changes are merged. This maintains the integrity of the documentation while simultaneously allowing it to be updatable and approvable.

Currently we are investigating using Starlight for this process.

Acceptance Criteria:

* We have a version controlled Starlight documentation portal served from a repository that engineers can submit documentation to.
* An initial outline of the organization of the documentation is defined, which may include global onboarding steps, team specific onboarding steps, and sections for different engineering concepts (i.e. service catalog, repository list, environment list, etc).

column1: Create Meaningful alerts for DeepRecon and DeepPilot for Accenture and JPM
column43:
As a DeepSee engineer, I want to know when an issue is happening before the customer reaches out to me. I also want to know when potential issues might be rising, potentially allowing me to resolve an issue before the customer ever sees it.

We need to build meaningful alerts for DeepRecon and DeepPilot. It’s important that when these alerts go off that one of the following happens:

# If the issue is critical, an engineer immediately begins work on it.
# If the issue is not critical, one of the following happens:
## The engineer creates a story to remove the alert if it is not relevant.
## The engineer creates a story that will resolve the issue before it becomes critical.
## The engineer adds one of the above relevant stories to the alert, indicating that it is a known issue, and helping to prioritize the resolution of the associated story based on occurance.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Create alerts for DeepRecon and DeepPilot in the JPM and Accenture environments that meet the above requirements.

As a DeepSee Engineer, I want to know when issues are happening in production before the customer tells me.

Currently [DeepPilot has a dashboard for JPM|https://us3.datadoghq.com/dashboard/4g2-ahu-ngj/extractor-service?fromUser=false&refresh_mode=sliding&view=spans&from_ts=1720377395972&to_ts=1720463795972&live=true] which gives us metrics and allows us to watch for anomalies in usage. These anomalies can then be tracked to identify metrics that should be alerted on.

Acceptance Criteria:

Rollbacks are a great way to quickly resolve customer issues by reverting code back to the last working state. It might not always be the correct answer, but it’s a really good tool to have.

We need to have a well documented strategy for our rollbacks that includes:

* Tactical:
** What currently can and cannot be rolled back.
** When should we and when should we not use rollbacks.
* Strategic:
** What stories do we need to improve our ability to rollback
*** Automatically track whether a commit can be rolled back?
*** Add rollback testing to our CI/CD pipeline so we can feel confident rolling back in production when we need to.
*** Tracking who can rollback, when, etc.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The desired outcome of this approach to have an outline of the recommended work and stages for enabling rollback in our CI/CD process.
* Write up next steps as stories and epics

One of the challenges with building software in the AI industry is having sufficient randomized data to meet our customer’s potential use cases. This is an even greater challenge when serving regulated industries, as the example data that would help us train is even harder to find.

While synthetic data is not the best for training models, it can be useful for testing. Synthetic data might be finely tailored to test a specific use case, or it might be mass produced to facilitate stress testing. Or it might be randomized to facilitate fuzzy testing. Regardless, generating synthetic data is not cost free.

This milestone tracks the various initiatives for generating synthetic test data to use for testing.

As a DeepSee customer who serves regulated industries, I can’t allow my customer’s data to leave my enclave. As such, I want to deploy the DeepSee Platform into my own cloud. Because I want my cloud/enclave/VPC to be as secure as possible, I want to restrict the number of requests that need to leave my VPC.

One source of unnecessary requests that are being made to outside of our tenant is the pyfunc images that support the Inference and Association Endpoints. Whenever these images start up they are building a whole python environment from scratch. Not only does this require requests for dependencies outside of the customer’s VPC, it also is the reason why it takes ~20 minutes for an endpoint to start up.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Image that is deployed as the SageMaker endpoint is fully built before being deployed to Sagemaker. This removes the need for the endpoints to call outside of the VPC when being built (better securing our customer’s environment) and should speed up deployment time as well.

The zip-extraction endpoint allows an archive to be extracted and the documents processed. When the documents are extracted they get added to the same execution as the original archive file. This means that if the endpoint is called multiple times, multiple copies of the documents will be extracted and added to the execution, which causes problems for work item processing and in other places. When we go to extract an archive, we should first verify that it hasn’t already been processed. If it has been processed, we should return a 409 with a message indicating that the archive has already been extracted.

Note, this check should be done in the {{ArchiveExtractionService.extractArchive}} service rather than at the endpoint. It’s possible for that method to be called by multiple routes, and we don’t want any of them to re-extract a previously extracted archives.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* If an archive document has already been processed, then trying to re-extract it should not succeed

column1: Limit rate at which documents are sent to heavy extraction
column43:
The changes we made for [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-684|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-684|smart-link] have made it so that it would be relatively easy to limit the number of documents sent to the heavy extraction pipeline.

The extractor service won’t have access to the extraction pipeline, so it won’t know how many documents are currently being processed, but it can still limit how many documents it sends during a specified period of time. For example, one or two per minute or something. This would help limit the load on the heavy extraction pipeline and reduce the number of failed extractions we see.

Additionally, it wouldn’t be too difficult to have the service automatically retry failed documents. We could queue a document for extraction when the service receives a notification that it failed, and it could also check for documents that were sent to processing, but haven’t been updated in a set amount of time.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The extractor service limits the rate at which it sends documents to the heavy extraction pipeline
* The number of documents sent during a specified period of time is configurable through environment variables

* The attachments should be added to the same execution as the original email
* Images embedded in the body of the email should also be uploaded as attachments
* We’ll have another story for triggering light extraction

column1: Provision EKS control plane in a different subnet than Node Groups
column43:
Currently the EKS control plane provisions its network interfaces in the same subnets that our node groups run in. This is not the recommended configuration and causes issues when trying to run failure scenarios e.g. the closest way to mimic an AZ going down is to run AWS Failure Injection Service which blocks all network traffic into and out of a subnet; however, with the control plain being in the same subnet as the nodes, the nodes are still reported as healthy and the cluster doesn't behave as it would if an AZ really went down.

To fix this, we can provision the control plane to use different subnets. Some things to keep in consideration:* The subnets only need to have 16 IPs \(The current subnets are much bigger than this\)
* The subnets can't be changed after you create the cluster
** You might be able to change them when you upgrade a cluster. This needs to be checked

*AC*

* Subnets are provisioned for the Control planes with a /28 netmask in AZ a,b,c
* Our Kubernetes clusters are set up to use these subnets for the control plane

column43: We want users to be able to configure the output of DeepPilot.  This would include selecting which fields are included in the file and the file type (CVS, Json, text)

The models have started taking a long time to start up, more than twice what they used to take. It used to take around 10 minutes to start a new endpoint instance, now it’s taking closer to 25 minutes. This means that environments where we go to zero instances the first documents will always time out before the model is able to come online, and the models are having trouble coming up in time to deal with increases in load. This is also causing problems when deploying new models, because the instances aren’t able to come up before the model deployment process decides that it has failed.

We only have data going back a couple of weeks, but it looks like the instances started taking longer to start up around May 1st.

column1: [spike] Referencing one checklist item within another checklist item
column43:
In process model, there are some checklist items whose extractions/factors preclude other checklist items. There are also some checklist items where only one or the other will pass, based on lack of information in some of the sources. We want a way to use the results of one checklist item in another checklist item in order to streamline the process model logic for these items.

Examples:

# Principal Protected:
## Checklist Item A: Is Principal Protected. Checklist Item B: Principal Protected Percent. 
## If A is true, then B needs to be reconciled. But if A is false (not principal protected), then B is not applicable (no principal protected % expected). In the checklist item logic for B, I want to be able to start from the results of checklist item A.
# Floating Details
## Checklist Item A: Has Floating Leg. Checklist Items B, C, D, etc: Floating leg details
## If A is false (no floating leg) then all of checklist items B through D are not applicable (no floating leg details). In the checklist item logic for these, I want to start from the results of checklist item A.
# Cusip/ISIN
## Checklist Item A: CUSIP. Checklist Item B: ISIN
## Most sources on the work item will only have CUSIP OR ISIN. If either one matches and the other is not found, we don’t need to reconcile the not found one - it can PASS based on the other one passing. I want a way to create that conditional relationship within the checklist items.

1 & 2 have a parent/child relationship, while 3 is slightly different. We have fewer use cases for 3 so while it should be considered, it doesn’t have to be solved in the first go.

AC: Document a proposal for how this can be accomplished, preferably using the existing FEEL engine.

We want to be able to extract a formula and corresponding values from an unstructured document and plug in the values to get the output of the formula so that we can automate the reconciliation between the formula on the unstructured document and the results on the system of record.

Similar to something like: [https://solvely.ai/?adjust_referrer=adjust_reftag%3DcjM96MdAOZF31&gad_source=1|https://solvely.ai/?adjust_referrer=adjust_reftag%3DcjM96MdAOZF31&gad_source=1|smart-link] 

See also: [https://deepseeai.slack.com/archives/C02C0LPUK1S/p1714682361452399|https://deepseeai.slack.com/archives/C02C0LPUK1S/p1714682361452399|smart-link]

column1: HSTS not enforced on api.dev.deepsee.ai (reported by Nessus)
column43: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS, as defined by RFC 6797. HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks, SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.

column43: Monitoring and observability stories result in solutions that provide insights into the behavior of systems and applications. By monitoring various metrics and observing system components, engineers can proactively identify performance issues, troubleshoot errors, and optimize resource utilization. This proactive approach enables teams to maintain high system reliability, improve user experience, and swiftly address potential issues before they escalate.

Operations management is the practice of providing the services and (preferably) services that enable engineers to efficiently and effectively manage their services in production. The solutions in this milestone should enable engineers to address production issues such as performance optimization, resource allocation, capacity planning, and disaster recovery. The epics in this Milestone will not only improve the above issues, but increase our engineers ability to do so quickly.

column1: Remove 30 second timeout on Dev Ingress

This obviously did not make for the most accurate test, and I suspect was more detrimental to the results rather than helpful.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Dev environment has the same timeout on ingress as our production environment so that we can more accurately test against it.

column1: Deploy Pod Autoscalers In Kubernetes For DeepView
column43:
*Description:*

To support our objectives around performance, reliability, and cost we can leverage [horizontal pod autoscalers (HPA)|https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/run-application/horizontal-pod-autoscale/] to ensure we have the optimum number of services running to meet customer demand while minimizing the cost footprint of our services.

*AC:*

* Deploy an HPA for all DeepPilot services to automatically scale workloads based on the resource utilization of CPU and Memory
* Set the scaling threshold at a level that makes sense 80% utilization may be a good targe

column1: Add Monitoring for Spot Instance Turnover
column43:
We need to monitor how often the EC2 spot instances are reclaimed.  This will help in determining if we would like to move forward with running production services on spot instances or if there is too great of a risk of downtime for a production environment.

To enable logging to monitor the spot instances, we should just need to add the [kubernetes-cluster-receiver|https://opentelemetry.io/docs/kubernetes/collector/components/#kubernetes-cluster-receiver] and the [kubernetes-object-receiver|https://opentelemetry.io/docs/kubernetes/collector/components/#kubernetes-objects-receiver] to OpenTelemetry.

column1: Ensure proper labeling of Application Pods In Our Kubernetes Environment
column43:
*Description:*

As a part of [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/CI-75|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/CI-75|smart-link] we added enforcement of terraform resource tagging based on the structure documented in [Confluence Here|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/IN/pages/2214920335/AWS+Cost+Tagging]. column1: Enforce Resource Limits on OPA Policies
column43:
*Description:*

To ensure applications are aware of costs and performance we want to make sure that we add proper [resource limits|https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/] to all workloads that are deployed into our K8s clusters.

We can enforce these resource limits using [OPA Gatekeeper|https://kubernetes.io/blog/2019/08/06/opa-gatekeeper-policy-and-governance-for-kubernetes/], which should already have been deployed into our clusters as a part of [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RE-35|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RE-35|smart-link] 

*AC:*

* Any workload that is deployed into a tenants namespace should be required to have at least a CPU and memory resource request and limit set
* If the workload does not have at least a CPU and memory resource request and limit set then we should reject the workload
* Update the existing manifests to include resource requests and limits

column1: Creating a Cloud Cost Model for Deeprecon
column43:
*Description:*

Accenture will need an adequately detailed cost model to ensure ongoing unit economics for Deeprecon. 

In order to do this we need to understand the correlation between volume and various cost driving metrics like:

* CPU
* Memory
* Disk
* Network

*AC:*

* Ensure we have proper metrics for CPU, memory, disk, and network being collected into Datadog
* Benchmark the Deeprecon service at various load levels so as to create a reasonably strong correlation between various technical metrics and load
* Collate the data into a form that can be analyzed
* Generate a cost projection based on analyzed data for various volumes of data.

Context: 

As a user of DeepRecon, I want to be able to assign different labels and move emails into different folders depending on rules that I write using blockly.   This will allow me to manage my email workflow, quickly find, and action tickets. 

*  I want to be able to use meta data (to/from/subject), categories, and extractions to create and execute these rules.  
* I want to be able to name the label field (DS-Action, DS-Priority (note all must start with DS-)).  
* I want to be able to assign emails to a folder. If the folder doesn’t exist, I want DS to create it.

As a user I want to be able to upload a .csv file in the UI that will replace the holiday calendar so that I can add and remove holidays in bulk.

As a user of DeepGPT I want to be able to ask DeepGPT about emails, issues, actors, or counterparties, and I want DeepGPT’s answers to be generated with context relative to the entity or resource I am asking about.

In order to accomplish this, DeepGPT will need access to a generative LLM for creating responses.

Unfortunately, there is not – or we have not yet found – an LLM that is compatible with our Cloud Agnostic vision. For the time being we are looking into a multi-cloud solution; Claude 3 on AWS, GPT4 on Azure, and TBD (but probably Gemini) for GCP.

In the short term we need Claude 3 in our dev environment. Please use this spike to determine how best to deploy Claude 3 without restricting a multi-cloud or eventual cloud agnostic solution in the future.

Acceptance Criter:

* Stories outlining how we will include Claude 3 in our infrastructure deployment.
* Additional stories to either capture the remaining remaining work for multi-cloud infrastructure or the spikes to research it.

column1: Make Claude 3 part of the DeepGPT deployment
column43:
As a user of DeepGPT I want to be able to ask DeepGPT about emails, issues, actors, or counterparties, and I want DeepGPT’s answers to be generated with context relative to the entity or resource I am asking about.

In order to accomplish this, DeepGPT will need access to a generative LLM for creating responses.

Acceptance Criteria:

* When DeepGPT is deployed it will also include access to a Claude 3 instance.

As a DeepSee customer I want to ask questions in natural language and have DeepGPT be able to answer them. This will require DeepGPT to be able to make inferences about my underlying data based on the questions I am asking.

In order to make inferences on the underlying data, DeepGPT needs a knowledge base, which is being designed by the ontology team. Until we have a knowledge base, however, we will be using a knowledge graph maintained in Neo4J.

As is the case with a relational database, we will need to maintain the schema for Neo4J. It is recommended that we do this with [Liquigraph|https://www.liquigraph.org/], which is intended to act like Liquibase for graph database schema management.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Enable schema management and migration of Neo4J in for DeepGPT.

column1: Store the index for reconciliation item details
column43:
We haven’t been storing the reconciliation item index for work item task details associated with reconciliations, because we were working under the assumption that there would only ever be one item per source, so it would be sufficient to record the source id to tell which detail went with which reconciliation item. However, JPM has reconciliation items that include multiple items from the same source, so we can’t tell which details go with which item. We need to start recording the index of the reconciliation item with the details so that we know how to group them.

We could expand this to do it for all work items. Manual items have parameters, validations have arguments, and reconciliations have reconciliation items. We could just store the index for all details and that would make it the same across all types, and possibly make it simpler. We don’t have to do this though, just something to keep in mind as a possibility.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The index of the reconciliation item is stored with the work item task details for reconciliation checklist items
* Reconciliation item details are returned with the correct reconciliation item.

As a DeepRecon engineer I need to access the Argo Workflows page (link?). Unfortunately this page takes a long time to load because it attempts to present all of the completed workflows.

We should create a job that will clear out completed workflows after an appropriate amount of time. Additionally, we should turn off any superfluous jobs, like the cron job that triggers data ingestion which is only used when creating initial training data.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The Argo Workflows page loads faster and will continue to load faster because it is no longer retaining completed workflows indefinitely.

column43: System hygiene is the practice of keeping our shared workspaces clean an uncluttered so that they are easy to maintain and troubleshoot. In most cases this work can be done manually, but as we bring on more customers, onboard more employees, and increase our feature set, some of this maintenance will need to be automated as it will be harder to keep up with manually.

By automating code integration, development, and deployment processes, CI/CD improves efficiency, quality assurance, agility in adapting to changing requirements, reduces time-to-market for new features and improvements while also improving the feedback loop with end-users or stakeholders. Additionally, it helps in risk mitigation by identifying potential issues early on in the development cycle. This milestone is for tracking the work that can be done to our CI/CD pipeline to increase our production capacity and the quality of our services.

As software engineers there a many processes that are repeated as part of the software development lifecycle. There is typically a time in any process in which the effort can easily be done manually. However, over time the cost of continuing to perform these processes can add up. Human error, change management, and training can make these processes consume more time than the best case scenario of them being completed. Even worse, tedium could lead to processes being skipped or performed mediocre. 

This Milestone encapsulates the various process that should be automated to improve the engineering team’s production capacity. These processes should improve the organization's throughput, reduce risk of error, and keep the team happy and productive.

Technical debt is a term used in software development to refer to the accumulated cost of additional rework caused by choosing an easy but limited solution now instead of using a better approach that would take longer to implement. This Milestone is used to track technical debt that is either directly affecting the production capacity of the team or it is accruing interest, we know it will be needed, and the longer we take the harder it will be to fix. It's important to distinguish between beneficial technical debt, which can be addressed to improve productivity, and false technical debt, which involves spending resources on optimizing processes or services that do not directly impact customer value or feature delivery.

column1: Store the version of used lookup tables

When a lookup table is used by a checklist item, we currently store the id of the lookup table that was used. We should also be storing the version of the lookup table that was used so that an auditor can know which version of the lookup table was used to produce a particular result. Alternatively, we could store the version id, which would allow us to lookup both the version number and the lookup table id.

column1: Create Processing Controller in Execution Manager
column43:
As a DeepSee User, I want to reduce the costs in effort and finances to have both the DeepRecon and DeepPilot products. That can be reduced by unifying the duplicate features in each product via a DeepSee Execution Manager.

Some executions will have more than one process to perform, as is the case with DeepRecon which will perform categorization and optionally Email Automations. For this purpose the Processing Engine needs to be able to track what processes need to be complete, and run them in parallel or in sequence as necessary.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Write a Processing Engine that will track what processes need to be performed for an execution, and ensure they are all ran in the proper order.
** Note in the future this will be managed via a configuration file, or perhaps a DB schema, meaning processes will be more dynamic. For the time being this management can be hardcoded specifically for DeepRecon and DeepPilot.
* Create a Callback that each process will call when complete so the Execution Manager / Processing Controller will know when all processing is complete.

column1: Enable Execution of Checklist Process via API
column43:
As a DeepSee User, I want to reduce the costs in effort and finances to have both the DeepRecon and DeepPilot products. That can be reduced by unifying the duplicate features in each product via a DeepSee Execution Manager.

Currently the Checklist Process is managed by the ChecklistProcessingService in DeepPilot and is triggered via a JMS queue. We can keep the JMS queue if it is helpful, but it needs to be behind an API that is called when the Checklist needs to be processed.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Checklist processing can be triggered via and API that contains the id of the execution to process checklists for.

As a DeepSee customer I want reduce costs in effort and in money when using DeepRecon and DeepPilot. I can have reduced costs in effort if DeepRecon and DeepPilot are more seamlessly integrated, and perform common functions such as extraction, feedback, training, processing, etc, with a similar interface, thus decreasing the cognitive load of the users I pay to use the application. Additionally I can reduce costs if I can reduce the resource footprint, storage, and processing functions of my executions. By reducing duplicate storage, process, and resources, DeepSee can deploy the product for less money and can pass the savings on to me.

In order to accomplish this, the DeepSee Engineers need to start unifying their common processes and features. This is going to be done via the Execution Manager Service, which will manage the extraction, processes, feedback, and testing of assets as they are uploaded to the DeepSee Platform.

Acceptance Criteria:

* After extraction, the Execution Manager can direct the predicted extractions to be used in the appropriate processes to support either DeepRecon, DeepPilot, or a whole new process.

Note that at this time this does not require a completely configurable Execution pipeline. Instead the processes for running DeepRecon and DeepPilot will be hardcoded into the Execution Manager based on solution and file type. Fully configurable templates will be created in a future phase of the execution manager.

As a DeepSee customer I want reduce costs in effort and in money when using DeepRecon and DeepPilot. I can have reduced costs in effort if DeepRecon and DeepPilot are more seamlessly integrated, and perform common functions such as extraction, feedback, training, processing, etc, with a similar interface, thus decreasing the cognitive load of the users I pay to use the application. Additionally I can reduce costs if I can reduce the resource footprint, storage, and processing functions of my executions. By reducing duplicate storage, process, and resources, DeepSee can deploy the product for less money and can pass the savings on to me.

In order to accomplish this, the DeepSee Engineers need to start unifying their common processes and features. This is going to be done via the Execution Manager Service, which will manage the extraction, processes, feedback, and testing of assets as they are uploaded to the DeepSee Platform.

Note that at this time this does not require a completely configurable Execution pipeline. column166: Unify Execution Management for Recon and Pilot

column43:
As a customer taking advantage of the Execution Manager, I want to ensure that the execution manager is independently scalable to my needs, and can be updated with my required features as frequently as possible without breaking my other products. In order to accomplish this the data that the Execution Manger manages needs to be encapsulated within the Execution Manager so that changes made to these data entities do not break DeepRecon or DeepPilot.

This will require the Execution Manager Service to expose the APIs required to access this data to Pilot and Recon, allowing data to be changed while still maintaining backwards compatibility.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The Execution Manager Service has it’s own API specification.
* APIs in DeepRecon or DeepPilot that are specific to the data owned by the Execution Manager are migrated to the Execution Manager Service.
* DeepRecon and DeepPilot are updated to call these APIs (even if the Execution Manager is not in it’s own service yet) to access this data. This will allow us to split this functionality more easily when it is it’s own service.

column1: Create And Migrate Execution Manager Database
column43:
As a customer taking advantage of the DeepSee Execution Manager service, I want the execution manager to be agile enough to be updated to meet my business needs. This will require the engineering team to be able to make quick updates to the service without breaking DeepRecon or DeepPilot.

As part of being able to make non-breaking changes, the Execution Manager needs to have complete control over it’s data base tables, with now other services reading or writing directly from it’s tables. This encapsulate data ownership within the service and give it the freedom it needs to change as needed without breaking other services.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Identify the tables that should be part of the Execution Manager and create a management strategy for managing those tables in it’s own schema.
* Once the data is populated, migrate the data from Pilot and Recon into the Execution Manager tables.
* No data should be lost in our production environments during this process.

As a customer taking advantage of the DeepSee Execution Manager Service, I want to get the latest, high quality updates from DeepSee so that I can always be using the latest features and have the ability to provide feedback on each iteration.

In order to do this, DeepSee needs to ensure that the changes to the DeepSee Execution Manager are being deployed via Continuous Deployment and adequately tested.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Create a new repository for the Execution Manager Service.
* Ensure the service is set up for Continuous Deployment and automated testing.
* Note that for the first phase of this service it will be calling the DeepPilot database. We will be separating the databases by service at a later time.

As a DeepSee Customer, I want a seamless experience between DeepRecon and DeepPilot. Each of these products have similar features, and I would like to work with them using a consistent interface, consistent principles, and consistent processes.

This will be managed by the DeepSee Execution Manager, which will manage the data concepts for our core execution pipelines, while calling modular processes for specific extraction, processing, testing, and training scenarios. The purpose of this Epic is to run the Execution Manager Service as it’s own service, making it independently scalable, easier to update, and more agile to maintain and improve.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Execution Management Service is it’s own deployable service that encapsulates all data it is in charge of maintaining, and exposes operations on that data via APIs.

DeepRecon and DeepPilot are currently two different products that have a number of common features between the two that each have their own implementation. This includes:

||*Feature*||*Pilot*||*Recon*||
|Provisioning|POST execution API|extract-and-categorize API|
|Extraction|Heavy, Structured|Light|
|Processing|Checklists|Categorization, Email Automations|
|Feedback|Work Items|Actionable Data|

Additionally, Recon will also need a testing mechanism similar to Pilot as well.

The outcome of this Milestone is to build an initial Execution Manager that can begin to unify the execution process for DeepRecon and DeepPilot such that the duplicated features above can be unified into a single execution pipeline.

This will provide the following benefits:

# Reduced code base means less maintenance, reduced change, and reduced risk of defects. This will result in increased engineering output.
# A unified execution pipeline will reduce the storage and processing needed to share data across DeepRecon and DeepPilot. 
# By standardizing the expected inputs and outputs of common actions, like extraction, processing, feedback and eventually training, we can create and bolt on additional modules to our execution manager with greater ease, further increasing our development capacity.

A living document which breaks down this process into more detail and provides diagrams can be found here: [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2193948686/Unifying+Recon+and+Pilot+via+a+Process+Modeler|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2193948686/Unifying+Recon+and+Pilot+via+a+Process+Modeler|smart-link]

*Description:*

This epic is about deploying necessary changes to ensure that all secrets are managed with Vault.

*Context:*

We have upgraded our capabilities with Vault to be able to enable more standardized secrets management across our environments including automatic rotation, dynamic injection, and short lived credentials.

*Business Objectives:*

By standardizing on overall secrets management we will enable more reliable, secure, and rapid deployment of new features, by minimizing manual support operations, simplifying application development & deployment, and no longer having long lived credential access to our data systems.

*Definition of Done:*

* All secret lifecycles are fully managed by Vault. 
* No more long lived application credentials for database access
* All secrets are injected using standard Kubernetes secrets as environment variables.

column1: Automate manual steps of DeepView deployment
column43:
There are currently some manual steps required to set up the connection between DeepView and DeepRecon. We should automate these to ensure that they get performed for new tenants, and to decrease the potential for human error.

Beyond enabling both services in the argocd manifests project, these additional steps need to be performed:
1. Enable deepview in the infra-platform project:
[https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/9c977c4fa4465f5ee7d21336aa110bf563301a09/aws/terraform/tenant/terraform.dev.tfvars#L18|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/9c977c4fa4465f5ee7d21336aa110bf563301a09/aws/terraform/tenant/terraform.dev.tfvars#L18] 
2. After deploying, look up the user id and user secret for the user created by this terraform:
[https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/9c977c4fa4465f5ee7d21336aa110bf563301a09/aws/terraform/tenant/modules/deepview/cognito.tf#L1|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/9c977c4fa4465f5ee7d21336aa110bf563301a09/aws/terraform/tenant/modules/deepview/cognito.tf#L1] 
3. Update the {{{tenant}/deepview/deeprecon}} secret with the user values and the authentication url
4. Update the {{ssoConfig.userPoolWebClientId}} value for deeprecon to include the user id of the new user:
[https://github.com/deepseeai/argocd-manifests/blob/bbc36fc9fff068aa281e6d483e06f615392576a2/argocd-applications/releases/development.yaml#L83|https://github.com/deepseeai/argocd-manifests/blob/bbc36fc9fff068aa281e6d483e06f615392576a2/argocd-applications/releases/development.yaml#L83] 
5. Restart the deeprecon service so that it picks up the new configurations
6. The {{reconauthconfig}} vault secret kubernetes resource for deepview will need to be deleted and re-created so that it picks up the new secret values
7. The DeepView service can then be restarted


Acceptance Criteria:

* The above process is performed automatically for new tenants

column1: Update API for Differentiate Labeling Sources in the Interface
column43:
As a DeepRecon user, I want to see the breakdown of labeled data by labeling source, separating user-labeled data from algorithm-labeled data So that I can understand the contribution of human labeling vs. algorithmic labeling to the overall data quality.

Current Behavior:

The system differentiates between labeled data and unsupervised data.

Desired Behavior:

The system should differentiate between labeled data based on the labeling source:

* Labeled by User: Data points that were labeled by a specific user (user_profile_id is not null).
* Labeled by Algorithm: Data points that were labeled by an algorithm (user_profile_id is null):
** Because it's the same: The algorithm identified the data point as matching an existing labeled data point.
** Because it's similar: The algorithm identified the data point as similar to existing labeled data points.

Benefits:

* This breakdown will provide better insights into the labeling effort.
* It will help assess the accuracy of algorithmic labeling compared to human labeling.
* It will allow for targeted improvements in either user labeling workflows or algorithmic labeling models.

Acceptance Criteria: 

* Hard code this graph in demo with the data below:
** 6648 emails (69%) Labeled by User
** 3024 emails (31%) Labeled by Algorithm

As a DeepSee user I want to be able to select a resource in the UI and ask DeepGPT questions about it. This will require that there is an API associated with DeepGPT that will accept my question, my user credentials, and the context within I am asking my question.

This should be exposed as an API.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Work with Rost to identify how context should be received.
* A synchronous API is defined that enables a client to ask a question, accepts the user’s credentials so that it can restrict access to certain information, and receive any context about the question being asked.
* The API will respond with an answer to the question.
** Also will have natural language queries
*** may need SQL queries as well
** Business logic
**  Should have confidence

As a DeepGPT user I want to be able to ask DeepGPT questions in natural language and receive  meaningful answers in return.

In order to enable this, we are going to need a service that can be deployed into our environments. This service should have it’s own repository and CD pipeline actions.

This work is to create the initial service for DeepGPT and should include:

Acceptance Criteria:

* Create the initial API specification for DeepGPT. It can be an oversimplified version of the initial endpoint that accepts a question and responds with an answer or “Hello World” so that we know it’s accessible.
* The repository creates a new service that builds a docker container and can be deployed into dev via CD pipeline.
* Includes setting up the CD action in GitHub actions along with the needed charts for the service.

Demonstrate Generative AI functionality in our demo environment.

This will allow Sales and Product to begin presenting demos to potential DeepGPT customers.

This will also create an initial integration point for current applications and a place to bolt on future DeepGPT features.

The DeepGPT Steel Thread will include:

* A knowledge graph in as a temporary placeholder for the knowledge base. This will be used to reason over implicit data about an email, issue, actor, etc.
* A DeepGPT service that is accessible via an API. This service can receive a question, the credentials of the user (so we can eventually determine what the user can and cannot access), and any other context that may be relevant to the question (i.e. The question is “Are there any other issues associated with this email?” then we will also need to send in the email the user is looking at)
* A generative AI model that is used for reasoning and answer generation.

Rather than have two backend teams, we want to have a single backend team working on a single platform that can support multiple products.

While there are epics and stories that will focus on unifying the features currently supported by these two teams, this epic is about the technical enablement tasks that will allow engineers to quickly create, maintain, and update various backend code bases, allowing us to split and regroup with greater ease as there will be consistency with the technologies used.

This initiative aims to standardize the core set of tools, libraries, and practices for common coding tasks enabling engineers to seamlessly transition and contribute across different codebases. the goal of this epic is to foster a unified technological environment that promotes efficiency, collaboration, and ease of navigation across our projects, without stifling the individual creativity and problem-solving approaches of our engineerings.
At the moment, the process glossary list is static and hardcoded. We should update this screen to show the email list being updated every time we clicked on a different label.

column1: Use ING data to identify expected load on DeepRecon
column43:
As a customer of DeepSee, I want to feel confident that DeepRecon can handle the messages I receive during my peak business hours.

As “premature optimization is the root of all evil” in software engineering, we want to ensure that we are able to adequately cover the expected scale from Accenture, but not guess at such an outrageous amount of emails at one time that we are building for a scale we will never achieve.

The purpose of this story is to use the emails we have from ING as a baseline for how many we anticipate receiving from Accenture and use this for our load tests.

Acceptance Critera:

* I am able to identify peak sending times for emails using ING email data.

Currently in the DeepView service we are leveraging JPQL to build out the queries used in the repository to fetch the data for API calls. The problem with this is that JPQL does not support more advanced query operations such as limiting the results returned from the database. 

This is a necessary feature for DeepView and currently we achieve limiting the results by filtering the results in-memory in our application. It’s obvious that this will not scale well when we begin working with larger datasets since we are retrieving ALL the rows from the database. 

We are going to need to re-write the repository to instead build out native SQL queries instead of using JPQL to build out the queries.

*Acceptance Criteria*

* The {{AggregateOperationRepository}} class needs to be re-written to build out native SQL queries instead of JPQL.
* All of the current functionality of the query API needs to be supported with the native SQL queries. This needs to include:
** Grouping by fields
** Grouping with numgrain
** Filtering on field values
** Ordering the results
** Limiting results 
** Joining multiple entities

Please retrain the JPM term-extraction and entity-association models.

column1: Enable the RDS Proxy for the Extractor Service
column43:
*Description:*

Recently the incident [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-611|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-611|smart-link] saw a large increase in the number of connections to our database. The underlying cause of this connection bloat was remedied in the Java code, but it revealed that we are susceptible to problems if we get a sudden growth in total connections on the database.

To mitigate this issue we can leverage the [RDS proxy|https://aws.amazon.com/rds/proxy/] that has already [been provisioned |https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/rds/home?region=us-east-1#proxy:id=jpm-prod-production-33c72d94-539d-4268-b120-7b3f57626cab]in [terraform here|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/9c8dfe40604edd93cc04e836e21c88324b54628a/aws/terraform/tenant/modules/deeprecon/rds.tf#L101].

column1: Support Many to Many Relationship for Normalized Headers & Headers
column43:
Currently there is a one to many relationship enforced in DeepRecon for normalized headers to headers. We need to update this logic to consider cases where there can be a header associated with multiple normalized headers. In this case we will want to implement an algorithm to determine the appropriate normalized header by running the value through the validations for each normalized header and analyzing the output. For example, TD could mean “Trade Details” or “Trade Date”. In this case if we are able to validate that the string is a date we would determine the normalized header to be Trade Date. Otherwise, it would be determined as Trade Details.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* When integrated with the DeepPilot term library we are able to handle cases where an extracted header has multiple candidates for a normalized header.

column1: Filter on Actionable Data Page By Exposure
column43:
As a Recon User, I need the ability to sort actionable data by "exposure", which means the sum of the notional value of trades within the thread.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The actionable data page should include a sorting option for "exposure".
* Sorting by "exposure" should arrange inquiries with the highest total notional value appearing at the top.
* "Exposure" should be displayed in a clear and easy-to-understand format, such as "total notional value".

Benefits for users:

* Improved inquiry qualification: By prioritizing inquiries with higher exposure, I can focus on opportunities with the greatest potential financial return.
* Enhanced decision-making: Sorting by exposure allows me to quickly assess the potential value of each inquiry and allocate resources effectively.
* Increased efficiency: Identifying high-value inquiries upfront helps me streamline the process and close inquiries faster.

Financial Impact:

* Implementing this feature is required for a broadridge deal.

Additional Notes:

* Consider allowing users to sort in both ascending and descending order by "exposure".

column1: Filter on Actionable Data Page By Age
column43:
As a Recon User, I need the ability to sort actionable data by "inquiry age", which means the number of days between the initial inquiry date and the current date. This functionality will help prioritize inquiries and improve conversion rates by allowing us to focus on the most recent leads.

Benefits:

* Improved efficiency: Sorting by age allows us to focus our efforts on the most relevant inquiries, saving time and resources.
* Enhanced customer experience: Addressing inquiries promptly demonstrates responsiveness and improves customer satisfaction.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The actionable data page should include a sorting option for "inquiry age".
* Sorting by "inquiry age" should arrange inquiries with the most recent inquiries appearing at the top.
* The "inquiry age" should be displayed in a clear and easy-to-understand format, such as "number of days ago".

Financial Impact:

* Implementing this feature is required for a Broadridge deal

Additional Notes:

* Consider allowing users to sort in both ascending and descending order by "inquiry age".

column1: Deploy Registered Application Credentials into Vault
column43:
As a DeepRecon customer I want DeepRecon to automate various processes in my email inbox, such as prioritizing emails, categorizing them, and moving them into different folders.

In order to enable this as a DeepRecon Engineer, I need to have the client id and secret key. These credentials need to be stored securely in Vault when the Registered Application is created in Entra.

Acceptance Criteria:

* When a registered application is created in Microsoft Entra via GitHub actions, the credentials are securely stored in Vault.
* DeepRecon is able to access the credentials for the registered application in use for the tenant it is deployed in.

column1: Deploy Registered Application Via GitHub Actions
column43:
As a IT professional working for a customer of DeepSee, I need to grant access to DeepSee to be able to read emails in my Microsoft Tenant.

In order to do this, DeepSee needs to register applications in Microsoft Entra that the customer can invite. All of these applications should be built the same and should have the same permissions, etc. Hence we are creating a terraform module to deploy these registered apps.

The outcome of this story is to create a GitHub action that will deploy the our Registered Application into Microsoft Entra on our tenant that we want to expose to our customer.

Acceptance Criteria:

* I can deploy a Registered Application into our tenant in Microsoft Entra via a GitHub action.

As a DeepSee Back End Engineer I need to know how my service is being used, where the load is the highest, and where things are breaking. This allows me to:

# Provide meaningful business metrics on customer usage.
# Know when a feature of the application is broken at the same time, or even before, the customer does.
# Know where to focus my efforts to scale a product.
# Automate the monitoring of my application.

For application engineers, this type of monitoring is best done at the API level. It is helpful to know when an API is called, how long it takes, how often it breaks, etc. This level of tracking also allows us to report to a customer what percentage of requests were successful in the case where we measuring SLAs.

[OPA has a built in OpenTelemetry collector|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/monitoring/] to use for monitoring, but this only appears to provide JVM specific metrics (i.e. threads, heap size, cpu usage) and does not provide the needed per endpoint metrics.

However, OPA does print out metrics for individual responses which include duration, and status for a request to a given path.


{noformat}{"client_addr":"127.0.0.6:56493","level":"info","msg":"Received request.","req_id":13,"req_method":"GET","req_path":"/health","time":"2024-03-05T20:20:15Z"}
{"client_addr":"127.0.0.6:56493","level":"info","msg":"Sent response.","req_id":13,"req_method":"GET","req_path":"/health","resp_bytes":3,"resp_duration":1.063315,"resp_status":200,"time":"2024-03-05T20:20:15Z"}{noformat}

Using this output, we should be able to create a [custom collector|https://opentelemetry.io/docs/collector/] that allows us to track the per API metrics needed for monitoring per API endpoint.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Create (or find) an otel collector that collects and aggregates data by endpoint and reports on the following by API endpoint
** Error rate (4xx + 5xx) / (total requests)
** average duration
** count

For the time being, this API will be very specific to the Status Dashboard Page. Instead of the UI making a query per widget, we will just return all data needed for the page. We should, however, keep the structure of the data for the individual widgets as similar to the query structure we are using in DeepView.

*Description:*

One of the items that Datadog has alerted on regarding misconfigurations as outlined in [this dashboard|https://us3.datadoghq.com/security/compliance?query=evaluation%3Afail&aggregation=rules&column=status&order=asc&sort=ruleSeverity%2CfailedResources-desc&timestamp=1709331721573&live=true] is that we should enable [key rotation|https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/rotate-keys.html] for our KMS Encryption Keys. We should enable key rotation for all of our keys so that Datadog no longer reports on it.

column1: [BE] Update date normalization to parse times from dates
column43:
Currently the Date Normalization process discards any time information because tracking the time adds a lot of complexity and we didn’t need the added precision.

DeepRecon started using the Pilot Date Normalization recently and would like time to be parsed and normalized as well. We currently allow a {{contextDate}} to be provided when normalizing dates, this should be used for determining the time zone of the parsed date.

We may want to introduce a new date-time data type, comparing date-times is significantly more complicated than comparing regular dates. So it would simplify things to add a new data type rather than rewriting all of Pilot’s checklist logic to account for dates with times.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Time values are parsed from dates
* The context date is used to determine the timezone of the parsed date
* The parsed date/time is stored

column1: [Spike] Research Options For Serving Models In Kubernetes
column43:
*Description:*

In order to save money and reduce our overall dependence on AWS services we want to explore options for serving models out of Kubernetes without leveraging AWS Sagemaker. 

Some options that support this are:

* [KServe|https://kserve.github.io/website/0.11/]
* [RayServe|https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/master/LICENSE] ([recommended by Rostyslav|https://deepseeai.slack.com/archives/C023MDQNHBQ/p1709146249373609?thread_ts=1709145527.824389&cid=C023MDQNHBQ])
* [TorchServe|https://pytorch.org/serve/] (licensing is a bit wonky)
* Roll our own serving capability

*AC:*

* Review the documentation for the available open source options to include comparisons based on complexity, ease of use, operational expense, and licensing
* After reviewing documentation deploy a POC using one of our existing inference models that are being served out of Sagemaker
* Document a draft recommendation in the [decision points|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/IN/pages/1857191949/Decision+Points] section of confluence
* Understanding how this will integrate with a CI/CD pipeline
* Draft stories under [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BE-28|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/BE-28|smart-link]to implement a production ready option based on our decision and analysis
* Solicit feedback from the rest of the team, particularly the ML team members.
