column1: Add Wait to the CICD pipeline for deployment approval
column43:
The prod approval step of the CICD pipeline can get in a state where it runs before Github is aware of the new deployment. This causes the approval step to fail and the pipeline to be stuck in the prod approval stage until someone manually approves the deployment. To fix this we should add some sort of a wait to the approval step to make sure there’s a deployment to approve before it runs or we could look at taking the prod approval step out and remove the branch protection rule since if it gets to that stage it should always be pushed to prod via the CICD pipeline

Acceptance Criteria:

* It’s determined whether we should remove the prod approval stage or fix it to wait
* Depending on the outcome of the previous AC, the approval step is either removed or fixed to wait until there is a deployment ready to approve

column1: [BE] Update the documentUrl field in work item details to use original rendition
column43:
The work item details endpoint returns a list of documents for a given work item ID, and each document in this list contains a {{documentUrl}} that is a presigned URL to download the file. This URL currently points to the pre-processed version of the file, meaning that it will download the file that our system created after ingesting the source file uploaded by the user. Specifically, if a source file is something like {{.docx}}, this URL will point to a {{.pdf}} since this is how we internally process {{.docx}} files.

What we want is to update that documentUrl field to point to the original uploaded file and not the pre-processed one. If a source has a {{.docx}} extension, the file pointed to by the {{documentUrl}} should likewise be a {{.docx}} file.

*Acceptance Criteria*

* Documents in the Work Item Details response should have a {{documentUrl}} that always points to the original uploaded file and not a file that has already been processed by our system.

column1: SPIKE: Figure out how to point the UI to an individual value in a cell with multiple values
column43:
When displaying an email that has gone through light extraction the UI needs to be able to point to the value within the email. For most values this is as simple as just providing the row and column, but if a cell has multiple values in it, then we’ll have to specify which value within the cell it should point to. This spike is to figure out how we want to do that. One thing to consider: However we do this, it needs to work for both values extracted from tables embedded in emails and values extracted from csv or xls files that are attached to emails. Part of the extraction context value we store may need to be something indicating which embedded table/attachment the value came from.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* A document exists outlining how we will point the UI to individual values in a cell with multiple values
* The approach works for both embedded tables and attachments
* The UI team has approved the proposed approach
* Stories for the work have been created
column250:
27/Feb/24 10:38 AM;624dc011fd5e450070484b01;If somebody picks this up before I do, I just want to note that we can solve this problem by structuring our predictions for light extraction the same way we do for heavy extraction.

Some cliff notes:

* The row of a table is a subgroup. We might have to have a generic entity.
* The columns of a table are the different terms in that group.
* If a cell has multiple values in it, then it is of form Array.

The only problem I can see is if the multiple values in a cell are not all of the same type or term (i.e. maybe a column has initial date and valuation date). In this case we can discuss, but we should keep the structure of our predictions as similar as they currently exist as we can.

column1: Replace all the user names with DeepSee on Terms
column43:
Context:  When setting up Pilot in a new customer, we don’t want users to be able to see the user names who added terms from other companies.  

Content: Replace all user names on the terms page with “DeepSee” prior to launching Pilot at a new customer.  Once the customer starts adding terms, it is fine for them to see who add terms, even if they are from other companies. 

Acceptance Criteria:

There are no specific user names list on this page when Pilot is used for the first time at a new customer.  



!image-20240208-225305.png|width=784,height=517!

*As a DeepSee User,* I want all attachments and documents to process in the fastest way possible.  This should be in 30s or less and optimally under 5 seconds.  

*So that,* the user experience is not negative and they get near-immediate results from DeepSee whether they are processing email attachments or executing templates in DeepPilot.

----

*Extra Details:*

*Topic: decrease the time to process a document (pdf, word, excel, etc.) The pipeline for processing documents includes two mandatory steps: generating images from documents to be then processed with OCR and obtaining the text with the relative coordinates in the document. Given that the hypothesis is that these two steps contribute significantly to the time required to process a document (documents with multiple pages are processed one page at a time, leading to diƯerent images to process through the OCR) and that this hypothesis should be verified (if it has not already been done from the team), a possible solution to simplify the process and speed it up is to parse the document with specific parsers (a Word parser for a Word document, a PDF parser for PDF document, etc.) and use the APIs of each parser to obtain the text and its coordinates. If obtaining the coordinates through the parser (for example, a CSV file) is impossible, a good proxy could be to define a font type and font size and calculate the coordinates based on the content. With this approach, the ML model for data extraction would directly use the text with the coordinates (calculated algorithmically or using specific APIs for the document type) without going through a transformation and conversion process.*

What is left, it's a system that recognizes if a picture is a print screen or a logo. I have a version, but I need to improve it a little, especially increasing the datset for the training

*Description:*

Within deeprecon we have several workflows that are triggered, and the pods hang out even after the workflow is completed. This creates a couple of problems: 

#  It pollutes the output of the running pods, making it difficult to see what is actually running
# Adds added latency on the Kubernetes API
# May consume resources that have un-intended or unknown side effects

We want to make sure these get cleaned up after each execution, which we should be able to accomplish using the [ttl strategy|https://argo-workflows.readthedocs.io/en/latest/fields/#ttlstrategy]

*AC:*

* After each successful or failed run the workflow pods are cleaned up according to some time to live configuration. The configuration can be any sane value for successful or failed pods, probably no more than 48 hours for failed runs.

column1: Validate All Vault Secret Configs To Include a Valid Refresh Period
column43:
*Description:*

We recently had an issue with vault whereby we encountered something called [lease explosion|https://developer.hashicorp.com/vault/docs/concepts/lease-explosions] whereby the vault-config operator was requesting new credential leases several times every second. This was caused by a misconfiguration of the VaultSecret resource, because we didn’t have the {{refreshPeriod}} set, it defaulted to zero, which led to the lease explosion.

To prevent something like this from happening again, we would like to ensure that we have some policy enforcement on our pods in production to prevent deployment of VaultSecrets that may violate our policies. We should be able to achieve this using [OPA with Kubernetes|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/].

*AC:*

* If a VaultSecret is launched without a valid refreshPeriod and it is for the app-config mount (doesn’t apply to the database credentials) it should be rejected by OPA
* OPA policy should be added to our policy repository in a folder called {{infra/kubernetes}}
* Policy should be automatically deployed into the cluster when possible

 refreshPeriod: 24h0m0s

column265: 5.6 Automation Rules and Appropriate API Calls

column43:
As a DeepSee user I want DeepSee to integrate with my third party applications in order to create knowledge driven automation.

In order to decouple the integrations from the events that trigger them, we will create a Webhook interface between the DeepSee products (DeepRecon and DeepPilot) and DIG. This will allow DIG to integrate with different third party applications in different ways for different customers.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Identify the events that need to trigger webhook cals.
* Identify signatures of webhook subscriptions, removal, publish, etc.
* Don’t make it perfect. It’s unlikely that we will create a solution at this point that will meet all our future needs, just focus on getting the initial approach out there.
* Write up additional stories based on findings and design.

In addition to showing that DIG can handle synchronous requests to the categorize and extract API, onboarding Broadridge to DIG will also let us demonstrate how egress integrations will be handled by dig.

Onboarding Accenture to DIG will demonstrate that DIG can handle synchronous requests to the categorize and extract API. It might also be a good introduction to Accenture on Webhooks, which I believe once they get enough load in Orchestra that they will be interested in investigating to clear up their active thread count.

Migrating JPM to DIG will demonstrate that DIG can handle SFTP connections that connect to DeepPilot’s provision document API.

It will also create a flow that can listen for events from DeepSee for future JPM integrations.

After DIG is created in [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PR-1310|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PR-1310|smart-link], we will need to migrate all customers to DIG.

This work might feel out of place at first (why fix something that is working?) but by migrating all our customers to DIG we will create the initial patterns for integrating customers into the DeepSee Platform and integrating with third party services. This will reduce the cognitive load of onboarding a customer by providing a clear pattern for integrations that ingress and egress.

As a DeepSee customer I want to be able to integrate DeepSee with various third party applications so that I can create a knowledge driven automations from DeepSee with the other services in my enclave.

In order to accomplish this, I DeepSee to build these integrations in DIG.

DeepSee will send events into DIG for various flows from a customer. In order for DIG to understand these events, we will need to update the DeepSee Connector to be able to listen for and trigger on these events.

As a DeepSee user, I want to be able to integrate my third party applications with DeepSee so that I can create knowledge driven automations.

In order to make these integrations flexible and agnostic of the application we are integrating with, we will need to create the integrations in Anypoint based on generic events from DeepSee. This will allow us to create an automation based on a generic event.

This epic includes the work to design and implement these webhooks. These webhooks need to meet the following requirements:

* Events can be triggered by DeepRecon or DeepPilot (suggesting that this may need to be a separate service.
* Our webhooks should guarantee at least once delivery. They should also include an id so that DIG can handle them idempotently if the actions triggered by the events are not idempotent.
* Webhook calls to the client need to be secure. The first step is identifying what this means when calling Anypoint.

As a DeepSee user I want to be able to integrate DeepSee with Outlook so that I can automate email functionality such as categorization, prioritization, and flagging.

This should be done via a Registered Application in Microsoft Entra, formerly Microsoft AD.

The management of this registered app should be done via terraform. Since the rebranding from Azure AD to Entra is a recent change, I believe this would currently still be done via the [Azure AD provider|https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/azuread/latest/docs].

Questions:

Before we can start this, we need to be sure we know where we want the managed app to reside. Should it be in our default tenant where we keep our emails, or should it be in it’s own tenant. I suspect it would be more secure it it’s own tenant.

Acceptance Criteria:

* A registered application is created for our Mulesoft connections.
* The client id and secret key are secured in Vault.

As a DeepSee user, I want to be able to integrate DeepSee with third party services.

Since we are using Mulesoft, this requires a managed deployment of Anypoint studio as part of our infrastructure. This can be managed as code via terraform using the [Terraform Anypoint Provider|https://registry.terraform.io/providers/mulesoft-anypoint/anypoint/latest/docs].

Acceptance Criteria:

* Our Anypoint instance is being managed via terraform, just like any other of our cloud resources.
column166: Manage Anypoint Studio Deployment from as code

column43:
As a DeepSee user I want to be able to integrate DeepSee with other applications that are part of my enclave so that I can create knowledge driven automations.

This requires DIG, backed by Mulesoft as an IPaaS to be set up as part of our platform.

As DeepSee user, I want to be able to connect DeepSee to various third parties, enabling DeepSee to integrate with these parties and provide automation outside of just the DeepSee ecosystem. 

The component of the DeepSee Platform that will enable this integration is the DIG, or Data Integration Gateway. We have chosen Mulesoft to be the IPaaS solution to obtain these integrations. This will save me time and effort in maintaining connections with multiple APIs. With DIG, we can have seamless connectivity to different third-party systems, allowing us to deliver enhanced services efficiently.

Composition of Work

# Build initial DIG implementation
## Anypoint studio management as code
## Application management as code for registered app.
## Define and implement webhooks
## Credential Management for Webhooks
## Build and deploy Webhook Connector in Anypoint
# Create Flows
## Create flows per customer. These can be written up as needed.

As a DeepView user I want to be able to query DeepView’s query API and quickly receive the results of my query. I want to feel confident that the queries I am writing do not have an impact on the performance of my queries.

When querying an entity that has hundreds of thousands of records, the query should be limited in what it can return. For example, when querying messages, we should restrict the query to only send a year’s worth of data. If there is no restriction on the date we should limit the default results to only be the last half a year.

Acceptance Criteria:

* We should not allow more than a year’s worth of sent emails to be returned at a time.
* When emails are queries without a limit on the sent date, we should automatically limit to the last half a year.

column1: Index all data columns in DeepView
column43:
As a DeepView user I want to be able to query DeepView’s query API and quickly receive the results of my query.

A year’s worth of records in DeepView is over 4M records in the database, and thus we should be looking for any performance increase we can, especially if it is an easy one.

Any column in the DeepView database that is counted, grouped, or filtered on should be indexed so that a full table scan does not need to be performed to aggregate the data.

Acceptance criteria:

* Ensure that all fields in the database that are used for filtering or aggregating are indexed.

column43:
As a non-technical user of DeepView, I might build queries that are too large to display meaningfully in a chart. I want DeepView to just truncate the response instead.

For example, when making the following query:

{noformat}messages/count?groups=sender.emailAddress,receiver.emailAddress&filters=sentTimestamp:since:1y{noformat}

During testing this has returned up to 21MB, which is way to large of a response to display in a graph meaningfully. 

Instead, if a response size is larger than 1MB DeepView should truncate the response.

Examples:

An array of values A1-AZ such that the response is larger than 1MB would be truncated like so:

{noformat}type: array
label: count
value:
  - type: datum
    label: A1
    value: 16
  - type: datum
    label: A2
    value: 23
    ...
  - type: datum
    label: AX
    value: 24
  - type: datum
    label: Other
    value: 1232 # the sum of the count for AY - AZ{noformat}

For a matrix, datum values should be added to array values one at a time in grouped order until the response reaches 1MB in size, then the remainder should be summarized based on what has already been added. In worst case scenario this might result in a response up to 2MB in size.

As an example, assume we have values A1 - AZ and values B1 - BZ where the A values are the outer (array) group. The summarized matrix would look something like the following

{noformat}type: matrix
label: count
value:
  - type: array
    label: A1
    value:
      - type: datum
        label: B1
        value: 1
      ...
      - type: datum
        label: BX
        value: 24
      - type: datum
        label: other #remaining values for A1:BY-BZ
        value: 51
  - type: array
    label: A2
    value:
      - type: datum
        label: B1
        value: 1
      ...
      - type: datum
        label: BX
        value: 24
      - type: datum
        label: other #remaining values for A2:BY-BZ
        value: 51
  ...
  - type: array
    label AX
    value: 
      - type: datum
        label: B1
        value: 1
      ...
      - type: datum
        label: other # remaining values for AX: BY-BZ
        value: 56
  - type: array
    label: other # remaining values for AY - AZ
    value:
      - type: datum
        label: B1 # sum of AY: B1 - AZ: B1
        value: 123
      ...
      - type: datum
        label: BX # sum of AY: BX - AZ: BX
        value: 323
      - type: datum
        label: other
        value: 652 # sum of (AY: BY - BZ) - (AZ: BY - BZ){noformat}

Acceptance Criteria:

* Large Responses from DeepView are summarized to be no larger than 2MB worst case scenario

column1: [BE] Add $value to the DeepView orders parameter
column43:
Currently, when you’re retrieving an aggregate value for a data model you can order the results by the aggregate value by specifying the {{order}} parameter. So if you want to count all the Messages and order the groups by the count, you say {{order=desc}}. If you want to order by the names of the groups you specify {{orders=<group_name>}} We want to simplify things for the UI by allowing them to use the orders parameter for both types of ordering. If the user wants to order by the count or sum or whatever, they would specify {{orders=$value}}.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The user can order by the aggregate result value by specifying {{orders=$value}}
* The [documentation|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2163867649/Predefined+Dashboard+Breakdown#Orders] has been updated

column43:
*Description:*

We want to unify our workflows and workloads related to machine learning operations so that we can:

* Reduce costs associated with hosting machine learning workloads on  AWS' Sagemaker 
* Minimize process overhead associated with administering training and deploying machine learning models
* Enable more rapid iteration on models

*What needs to be done?*

* Create a unified model training pipeline using cloud native solutions like Argo Workflows, Kubeflow, and MLFlow 
* Serve our models using a Kubernetes native solution instead of Sagemaker

*Definition of Done:*

We are no longer using sagemaker for our training pipelines or to serve our ML models

Note that this story is the ability to connect to a customer tenant and add metadata. The metadata that needs to be added is based on each automation rule, which will be implemented in another story.

column250:
22/Apr/24 10:19 AM;621fa613a124500068874d6e;Knative Serving works by having a proxy service (activator) hold onto a request while the Knative autoscaler spins up a new pod to service the request if needed. This activator is used for the entire cluster. Because the requests for services that are running as a Knative service come from the activator pod instead of the actual origin of the request, our auth policies block knative from working. You can write an auth policy to allow traffic from the knative activator, but since the activator handles traffic for the cluster to knative services it ends up being more permissive than what is acceptable. The problem can be summed in the following points:

* Requests to Knative services go through the cluster-wide Activator service
* Auth policies need to allow traffic from the Activator service
* Allowing traffic from the Activator service is too permissive (Any service that has access to send requests to the Activator service has access to call any Knative service in the cluster)

Possible solutions:

* Use X-Forwarded-Client-Cert header to restrict access
** You need to add a custom envoy configuration to add the entire requester chain to the header since by default istio only has the last hop's client cert in that header e.g. the activator’s cert instead of the cert of the originator of the request
** Istio auth policies only allow you to do a prefix, suffix, or exact match on the header. Since the cert of the originator is in the middle of the header, there’s not a good way to write an auth policy to look for this.
*** We could use OPA to fix this issue
* Use auth policies that target the activator to restrict access
** If we create auth policies for traffic to the activator, we could use the request principal and the host header to possibly restrict access e.g. if request principal starts with `cluster.local/ns/dev/*` then only allow requests to the activator service that have a host header that has a suffix of {{*.dev}}
** This requires tenant configuration to not all be in the same namespace since the activator will be in another namespace
*** It means that the argocd tenant project will need to be allowed to provision resources outside of the namespace that they’re created in
column251: 22/Apr/24 10:30 AM;621fa613a124500068874d6e;Any service that is calling another service from within the cluster will need to have the URL for the destination be updated to <service name>.<namespace> instead of just <service name>. This is because Knative needs to have a more qualified domain name. I’m assuming this is because the Activator needs it to know the service it needs to send it to since it’s proxying traffic to all knative services in the entire cluster

column1: Identify if communications are internal or external
column43:
*Why do we do it (context):* 

DeepRecon's goal is to make our customers' work more efficient.

Differentiating and displaying if a communication is internal or external is powerful in transforming our customer business because internal communications can be revisited and reduced by agreeing on different internal procedures. It is a change that only requires internal coordination.



*What we need to do (outcome):*

We need to identify by communication ID if:

*  all email addresses linked to that communication are internal ---> flag as internal communication
* if at least one email address in the communication is external ---> flag as external communication



*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

When the backend identify for each communication if it is external or internal 

When we can use the information above to display counts of # of internal communication and # of external communication on DeepView.



*What is out of scope:*

Changes on DeepView 

Changes to the data being fed to DeepView

We currently have [this helm chart|https://github.com/deepseeai/argocd-manifests/tree/main/tenants] that is used to configure tenants for HA environments. Currently we attempt to enable precise configuration using [the extraValues|https://github.com/deepseeai/argocd-manifests/blob/9e8d036ea3fab0425dba4151b0519c0565e7d33d/tenants/templates/apps.yaml#L54] parameter which enables additional configuration on each of the apps. Currently this does not allow for precise configuration of individual customCharts like for example the {{predictionAPI}} because the extraValues get applied to all services in the sub-chart [as shown here|https://github.com/deepseeai/argocd-manifests/blob/9e8d036ea3fab0425dba4151b0519c0565e7d33d/deeprecon-ha/templates/apps.yaml#L115] we should find a way to enable more precise configuration of each of the individual services.

*AC:*

* All configuration values should be configurable even for dependent charts in the HA setup

*Description:*

Achieving a robust Annualized Recurring Revenue model means finding the optimal pricing strategy that results in rapid adoption of our product without compromising long term unit economics.

When it comes to the costs of goods sold for a customer the number one drivers are always going to be infrastructure. Infrastructure costs consist of two categories:

* Operational Expense
* Overhead

Operational expense is the cost necessary to process the data through our system for a given customer, this is basically how much CPU we need to process data.

Overhead is any resource that is not being used directly for processing documents and is considered process waste.

*What needs to be done?*

* Automate the scaling of database systems to automatically scale as data is consumed
* Leverage data compression strategies along with the use of “cold“ storage for infrequently used data
* Deploy Serverless options for services using technologies like [K-Native|https://knative.dev/docs/] to ensure we are only using resources as requests are processed

*Definition of Done:*

* Our resource usage density is >=80%

*Context:*

Supporting sales initiatives is one of our primary concerns to achieve our goals around annual recurring revenue. Ensuring that we can rapidly respond to requests for POC’s and new environments for customers will be critical for this.  Having a systematic and automated way to provision new environments is one of the most critical things that we can do to achieve these goals.

Currently it takes 3-4 days to have a fully functional tenant environment provisioned and this is because there are several undocumented manual steps and other gotchas that have to be remedied as the come up.

*AC:* 

* Anyone with access to the infrastructure environments should be able to follow specific documented steps and have a fully provisioned tenant environment with DeepRecon, DeepPilot, and DeepView within 4 hours or less. 
* The terraform is modularized to support running parts and pieces of the infrastructure

*Context:* 
As we have built out our environments in parallel we have duplicated some of our resources and control planes to support JPM while building out infrastructure for new and prospective customers. In order to save on cloud costs and streamline operational support we should unify control planes and deployment modes.


*AC:* 

* All deployments across all our K8s cluster are done out of the centralized [argocd.internal.deepsee.ai|http://argocd.internal.deepsee.ai/].
* We only have one production environment in each of the logical trade zones US and EU.
* There is only one 'non-prod' cluster where all the non-prod tenants Dev and Stage are deployed
* The non-prod cluster is also HA within the US tradezone
* Stage is deployed HA as a warm standby
* Dev is deployed as a single cluster

column1: Infrastructure and Application Monitoring and Logging
column43:
To ensure effective operation, maintenance, and optimization of our infrastructure, we require a solution to aggregate system logs, application metrics, and traces. This is critical for supporting our customers and gaining insights into system costs and performance metrics.

We have chosen Datadog as the platform for aggregating and visualizing system metrics, and we will utilize OpenTelemetry (OTEL) to send metrics to Datadog. This Epic encompasses the tasks necessary to integrate applicable logs, metrics, traces, and other telemetry data into Datadog.

h3. +*Financial Impact:*+

* Improving operational efficiency through centralized monitoring and analysis of system performance, potentially reducing downtime and associated costs.
* Enhancing customer satisfaction by proactively addressing issues and optimizing system performance, potentially reducing churn and increasing revenue.
* Providing valuable insights into system costs and resource utilization, enabling better resource allocation and cost optimization strategies, potentially leading to significant cost savings over time.

h3. +*Definition of Done:*+

* OpenTelemetry (OTEL) is configured and successfully sending logs and traces for both development and production environments to Datadog.
* Applications are configured to send all logs to {{stdout}} for aggregation by OTEL to send to Datadog.
* Alerts are configured based on predefined thresholds to notify relevant stakeholders of any critical issues or anomalies detected by the system.

As a DeepRecon user I want to be able to create automations that will update the priority, folders, flags, etc of a user’s email. In order to do this I need to connect to the Microsoft Graph API via a registered application using a service account.

Using a service account means that we will need to manage the tokens for connecting to Microsoft Graph. Microsoft Graph uses OAuth 2.0 and will grant us both an access token and a refresh token. This will require a user to login manually at least once. In order to avoid them from having to log in manually again in the future, we should keep the refresh token alive.

Acceptance Criteria:

* A mechanism is added to DeepRecon to allow for a service account user to be logged in.
* DeepRecon is able to keep the token active in a secure manner.
** A service account password should be reset periodically. Will this require a manual login each time? Or is it possible to just provide an endpoint for logging in service account users?
* Determine how to differentiate a service account user vs. a normal user.

As a DeepRecon user I want to be able to collect statistics based on the counterparties that I am interacting with. However, counterparties might be defined in multiple ways. For example an email from {{@jpm.com}} and an email from {{@jpmorgan.com}} come from two different domains but are considered the same counterparty.

As DeepView is intended to be fast, we do not want to calculate the counterparty assignment when querying DeepView. Instead the correct counterparty assignment should happen in DeepRecon at time of processing.

Acceptance Criteria:

* emails from multiple domains can be assigned to a single counterparty in DeepRecon.
* This data is propagated to DeepView where it can be queried.

column1: Call FEEL endpoint to evaluate Blockly blocks
column43:
As a DeepRecon user I want to be able to create automations that will trigger actions against my emails in my Outlook Server. The logic for triggering these actions{color:#ff5630} {color}{color:#ff5630}-may be defined using Blockly blocks and- {color}should take advantage of the existing FEEL engine.

Once [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-470|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-470|smart-link] is done, Recon will have a new endpoint that can be called to execute a FEEL expression that will automatically populate Lookups and provide any inferred terms that were extracted in DeepExtraction.

Acceptance Criteria:

* DeepRecon calls the new feel endpoint provided in [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-470|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-470|smart-link] to evaluate FEEL expressions.
* DeepRecon builds a context containing any data needed for the FEEL expression evaluation that is not yet part of the current context builder.
* DeepRecon’s context references any Lookup Tables used in any of the expressions so the feel endpoint can pre-populate the context.

Technical Notes:

* [Sequence Diagram|https://literate-umbrella-d17fac58.pages.github.io/docs/diagrams/Architecture/automations.html] showing what parts of the FEEL context are populated by Recon and Pilot.
* [Document|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~624dc011fd5e450070484b01/pages/2197880833/Using+Blockly+and+Feel+Engine+for+Label+Assignment+Logic] containing initial thoughts on enabling logic for automations. The first paragraph contains lots of helpful links that provide more context.

It will likely be better to provide the users token and only return the Categories they have access to rather than a robot token that has access to all categories.

column1: Add Light Extraction Terms and Labels to Dynamic Blockly Components
column43:
As a DeepRecon user I want to be able to make changes to an email based on the Terms that are parsed from the email (using light extraction) or the Label on the email (based on categorization).

In order to allow the user to use Terms and Labels in their calculations, we will need to provide DeepRecon Terms and Labels in our Dynamic Blockly Editor. This means the UI will need to create new stencils that allow these values to be used in calculations.

Acceptance Criteria:

* DeepRecon terms can be used in the Automations Blockly Editor.
** DeepRecon and DeepPilot each have their own glossary containing their own term definitions, which sometimes overlap. For example the Trade Date term may be extracted through light extraction and through heavy extraction, and they might even return different values. When building calculations the user will need to be able to specify which value they want to use. For this reason, we might want to have two different types of Term Blocks.
** Although DeepRecon and DeepPilot currently have their own glossaries, we do intend to have them use a single glossary (with luck before the end of the first half of 2024). With this in mind we should try to keep the feature set between the two term types as similar as possible (See the [Term Standardization page in this diagram|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/87a9c3a7-f41e-4ae7-9850-75d6870bf021/edit?invitationId=inv_057a6d6b-26e9-4da2-8950-22c0e4dd3d72&page=x_eTO1KoFHTX#] to see the high level features of each one and how we intend to combine them). The point being, although these are two different types of terms, we should keep them as easy to bring together as possible in the future.
* DeepRecon Labels can be used in the Automations Blockly Editor.
** Note that Labels are neither DeepRecon nor DeepPilot terms. However, they may at some point be considered a type of predicted value that can receive feedback.

column43:
Context: Broadridge wants to be able to quickly sort emails that the teams needs to do something with versus those that do not require any action.  

There are some emails that are just informational but don’t need action. Those emails they. want to flag with no action.  

This allows the users to know what they still need to be able to do and focus their efforts.

Rules will be set using the following inputs

# To
# From
# Subject

These rules will determine if the Action/No Action Field in Outlook should be set to Y or N

This field will also be appended to the meta data of the email for use by DeepView in visualizations.

* Acceptance Criteria
** User is able to write rules to identify emails that need their action / no action field set to either “Y” or “N”
** Some emails with a value of “N” will have this flag set, and there will be a second rule paired with it  to move the email to another folder to keep it as a record, but that the team will not take any action with it.
** An API Call is made with. the outcome of the rules to set the field in the outlook mailbox to the correct value of “Y” or “N”
** The outcome of the rule is displayed on Outlook custom field below to show action/no action per email
* !image-20240109-182731.png|width=1554,height=227!

* For additional context of other fields that will be set in Outlook please reference this chart.
* 

|Field to update in Outlook from DeepRecon|Value|Default|Created in Outlook by our Customers|Rule Based (To/From/Subject)|Extraction / Model Based|JIRA|Milestone|
|DS-Action/No Action|2 - Yes or No|Blank|Y|Y| |PR-1288|5.1|
|DS-Priority|4 - Critical, High, Medium, or Low|Blank|Y|Y| |PR-1287|5.2|
|DS-Sentiment|1 - Escalated|Blank|Y|Y|Phase 2 - Not 1H 2024|PR-1284|5.4|
|DS-Category|TBD - One for each category we define|Blank|Y|Y| |PR-1285|5.5|
|DS-Target Counterparty|TBD - One for each supported Counterparty|Blank|Y| |Y|PR-1292|5.65|

column1: Enable Full Stack Local Development Of All Resources
column43:
*Description:*

*Why we need it?*

In order to more rapidly iterate on functionality within our system and further constrain cloud costs, we can enable delivery teams to develop the system locally including all infrastructure components.

This makes it easier to detect problems early in the development cycle. It ensures that system changes are done in a wholistic way. Furthermore, by enabling local development we minimize the need for non-production resources further constraining or cost structures in the cloud.

*What is it?*

There are 3 main components that currently prevent full stack local development:

# ML Pre-processing pipeline
# ML Inference Pipeline
# Sagemaker model endpoints

We can move each of these into a cloud native Kubernetes solution. For the pipelines we should be able to use our already deployed [Argo Workflows instances|https://argoproj.github.io/workflows/] and for the Sagemaker model endpoints we can just hose those models in the Kube cluster similarly to how the DeepRecon team is already doing.

Once we have moved these 3 items into a cloud native solution we will be able to leverage Tilt to enable the full stack development on developer workstations.  

*Definition of Done:*

* All development of new capabilities can be done from a developer workstation including integration with infrastructure components and other applications
* Dev Should only be used for automated testing

column1: DIG: Update Customer Email Attributes Endpoint for DeepRecon
column43:
h3. As a DeepRecon Engineer integrating with our Customer’s email Outlook instance

I want an API endpoint that allows for the updating of attributes of each email individually,

*So that* I can efficiently integrate with Outlook systems to programmatically modify key attributes of emails specifically changing their folder locations, categorizing them for better organization, and flagging them for priority attention.

h3. AC:

# *Successful Email Update:*
#* *Given* a valid request with an {{emailId}}, {{sourceFolderDestination}}, and optional {{Category}} and {{Flag}},
#* *When* the request is sent to the {{/updateEmail}} endpoint,
#* *Then* the API should successfully update the specified email in Outlook with the provided details.
# *Handling Invalid Email ID:*
#* *Given* an invalid or non-existent {{emailId}},
#* *When* the request is sent,
#* *Then* the API should return a 404 Not Found error.
# *Error Handling for Bad Requests:*
#* *Given* a request with missing required fields ({{emailId}}, {{sourceFolderDestination}}) or malformed data,
#* *When* the request is sent,
#* *Then* the API should return a 400 Bad Request error.
# *Confirmation of Update:*
#* *Given* a successful update,
#* *When* the request has been processed,

As a DeepRecon customer I need to be able to build dashboards that allow me define different views of my email processes. I need to be able to create dashboards for my individual projects or – as a organizational leader – across multiple projects. I should be able to control who has visibility into each dashboard I create.

* I am able to build my own dashboards, define the widgets in those dashboards, and define the data that is displayed in those widgets.
* I can build dashboards that display data across projects. Restrictions are in place to ensure that only the right people can see that data.

DeepRecon users need to be able to see the results of their process emails so they can see trends or problems in their processes via standard dashboards. This view will be limited to one project.

DeepView is a service that provides the APIs and data models for displaying analytics data. DeepView will be able to provide the data for 6 screens.

** Overview

* Data in DeepView is aggregated from DeepRecon

column1: 1.3 The light extraction results need to appear accurate
column43:
*Why do we do it (context):*

DeepRecon offers categorization, data extraction, and analytics.

Data extraction process is divided into light extraction (algorithmic) and heavy extraction (machine learning BROS model)

The light extraction dictionary is not transparent to SMEs, and whenever we need to change/add to it DeepSee engineering team needs to be involved.

The light extraction doesn’t have a UI where SMEs can define what needs to be extracted.



*What we need to do (outcome):*

* We need to make {color:#4c9aff}*light extraction scalable by creating a UI that allows SMEs to maintain/update the original column header to normalize the header dictionary*{color} used by light extraction.
* The light extraction dictionary needs to be created, and it is applicable per project.
* 

*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

* *User can upload (structured) document for light extraction*
* *Terms found with existing mappings/labels pre-extracted*
* *User can add a mapping/label*

# _User can select term_
# _User can select value in the document_
# _DeepSee identifies a label_
# _User can check to see if label is correct_

 _-If correct, user saves document/publishes the mapping_

 _-If not correct, user can select correct label in right hand “configure” panel_

 5. _The same label is applied to extract all rows/subgroups_

 6. _The same label used to extract future documents_

*Configuration Screen*

# _User can select values that should be extracted, identify with possible labels_

     _a. Key on the left with a colon (ie “RIC”)_

     _b. Table Header (is “Trade Date”)_

*Scenario 1*

# _User can select term trade date_
# _DeepSee labels using column header_
# _Annotation is applied to all rows_

*Scenario 2*

# _User selects term SEDOL_
# _User selects string in first row_
# _First label found is “SEDOL” so label is selected_
# _Annotation is applied to all rows_
# _User can overuse and select “trade details” label_
# _Annotation is updated to include full cell with the header for all rows_

*What is out of scope:*

-Concatenating Multiple Labels

-Rerouting a table

-Csv, excel, and tables in the body can not be rerouted to heavy extraction

-an email that has free text plus a table in the body requires heavy and light extraction

column1: 3. Human in the loop and retraining
Bug: fix parsing key-values from cells when there is no whitespace after ':'
column43:
*Why do we do it (context):*

ACCENTURE_EML parser extracts new columns from cells with key-values.
The current implementation assumes that keys are separated from values with “: “ (colon + whitespace).
Some test emails with tables contains key-values separated by “:” (colon without a white space), e.g.:

!image-20231121-140634.png|width=1854,height=545!

* see the values in the red rectangle: {{SWIFT Del Ref:AP00368912184Q1 SWIFT Rec Ref:AP00962912184Q3 Agent BIC Code: 543454}}

In such cases, the “:” will be treated as part of the key or value:

* {{key_1:value_1 key_2: value_2}} will be parsed as (key, value) pairs: {{("key_1:value_1 key_2", "value_2")}}
* {{key_1: value_1 key_2:value_2}} will be parsed as (key, value) pairs: {{("key_1", "value_1 key_2:value_2")}}



*What we need to do (expected outcome):*

Use “:” (comma without space) to parse key-value pairs.

* {{key_1:value_1 key_2: value_2}} should be parsed as: {{("key_1", "value_1"), ("key_2", "value_2")}}
* {{key_1: value_1 key_2:value_2}} should be parsed as: {{("key_1", "value_1"), ("key_2", "value_2")}}



*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

We are parsing all key-values correctly in the Accenture emails generated in dev env (such as included above).



*What is out of scope:*

-



----

*Implementation Notes*

* see the comment [below|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-2070?focusedCommentId=35327]
column250:
22/Nov/23 2:16 AM;712020:ce0a682b-cdd4-4b0c-bb56-14881add2514;At this moment we are parsing key-values from the cell’s normalized text. So, instead of using original html text like: {noformat}

key: value

key: value

...{noformat} or {noformat}
  • key: value
  • key: value
    • ...
{noformat} we are parsing following string: {noformat}key: value key: value{noformat} To solve this bug, I see 2 options: *Option 1 (faster)* * we will be parsing from the cell’s normalized data * keys or values cannot contain “:” character (so “composed:key: composed:value” will be parsed as 2 (key, value) pairs: (“composed”, “key”), (“composed”, “value”) *Option2 (longer)* * we will pass the original structured text along Cell structure ** … remembering not to store this structured text in the json format ({{extracted_table.content}} column) * we can correctly parse the key-value in most cases, but still, there will be some problems to parse following data: ** {{

foo:bar:baz

}} - should be parsed as {{("foo", "bar:baz")}} or {{("foo:bar", "baz")}} ?
column251: 22/Nov/23 2:16 AM;712020:ce0a682b-cdd4-4b0c-bb56-14881add2514;[~accountid:62f58acfe50f2f2a39579be7] - can we assume, that “keys” and “values” don’t contain any “:” (colon) characters?
column252:
28/Nov/23 6:09 AM;63d955a3010d356379708136;In order to be sure we can process Accenture data reliably, we have to enforce few rules on 'in cell key value pairs' formatting:

# no colon in the key
# no line break in key
# line break is separator between key value pairs

By line break we mean any character/sign that results in text starting in new line (we need to support html and non html new line line breaks).

Given those rules are followed, to extract keys and their respective values we would follow the steps (in this order):

# split by carriage return (each split would be key value pair)
# iterate over key value pairs and split each by first colon (this way we are sure that left part of split is key and the rest [doesnt matter if it includes colon or not] is value)

[~accountid:62f58acfe50f2f2a39579be7]  - BE devs and I discussed this approach with [~accountid:61b79c274014290070fa34d4] and to be able to implement it, we need to ask Accenture, to follow the rules provided above.

column1: Bug: 409 when changing dataset name while data set is in training
column43:
*Why do we do it (context):*

Changing dataset name fails when dataset is in training.
Steps to reproduce bug:

* Prerequisite: dataset with status “Training in progress”
** e.g. we can create new dataset, change dataset’s emails, or finish labelling
* When changing the dataset name (Training > select database > Edit > change name & confirm changes)
* Outcome:
** the response from the BE was: {{409 - Active workflow for subject 'ML_LABEL_OR_CHALLENGE__MAIN' and data '{"dataset_id": 25}' already exists}}
** no error is displayed on UI
** the old name is still visible in the datasets table


*What we need to do (expected outcome):*

When changing dataset details:

* If we are changing only the name

(BE should not start the dataset training)
* If we are changing only changing email set:
** when the dataset is not in training: the BE should send 200  and start the training
** when the dataset is in training: the BE should send 409 (Active workflow already exists)
* If we are changing name and email set:
** if the dataset is not in training:
*** the name should be changed
*** the BE should start the training
** if the dataset is in training:
*** the name should be changed
*** the BE should send 409 response - Active workflow already exists


*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

We are able to change the name when dataset status is “training in progress”.

column1: Create Reporting and Dashboards For Infrastructure Costs
column43:
*Context:*

Once we have properly tagged resources and are able to get costing data on a per tenant, product, and service basis ( [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/CI-47|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/CI-47|smart-link] ; [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/CI-46|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/CI-46|smart-link]  ) we will be able to create reports regarding these costs to enable all stakeholders to clearly see our costs of goods sold.

*Outcomes:*

Having a portal where we can quickly visualize current costs and trends across our infrastructure footprint we can have more intelligent fact based conversations with investors, finance, and product teams about our unit economics. 

*Definition of Done:*

* A dashboard exists in  our metric visualization tool that shows:
** Current Total Costs Per Tenant
** Infrastructure Usage Density on a dollar basis
** Per Tenant Costs Broken Down by Product
** Per Tenant Costs Broken Down by Service
** Cost Per Data Unit (MB, KB, GB) processed through the system
** Each cost metric on a rolling average basis overtime

column1: Adjust Output Patch to process all outputs regardless of status
column43:
Right now the patch checks the workItem status and if it is COMPLETE executes completion event outputs and anything else generates the CREATE event outputs.

The behavior should be if status = ‘NOTSTARTED’ or ‘STARTED’ do create event outputs.
If ‘COMPLETE’ do create and complete event outputs.

This will cover 90% of use cases. we could create another endpoint that specifically targets a specific output - but that is more work and a more complex set of lookups to formulate the correct PATCH call.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

PATCH behaves more precisely to all the appropriate outputs based on the current status of the WorkItem.

column1: Automated Storage Scaling For Persistent Workloads
column43:
*Context:*

In order to achieve our goals related to costs and usage density as outlined in this milestone: [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PR-1238|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PR-1238|smart-link] we want to automate the scaling of persistent workloads like:

* Postgres
* Kafka
* Mongo

*Outcomes:*

By automating the scaling of database resources we can achieve more usage density of our overall resources by reducing the de-facto over provisioning of database systems and therefore increase our overall usage density across the board

*Definition of Done:*

* By monitoring disk usage on databases we can respond to disk pressure events by automatically scaling the databases for a tenant, without human intervention
* Scale events are logged and recorded in our logging system for review and diagnostics if necessary

column1: All Kubernetes Costs are Reported and Allocated Correctly
column43:
*Context:*

To support our goals to drive down our marginal cost of goods sold, we need to accurately allocate costs of services deployed into our Kubernetes cluster based on tenant, product, and service. We should be able to achieve this using [KubeCost|https://github.com/kubecost] or [OpenCost|https://github.com/opencost/opencost].  

*Outcomes:*

Once we have adequately allocated costs along the correct dimensions then we can begin creating strategies for driving down costs of our infrastructure and achieving >80% usage density across our infrastructure. 

*Definition of Done:*

* All costs for CPU, Memory, and Disk are allocated to the appropriate tenant, service, and product
* Cost data is reported and sent to our metric aggregation tool
* Automated policy enforcement for labeling resources using [OPA in Kubernetes|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/kubernetes-introduction/]

column1: Properly Tag All Cloud Provisioned Resources
column43:
*Context:*

In order to ensure that we have proper cost allocations across our environments and tenants we need to have a robust tagging structure that supports reporting at several layers of granularity:

* Tenant
* Product

We also need to make sure that we properly enforce policy around effective tagging of resources provisioned in Terraform. 

*Outcome:*

* We will have all the data we need to allocate costs for all resources provisioned in our cloud environments with Terraform

*Definition of Done:*

* Define a tagging schema with proper level of detail to ensure we can track costs back to tenant and product.
* Implement automated policy enforcement [using OPA|https://blog.gruntwork.io/automatically-enforce-policies-on-your-terraform-modules-using-opa-and-terratest-d6a3f34330a1] into our build and deployment pipeline to ensure all new and existing terraform complies with our cost tagging policies

Driving down costs for our infrastructure means reducing the overhead or unused resources that are allocated in our cloud environment. We currently operate with very low cost efficiency, but we want to improve overall cost efficiency of our infrastructure in a sustainable way.

*Outcomes:*

*Definition of Done:*

*Description:*

Once the sales team has developed a prospect in our sales pipelines the number one hurdle that Deepsee faces when getting adoption of our product is the internal IT and security processes for the customers. Security teams especially want to ensure that the data they provide to Deepsee is going to be secure and IT teams will want to know answers to questions around reliability and portability.

*What needs to be done?*

* Create sales friendly documentation about our security environment in a format that the sales team can easily share with internal IT teams for the prospect
* Create sales friendly documentation for how we integrate with their environments whether they are in AWS, on-premise, or elsewhere
* Create sales friendly documentation that explains our environment and tech stack in an accessible way for internal IT teams

*Definition of Done:*

* The sales team has all the collateral they need to quickly share information with the IT teams at our prospect’s request without having to involve infrastructure team members.
column166: Create Sales Collateral Around our Infrastructure and Security

column43:
*Description:*

Achieving a robust Annualized Recurring Revenue model means finding the optimal pricing strategy that results in rapid  adoption of our product without compromising long term unit economics.

When it comes to the costs of goods sold for a customer the number one drivers are always going to be infrastructure. Infrastructure costs consist of two categories:

* Operational Expense
* Overhead

Operational expense is the cost necessary to process the data through our system for a given customer, this is basically how much CPU we need to process data. 

Overhead is any resource that is not being used directly for processing documents and is considered process waste.

*What needs to be done?*

* Automate the scaling of database systems to automatically scale as data is consumed
* Leverage data compression strategies along with the use of “cold“ storage for infrequently used data
* Deploy Serverless options for services using technologies like [K-Native|https://knative.dev/docs/] to ensure we are only using resources as requests are processed

*Definition of Done:*

* Our resource usage density is >=80%

## This will ensure that we can be onboarding multiple DeepRecon customers simultaneously

The DeepGPT visualizations cement in our prospects minds that we are delivering them insights from their emails that they cannot generate through any other means.  We need to optimize the work we are delivering through our data model, ontology, knowledge base, and knowledge graph to deliver these functions to them using the emails and attachments processed.

+*Product Manager:*+ [~accountid:639cca82f78d12c0f4720283] 

+*Tech Lead:*+ [~accountid:61b79c274014290070fa34d4] 

+*Architect:*+ [~accountid:624dc011fd5e450070484b01]

h3. +*Composition of Work*+

# UI in the actionable data and DeepView screens that show DeepView
# Options to:
## Generate an email response (with some gaps for details that are unavailble)
## Generate multiple emails responses when outside data will require different answers based on a piece of data that is unknown
## Ask questions related to this process or specific email
## Answer those questions with data and visualizations that are helpful and insightful
## Propose questions to ask that could be useful to give context
# A broader semantic search across all emails instead of on an individual email basis.  This view will appear in DeepView and not in DeepRecon.

┆{color:#707070}Issue is synchronized with a {color}[{color:#707070}Trello card{color}|https://trello.com/c/1rrV8xNB]{color:#707070} by {color}[{color:#707070}Unito{color}|https://www.unito.io]

DeepRecon needs to showcase all its features and delight our initial customers and make a great impression that compels more adoption and more revenue.

To do this we need to ensure that all of the following items are working very well and fully tested:

‌+*Product Manager:*+ [~accountid:62f58acfe50f2f2a39579be7] 

+*Tech Lead:*+ [~accountid:63d955a3010d356379708136] 

+*Architect:*+ [~accountid:624dc011fd5e450070484b01]

h3. +*Composition of Work*+

# Email categorization and light extraction core functionality.
## DeepRecon uploads new emails successfully to train
## The training process goes smoothly from initial clustering and classification to incorporating HITL feedback and retraining
## The light extraction results need to appear accurate
## Feedback is received through the UI on when it is accurate or not
## Changes to labels need to be done using Process Glossary
## Expose categorization API to customer
# Integrated with Content Maps for Heavy Extraction
## The algorithm that analyzes an email and its extraction must trigger the need for heavy extraction correctly and consistently
## The algorithm must receive and incorporate feedback to start or stop routing message types to heavy
## The extracted data must show up in the Actionable Data UI
## AWS Textract feature flag
# Manual/Engineering ability to retrain the categorization model
## The models are easily retrained to incorporate user feedback
# DeepRecon publishes data to DeepView
## “NOW” we need to get the Broadridge data into the UI as “dummy data” to drive the screens
## “NEXT” ASAP we need the data to be sent to the DeepView to start ensuring we are populating the new dashboards as expected through DeepView
# DeepRecon has Projects
## RBAC mapping

Note:  One thing that could be explored here but is not required is making some DeepPilot functions modular so they can be deployed separately and not require a full DeepPilot deployment:

# Term Glossary - (Used similarly to process categories and linked to what is needed)
# Content Map - (Used to define attributes required from attachments.  Requires safeguards before putting to the users.)
# Process Model - We want a similar feel to Process model now, but we will need far simpler logic to drive things like the movement of email, alerts, and flagging/priority.

20/Nov/23 5:08 PM;624dc011fd5e450070484b01;[~accountid:62f58acfe50f2f2a39579be7], I like the way you are thinking here. I have been trying to organize the work needed for DeepRecon and have a similar grouping. Would like to point out some observations I had while grouping the work together and see if you agree on any of the following action items:

# Is there value on splitting the “Email categorization and light extraction” and “Integration with Content Maps for Heavy Extraction?” As I understand it, I believe 80% of the Accenture use cases don’t need heavy extraction. If this is the case, I would recommend this is reflected in our Milestones. However, if there is no value in first delivering categorization and light extraction and later delivering Heavy Extraction, then we should treat them as a single work stream.
# Agreed that model retraining is it’s own work stream. Seeing as our short term solution is to have Delaney take feedback and kick off retraining. I think we should kick this can down the road for as long as we can.
# In that vein, is Objective 1.2 needed for Accenture go live? It sounds to me like we are going to do the initial training for them. In which case the initial training is not required for Accenture (although is possible to deliver), and thus I question if it should be it’s own work stream.

column1: Add Kafka connection/credential info to DeepPilot
column43:
In order to start using messaging for data movement between DeepPilot and DeepView and DeepRecon and DeepView, we need to have the connection info for the deployed Kafka instance made available to the DeepPilot and DeepRecon service as environment variables for the service to pick up.

DeepView will also need this information for consumers

h4. Acceptance Criteria:

All the connection info is available to DeepPilot and DeepRecon when the service starts up via ENV variables in order to connect to the Kafka service

Same info available to DeepView service as well when it is ready for deployment [https://github.com/deepseeai/deep-view-service|https://github.com/deepseeai/deep-view-service|smart-link]

column1: [BE] Label Challenge Updates Don't Save in Broadridge
Ensure all connections to Postgres are done over a secure encryption method
column43:
*Narrative:*

Currently we enforce mutual TLS for all services that communicate within our Kubernetes cluster, but some services still make connections outside the k8s cluster, one such example is when the pre-processing and inference pipelines make connections to the database.

For our HA deployments we will begin to leverage Postgres in our K8s cluster, but we need to expose the Postgres instance using a Load Balancer that will enable inbound DB connections from Lambdas running in the same tenant network. Unfortunately, Postgres has a different ssl handshake protocol than standard ssl protocols for things like HTTPS. Currently our solution has an un-encrypted connection over private networking to the database from the Lambdas, we need a solution for this.

*AC:*

* Consider and research options for solving this challenge in our environments
** Putting an API in front of the DB that the Lambdas consume
** Moving the lambdas into our K8s cluster
* Present options along with a recommended approach to the architecture working group for discussion and review
column265: Need to support deploying Accenture as a Mutli-Region HA configuration

column43:
To control our costs, we need better allocation of our infrastructure so that it is more fully used and thus we are only buying what is needed.  Currently Core Team says we are only using 20% or resources we’ve allocated to DeepRecon and DeepPilot.  That means that our costs are much higher than what is possible. The exact elements of this work is directly related to the instrumentation prioritized above this.

‌

As a user of DeepRecon I want to accomplish these things off the back of emails that I extract data from and assign a category:

1\. Move an email - Organize email based workflows

2\. Screen an email - Minimize manual screening that can be automated

3\. Generate an alert - Get Alerts on the most critical problems

4\. Send a response - Automate simple responses or atleast the generation of them to save time and increase efficiency

‌

As much as possible, we should get this logic from our customers in a familiar way to how we capture logic from our customers in DeepPilot (aka process model and checklists)

Acceptance Criteria

# Moving an email
## This can include
### moving it to an ARCHIVE folder where it is available but does not require action
### moving it to a specific folder assigned to a team member or a counterparty to organize work that is happening in the same shared box
## The criteria is set by a set of rules managed by the customer which use variables extracted from the email and attachment
### Sample variables - Domain, specific email address, specific subject, Category assigned
# Screen an email
## Per category we know the data elements required to resolve each one.
## In our processing we look for and extract these elements
## When an element is not found, DeepRecon knows and can reply with a pre-defined email stating something like “Thank you for your request, to help us address it, can you also include XXX.  Where X is the missing field(s).
# Generate an alert
## Similar to moving an email, but this will define an alert.
## Alerts can be a tab or floating box in the UI that bring to the attention of our users things that are most critical
## Each alert should show the Alert and which Counterparty it came from
## They should link to the the email in the actionable data screen
## They should be able to manually turn off the alert when they are addressing it so that it updates all users accordingly
# Send a Response
## Leveraging the work from the NSI team it will draft an email response to the email being viewed on the actionable data screen
## It will know the category and historical responses so that it knows what to send.
## If there are multiple answers dependent on data which it does not have it will both generate multiple responses and/or create blank spaces for the user to manually adjust the output
## Initially this will be in a text file that can be edited and then copied and pasted into a email to send.

column1: [TECH DEBT] Update all scripts to be able to use the new AWS login functionality
column43: The current approach uses the AWS config from the environment variables. We no longer use this method which causes issues when we run things locally

*Narrative:*

Currently we leverage an AWS Secret to control the username and password for the RDS database, [particularly for JP Morgan|https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/secret?name=jpm-prod-production-33c72d94-539d-4268-b120-7b3f57626cab-3b5231caa432871f&region=us-east-1] this password is initially generated from the Terraform script then is automatically rotated using the [rotation lambda|https://eu-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/lambda/home?region=eu-west-1#/functions/db-key-rotation-lambda?tab=image] that is built using the [code here|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/tree/main/aws/lambdas/key-rotation]. This means that the secret is dynamically updated on a periodic basis (every 30 days).

The secret keeps the current password and the previous password in history. If for some reason though we lose access to that secret or the DB name and password gets corrupted then we will no longer have access to the database, this is a low risk occurrence but would be very high impact. 

We should have  root user that is stored somewhere as a backup in case we ever lose access to the database username and password.

*AC:*

* Create a root user for the RDS database with a new password with admin privileges to create users with any access
* Create a vault database configuration for the JPM RDS instance using the password created from above
** Setup the password to auto rotate the password every 30 days
* Create vault database role for admin users so vault can create admin users in the database
** Make the admin user rotate every 1 day
* Create a 'VaultSecret' object in Kubernetes that references the admin role for creating users
** VaultSecret should refresh every 12 hours

column1: expected_terms stored in the wrong format
column43:
It appears that the {{wit_source_factor_detals.expected_terms}} values are being stored in the wrong format. This may only be the case for work_items based on a test execution - I checked all work_items that were the result of `STP` documents and they appear to be in the correct format.


This column is meant to be a simple comma separated list of distinct normalized term names that would look like the following

{{notional-currency, applicable-fx-rate, underlying-bloomberg-ticker, underlying-trade-currency, underlying-exchange}}

There are a large pool of records that just appear to have copied the values from work_item_tasks.checklist_calculation_terms 

{{{"1cc10ad8-0eb2-4d12-884d-f53fb91dc4bd":["underlying-ric","underlying-bloomberg-ticker","underlying-trade-currency"],"3e2b18b2-1f2c-4cd6-89f9-7efca9f38df9":["underlying-ric","underlying-bloomberg-ticker","underlying-trade-currency"]}}}

- and while the value is a subset of the data in that column, they are not the same.

The question is if this has a functional impact or not
If so, we should make it all executions behave the same and finally do we need to do any kind of cleanup (is it okay that old tests have this bad format)

h4. Acceptance Criteria:

* Functional change to store the data in the correct format
* evaluate and create fixes for anything that could have historical impact.

{noformat}select wi.last_modified_at, wit.checklist_normalized_title, c."name", c.project_id, wi.checklist_id, wi.checklist_version, wit.checklist_type, wit.checklist_item_id,
wsfd.source_detail_id,
wsfd.id as factor_id, wsfd.expression, wsfd.expected_terms, wsfd.feel_output, wsfd.string_constant_output, wsfd.date_constant_output, wsfd.boolean_constant_output, wsfd.number_constant_output, wsfd.extracted_term_id, wsfd.statement_location, 
wsfd.lookup_table_id, wsfd.lookup_table_name, wsfd.lookup_table_normalized_name, wsfd.parent_factor_id
from work_items wi
join checklists c on wi.checklist_id = c.id
join executions e on wi.execution_id = e.id
join work_item_tasks wit on wi.id = wit.work_item_id
join wit_source_details wsd on wit.id = wsd.work_item_task_id 
join wit_source_factor_details wsfd on wsd.id = wsfd.source_detail_id 
where 
wit.tombstone = false

column43:
*Summary:* Context will be very useful in augmenting users in generating responses to common queries.  It gives the ability to demonstrate that “they know” each counterparty even when they do not get to answer each request.

‌

*Description*:

DeepRecon transforms incoming emails into actionable data to ensure quick resolution. When paired with DeepGPT, all historical and similar responses are considered to create context for the user which is valuable in having the most accurate response to a counter party and in making informed decisions.

‌

*Acceptance Criteria:*

# *DeepGPT* can list common questions based on the counterparty and task.      (Eg, “What % of trades break on this field?”, “How often is this break a false exception”, “How often do we amend to match counterparty on this field?”, “What is the distribution of values for this field”?)
# *DeepGPT* can generate data visuals that are helpful in communicating with counterparties.   (Eg, Bar graphs, pie charts, word maps like *DeepView)*
# *DeepGPT* can provide trend discovery and anomaly detection.          (Eg, Nadiya mentions that various people can work on the same annotations. Some of them think that in one document _Premium Amount Payer_ - is _Counterparty A,_ and others think that Premium Amount Payer is absent in the same document (and there are many such examples, that reduce accuracy).
   If we used the knowledge base, we would predict and suggest to all users that _Premium Amount Payer_ is _Counterparty A_ based on the verified entities history for the current client.)

Initially this feedback will include the following:

Acceptance Criteria

Users want more labels to provide normalized context to their emails and help them prioritize at a quick glance.

‌

Priority and Sentiment can be viewed differently but related.

Priority is set by rules defined by the counterparty.  Sentiment is reliant on email content and can be explicit such as “Escalation” in the Subject line or email body or it can rely upon a model’s interpretation of sentiment such as tone of voice.  We should look for an existing model here and not worry about training our own unless absolutely necessary.

‌

Acceptance Criteria:

Priority

# Rules to set priority are input into a  similar interface to the rules in the Phase 1 automation for moving emails.
# Priorities are Critical, High, Medium, Low, No Response Required
# A priority email should get an attribute
## Visible in DeepRecon’s UI
## Filterable in DeepView
## Part of the API payload
# Ideally we will be able to update outlook as well as an option
## On/Off for the priority flag (Set threshold as Critical or High or both)
## A label
## A movement to a folder labelled with the priority
# Charts that show priority requests by counterparty and category over time in DeepView

Sentiment

# Initially we only need assign three values per email
## Positive
## Negative
## Escalation
## Note: we will assign no value if it is neutral
# Escalation will be assigned when it is explicitly stated that something is being escalated
# Negative will include chasers and examples of frustrated customers
# Sentiment will be a label in the DeepRecon UI and if possible an outlook label.

‌

DeepSee customers will have large repositories of documents that we need to be able to quickly analyze and tag so that they referencable by other services to look up data or to use as examples for creating similar documents.  The crawler will tag each document with ~10 tags that it finds within the document.  These tags are stored as meta that can be used to quickly look up similar documents in the future by other services.

‌

Acceptance Criteria

# Define the Tag Names by user
## Probably a version of content map but simplified
## examples - Effective date, type of document, counterparty, region, trading desk/business unit, type of underlyer, expiration date, Settlement Currency
# Define the repository
# Process to move through all documents in the repository and updated UI to show progress
# Tag or documents in the repository to show what has been processed
# UI to show the document and meta data to give HITL feedback
# API to query and get back all related documents or a percentage match based on a confidence level

Integrate Crowdstrike Vulnerability Scanning with Jira Ticketing
column43:
*Narrative:*

Create Crowdstrike Workflow(s) that generate Jira Tickets based on vulnerabilities found in our assets. e.g., containers.  

*AC:*

* Create System Users in Crowdstrike and in Jira (needs testing).
* Using Crowdstrike system user create a Jira configuration in the Jira Add-on. 
* System User will own and run one or more Crowdstrike Workflows.
* Workflows will use the Following:
** Using one workflow with many conditions or many workflow, one per team.
** Workflow will run by trigger: Asset Management > Unmanaged /Unsupported Asset Change.
** Condition(s) will be something like: Confidence equal to High (no critical confidence exists in the options).
** If condition is met run Action: Create Jira Issue.
** Requires Jira Integration Add-on be configured (Found in Crowdstrike apps store).

We have plans in the future to improve the reading order of the OCR so that it's more natural . It needs some experimentation with more OCR settings to improve extractions and also fix these minor OCR bugs. 

Moving this ticket to the backlog and we can confirm the issue is gone after we update the OCR engine

column1: [BE] Allow SME to define which data points are required for each category
column43:
{color:#0747a6}*Why do we do it (context):*{color}

DeepRecon is a solution that allows SMEs to categorize their emails and define which data extraction is required per category.

As part of the training process, the SME needs to define for each category which data points they require in the end result (that will be displayed in the actionable data page)

Example:

* Category: Suppress Instructions
* Actionable data required: Client reference, Case Type, Intent, Reply or Spontaneous, Local Code, ISIN, Way, Quantity, Amount, ESD/VS, CCY, Counterparty, SEDOL



{color:#0747a6}*What we need to do (outcome):*{color}

*Overall conditions*

* each category can only have 1 actionable data required list
* SMEs can update the list of categories
* SMEs can update the actionable data required list
* Updates are not retroactive
* The “actionable data required list” is made of terms from the terms library

* The “category list” is made of process and subprocess from the process library



*Scenario 1*: 1 category → 1 Actionable data required list

* Category: Unmatched trade economics_agree to amend trade
* Actionable data required list: Client reference, Case Type, Intent, Reply or Spontaneous, Local Code, ISIN, Way, Quantity, Amount



*Scenario 2*: N category → 1 Actionable data required list

* Category: Unmatched trade economics_disagree to amend trade ; Suppress instructions_Trade to be cancelled by Bank ; [other category]; [other category]
* Actionable data required list: Client reference, Case Type, Intent, Reply or Spontaneous, Local Code, ISIN, Way, Quantity, Amount



{color:#0747a6}*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*{color}

API Accenture is fetching the list of terms from this page and not from the content map

Actionable data page output is aligned with the list of terms we have here



{color:#0747a6}*What is out of scope:*{color}

N/A
