column265: Enable options for Connecting to DeepSee over Private Networks

column43:
*Context:*

Supporting sales initiatives is one of our primary concerns to achieve our goals around annual recurring revenue. Ensuring that we can rapidly respond to requests for POC’s and new environments for customers will be critical for this.  Having a systematic and automated way to provision new environments is one of the most critical things that we can do to achieve these goals.

Currently it takes 3-4 days to have a fully functional tenant environment provisioned and this is because there are several undocumented manual steps and other gotchas that have to be remedied as the come up. Manual steps include:

* secret creation in kubernetes
* syncing order for service accounts, gateways, and other configuration
* updating the VPN
* CIDR range calculation
* AWS Workspace creation

For the most part there are automated solutions for each of these and for any others that we may encounter. 

*Definition of Done:*

* Anyone with access to the infrastructure environments should be able to follow specific documented steps and have a fully provisioned tenant environment with DeepRecon, DeepPilot, and DeepView within 4 hours or less. 
* The terraform is modularized to support running parts and pieces of the infrastructure
*

column1: Make sure we have appropriate controls in place to avoid customer data loss
column43:
*Context:*

Protecting our customer’s data is critical to maintaining trust in the financial services and banking sector. For this reason we need to ensure that we have a robust data loss prevention strategy and that our infrastructure supports this strategy.

*Definition of Done:*

* All traffic egressed out of our networks is tracked and logged
* Services within our environment can only make calls outside our network that are explicitly allowed through a firewall
* All requests made to AWS services are done through service endpoints to mitigate traffic egressing from within our customer networks
* We have clear line of site using Datadog to all connections outside our network
* Any access made to document storage that originated outside the customer network is alerted

*Narrative:*

To support the private ingress options for our customers as documented in [Lucid Charts here|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/6c73ba3e-ca2a-4b64-ade0-bd51b6529334/edit?page=0_0&invitationId=inv_7f96fcb9-872d-46c7-a34b-aa280135bb86#]. We need a way to optionally provision private ingress VPC’s for each new tenant along with the VPC endpoints need to setup [AWS Private Link|https://aws.amazon.com/privatelink/]



*AC:*

* For the Tenant Terraform deployed with Terra Grunt we need to add the option to enable a separate private ingress VPC
* Determine the IP ranges that we will enable newly created Tenant ingress networks out of and document them in Confluence
* The endpoint is created to front the DeepSee applications deployed in the DeepSee VPC that lives behind the Transit Gateway
* The private networking should be the default configuration

column1: Create Datamodel APIs to support Query creation
column43:
As a DeepView user, I need to be able to define the data I want to display in my diagrams. The data will be populated via the DeepView Rest Query APIs, but a user is not going to want to build the queries for these APIs. Instead, the UI will need to guide the user in this process.

The most important part of this will be listing the fields that are supported by the data model the user is building a query for, and what those field types are (which will imply the operations that can apply to those fields).

Acceptance Criteria:

* An API (or maybe just a schema? Or an API that provides a schema?) is provided that allows the UI to know what fields can be added to the query and how to use them.
column166: Create Datamodel APIs to support Query creation

column43:
As the DeepView team, I need to be able to provide a service that collects data from our existing services (DeepRecon and DeepPilot) and aggregates that data so that it can be queried by the client and used for dashboards, reporting, etc.

This requires additional resources in our ecosystem for storing data specifically for reporting and insights. It also requires resources to handle events from various services.

When do we stop?

* DeepView is able to query other services for data which is stored in it’s own datastore.
* DeepView can receive notifications from the DeepRecon and DeepPilot services related to relevant events.

As a client with with a paragraph describing a series of dates, I need to be able to convert that paragraph into a list of dates. The client will send my model endpoint the paragraph to convert and any contextual information. My model will return a list of dates in ISO-8601 {{date}} format.

Additionally, I will be able to query the DeepRecon database to receive feedback for my model.

When do we stop

* A model exists with an endpoint which will convert a paragraph to a list of dates
* An API contract is defined for calling the model
* The model is part of the MLOps pipeline and is added to the inference model chain
* We have a path forward for training (recognizing it may be different for this model then some of our other ones).

As a DeepPilot user I want to be able to a paragraph that describes a series of dates and – as an output – provide a series of dates that can be used for validation, reconciliation, and in calculation.

When do we stop working?

* I am able to convert a paragraph describing the frequency of a series of dates into an array of dates.
* I am able to provide feedback on the dates that DeepPilot provides, in case the predicted dates are wrong.

column1: [BE] Allow users to specify where a subgroup starts when providing a mapping expression for a subgroup term
column43:
As we start allowing array terms in subgroups, multiple subgroups, and nested subgroups it’s going to be more ambiguous and difficult to automatically figure out which values belong to which subgroups. All the terms in a given subgroup will share a common base, having the user specify which portion of a mapping expression represents the subgroup will avoid ambiguity and ensure that terms are extracted the way the user expects them to be.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* When specifying a mapping expression for subgroup terms the user is able to specify the ‘subgroup stem'
* If the ‘subgroup stem’ is present for a term it is used when assigning subgroups, if not it will default to the current behavior
* If any term in a subgroup has the ‘subgroup stem’ specified, then we can use that value for all the terms in the same subgroup

*REVIEW LABELS AFTER TRAINING*

We need an option to review the labels assigned during training. We need to be able to filter specific subsets of labels, e.g.

* low/medium/high confidence
* only UNSUPERVISED
* only LABELLED
* LABELLED and low confidence
* UNSUPERVISED and low confidence
* LABELLED label different than PREDICTED label
* UNSUPERVISED label different than PREDICTED label

This review screen needs to be visible only to DeepSee engineers. The client’s SME does not have or need the knowledge of what “UNSUPERVISED” label means etc. The functionality for the client will be implemented as part of [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1766|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1766|smart-link]

column1: Re-architect Flower to use gRPC Re-Request Transport
column43:
Flower was configured to run with gRPC Bi-Directional Streaming. Streams are being terminated by AWS ALBs when the sessions become idle. 

AC:

* Server will need to use re-request argument --grpc-rere
* Client will also need to be configured for the re-request transport. 
* Define a separate Flower Driver.



See recorded demo for additional details.

*Narrative:*

As we leverage services like Azure OCR and deploy across multiple clouds to support different customer use cases across multiple clouds we will need to facilitate routing between multiple clouds in a secure and compliant way. 

We have several options to approach this and will need to research options to include tradeoffs between cost, complexity, and time. 

Here are some link resources as a starting point:

* [https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cloud-adoption-framework/ready/azure-best-practices/connectivity-to-other-providers|https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cloud-adoption-framework/ready/azure-best-practices/connectivity-to-other-providers|smart-link] 
* [https://cloud.google.com/network-connectivity/docs/interconnect/how-to/cci/aws/choose-locations|https://cloud.google.com/network-connectivity/docs/interconnect/how-to/cci/aws/choose-locations|smart-link] 
* [https://developers.cloudflare.com/magic-wan/|https://developers.cloudflare.com/magic-wan/|smart-link] 

*AC:*

* Research connectivity options between clouds
* Identify the tradeoffs for each option
* Based on research document a recommendation in the [decision points section|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/IN/pages/1857191949/Decision+Points]
*

*Narrative:*

Hashicorp recently changed the licensing [agreement for Terraform|https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/blob/main/LICENSE] that makes it more restrictive. In response to this the Linux Foundation has forked terraform into [OpenTofu|https://opentofu.org/] which is distributed under the [Mozilla Public 2.0 License|https://github.com/opentofu/opentofu/blob/main/LICENSE]. 

 To mitigate compliance risk  we should investigate using OpenTofu instead of terraform.

*AC:*

* Investigate how difficult it will be to transition to open terraform
** How is it installed?
** Is it compatible with our current Terraform
** Would we need to make any major changes to how we provision our infrastructure to use Open Tofu
* Write any stories needed to complete the transition

*Why we need that:*

* In case we have multiple datasets for the single data source, and we will train models on each of them ( the small models ), it may happen that during training of the single model ( by Single Model Workflow ) it will recognize, that there are conflicts between datasets ( the same text appeared in both datasets and received different label ).
* We need to allow users to resolve those mentioned conflicts per data source.
** We have an existing flow that allows us to resolve conflicts per a single training dataset, so the pages of the UI already exist. We are missing a place in the UI that will allow the user to navigate to a page that will pull the label challenges per data source
* The API is already implemented.
** To get the challenges for data source, one should use {{source_id}} filter from this endpoint
[https://messages.dev.deepsee.ai/api/v2/docs#/labels/get_list_of_challenge_groups_api_v2_labels_challenge_groups_get|https://messages.dev.deepsee.ai/api/v2/docs#/labels/get_list_of_challenge_groups_api_v2_labels_challenge_groups_get]
Please confirm that with [~accountid:712020:ce0a682b-cdd4-4b0c-bb56-14881add2514] 
* The system will not proceed and will not train a model as long as there are unresolved labelling challenges per data source. [~accountid:633dacf93ac41ebde76e45ab] can give you more information.


Some designs can be found in the FeedbackLoop Lucid

column1: [BE] Add RBAC Policy verification to integration tests
column43:
Whenever we add a new endpoint we need to update the OPA policy documents here: [https://github.com/deepseeai/opa-policy|https://github.com/deepseeai/opa-policy|smart-link] 
If we neglect to do this, then users will not be able to access the new endpoint. We’ve had several incidents caused by the policy documents not being updated for a new endpoint. To prevent future incidents we should start testing the current OPA policy document as part of our integration testing.

We’ll need to pull in the latest policy documents from the opa-policy repository, start up the spring service locally with opa security enabled (An article on how to do that can be found here: [https://www.baeldung.com/spring-security-authorization-opa|https://www.baeldung.com/spring-security-authorization-opa|smart-link]), and make test API calls against all of the endpoint defined in our API spec to ensure that access to the endpoints is enabled.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* We pull the latest OPA policy document from the opa-policy repo when doing our integration tests
* We test all the endpoints defined in the specification against the service with OPA authorization enabled to ensure that all the endpoints have the correct authorizations
* The build fails if any endpoints do not have the correct authorizations

||*Employee access to production*||*Employee is using VDI*||*Outcome*||

column1: Additional performance improvement on work item status update
column43:
It seems that updating the status counts that are part of the WorkItemEntity when doing the PATCH for work item status updates is our new bottleneck

It is believed we could improve this performance we could do a Projection type fetch of the WorkItemEntity and a custom update to only work on the WorkItemEntity (work_items table) ignoring dependent objects.

Additionally, as there are calls to this endpoint that don’t actually update the status, in these scenarios we could skip this step entirely.
column265: Improve Work Item Processing & Management Scale

column43:
As a Process Designer or Process Manager in DeepPilot, I want to be able to deploy a model to production and then test it before I promote that model to be used for STP.

This means that when the MLP is executed, the model to use for the execution needs to be passed in by the client. The client then becomes responsible for defining which model to use, and the MLP is just responsible for executing the configured model.

More information can be found in the [Modelchain Management Architecture|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ARCH/pages/2127921153/Modelchain+Management+Architecture] document.

column1: Don't create a new message when running message extraction again on the same path via Preprocessor API
column43:
*Why do we do it (context):*

When handling duplicated request (with the same {{sourceId}} and email {{path}}) we don’t want to create new {{Message}} (with new tables and new inquiries).
We want to reuse the already extracted Message.

*What we need to do (outcome):*

Check if the email has already been process for the given source.
If an email has been already extracted, return data from DB.

*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

Handling multiple times the same (duplicated) request, doesn’t create new {{Message}}.
The response should be the same.

*What is out of scope:*

* (?) Do we want to rerun email processing? It would be useful when fixing or extracting additional data with newer version of [Preprocessor.|http://Preprocessor.IT]
It would be useful to rerun Preprocessing via Preprocessor API or Promethia Worfklows. See:
** we would need this functionality if we want to fix already processed messages: [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1908|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1908|smart-link]
** it’s related to: [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1505|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1505|smart-link] 
** the question is: Should we allow to process message again to update extracted data? Should we also update created inquiries? Or maybe create a new version of inquiries?

column1: Store which docs/predictions were used for each model training (each modelchain version)

Then use the data to power a GPT model to ask anything about bonds

column1: Leverage The RDS Proxy For Database Connections
column43:
*Narrative:*

We recently had [an incident |https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/PRGM/pages/2153971713/DCS-309+-+Prod+issue+-+[…]t+loading+in+DeepRecon+impacting+Operation+BAU+of+25+users] that negatively impacted JP Morgan, whereby the db connections were maxed out. The root of the issue is that we are not connecting through the DB proxy, but instead connecting directly to the database. We can resolve this issue by updating this [line in the terraform|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/92be709962ea4848bff7e55a67db4d1e97285b41/aws/terraform/tenant/modules/deeprecon/rds.tf#L299] to point at the DB Proxy instead of the db endpoint. 

*AC:*

* Update the secret in Terraform to point at the proxy instead of directly to the db endpoint

column1: Add sealed config for promethia__workflows to changing pod resource requests in vault
column43:
ℹ️ Context: Currently the configs that re not sealed will be overwritten on every deployment by the presync config job. 
In order to be able to change configurations in vault without being overwritten we put the path of the config into {{sealed_configs}} array. Such configs will be created if they are missing in vault, but will not be overwritten by the presync config job on next deployments. This will allow us the change the config directly in vault



*Why do we do it (context):*

* During the tests with big data volume we faced OOM error → [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1892|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1892|smart-link] 
* We have noticed that we would need to redeploy the workflow and push it through all environments to make a change
* We need a convenient way to do it quickly

*What we need to do (outcome):*

* Create a sealed config in the messages onboarding project
* The values from the sealed config should be referenced by the config of the workflows

*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

* A [sealed config|https://github.com/deepseeai/deeprecon-messages-onboarding/blob/4e0ebc64ffa7e6645a0f2778e0cae3cb2c62b679/onboarding/cli.py#L260] for resources is created
* The sealed config for resources is referenced by the [workflow config|https://github.com/deepseeai/deeprecon-messages-onboarding/blob/4e0ebc64ffa7e6645a0f2778e0cae3cb2c62b679/onboarding/__init__.py#L300]
* Test on dev with changed config was performed and the change was reflected in the workflow ( manifest of a given task ) 

*What is out of scope:*

column1: Configure Service Level Operational Dashboards Per Tenant
column43:
*Narrative:*

We want to ensure we have proper dashboards to support diagnosing and resolving incidents in production. Now that we are sending logs and telemetry data to our Datadog backend we want to create dashboards for insights into the operational health of the system.

*Assumption:*

There will be a separate story to instrument our database systems. This story only encompasses the stateless services.

*AC:*

* All dashboards are organized and grouped according to tenants
* For each tenant there should be a dashboard for each service operating in the tenant with core metrics including:
** CPU
** Memory Usage
** Error rates (based on status codes in envoy logs)
* The dashboards should be created in an automated way either through terraform or some other mechanism so that the dashboard configurations are in code and will be deployed in an automated way.

column1: Deploy a Global Load Balancer to Direct Traffic Across Multiple Regions
column43:
*Narrative:*

To support our multi-region HA footprint we want to balance traffic across multiple regions. The first use case for this is our deployment with Accenture. We can leverage [AWS' Global Accelerator |https://aws.amazon.com/global-accelerator/pricing/]for this purpose.

Ultimately our infrastructure should look similar to [this diagram.|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/8a07eb05-1bbb-46e9-abab-e1cd72ac433d/edit?invitationId=inv_9097787f-8556-4ed0-b6d7-477ac09d3abb&page=xJ22.ZsAwsBv#]

*AC:*

* The configuration for the global load balancer is added to the [HA terraform|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/tree/main/aws/terraform/HA/networking]
* The global load balancer is configured to send 10% of traffic to our secondary region (eu-central-1) and 90% of traffic to the primary region (eu-west-1)
* DNS is configured for the eu region to send traffic to the global load balancer 
** The DNS should be configured with the following format: 
{noformat}app.<tradezone>.deepsee.ai ex) app.eu.deepsee.ai{noformat}
column265: Need to support deploying Accenture as a Mutli-Region HA configuration

column1: Increase size of JPM RDS database
column43:
The current JPM RDS Posgres Database (jpm-prod-production-33c72d94-539d-4268-b120-7b3f57626cab) is sized fairly small and we want to add resources for recent issues we’ve had with overall db resource availability and to improve monitoring

These are the changes to implement


* Update the minor version of the database to 13.11 (currently 13.10) and if we feel it is appropriate, turn on auto-upgrade of minor versions)
* enable enhanced monitoring
* enable performance insights
* modify the instance class to `db.t3.xlarge`

We do not want these changes applied immediately, but in the maintenance window (currently set for Wednesdays between 9:23 - 9:53 PM Mountain Time). because this will result in some downtime.


JPM has a standing maintenance window between 11:00 pm - 1:00 am on weeknights - but [~accountid:6169f2d407ac3c0068b87173] has indicated the window defined in RDS would be less impactful - if, for some reason this does not end up being the case, we should modify the RDS defined maintenance window to align with the JPM standing window.

It would be best if we run a backup of the database in the hour prior to the maintenance window - it currently runs early in the morning and in this case there would be more potential data loss with the standard backup window (again, maybe a good idea to do regular backups in the hour(s) just prior to the normal maintenance window instead of after it)

h5. Acceptance Criteria:

* Changes set for the JPM RDS instance and verified via AWS Console that they are scheduled for the next maintenance window
* Schedule a Backup for 90 minutes prior to the scheduled maintenance window
* Post maintenance window, validate the updates were applied and the db is functioning

[Moved to PR-1193]

*REVIEW LABELS AFTER TRAINING*

We need an option to review the labels assigned during training. We need to be able to filter specific subsets of labels, e.g.

* low/medium/high confidence
* only UNSUPERVISED
* only LABELLED
* LABELLED and low confidence
* UNSUPERVISED and low confidence
* LABELLED label different than PREDICTED label
* UNSUPERVISED label different than PREDICTED label

The client’s SME does not have or need the knowledge of what “UNSUPERVISED” label means etc. The functionality for the client will be implemented as part of [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1766|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/RECON-1766|smart-link]

column1: Set `MessageProcessing.ingestion_version` to the current version of Preprocessor
column43:
h3. Why do we do it (context):

When analyzing bugs related to parsed emails, extracted data and inquiries,
we want to know the exact version of preprocessor used to executing given {{MessageProcessing}}.

At this moment we are setting {{ingestion_version}} to a dummy value at the moment of {{MessageProcessing}} creation.

h3. What we need to do (outcome):

Set {{MessageProcessing.ingestion_version}} to the {{<commit-id>}} of the preprocessor implementation handling given {{MEssageProcessing}}.

* Preprocessor should overwrite {{ingestion_version}} each time it is processing a {{MessageProcessing}}
* Note: we can also use a docker image tag (if we can be able to easily relate it to a commit-id)

h3. When do we stop (acceptance criteria):

{{ingestion_version}} of {{MessageProcessing}} created by the promethia workflow should be set to a meaningful value (an empty string, “unprocessed” or sth similar).

After batch ingestion workflow and realtime processing via Preprocessor HTTP API, the {{MessageProcessing.ingestion_version}} contains enough information to identify the exact implementation version (commit id) of the preprocessor.

h3. What is out of scope:

* Defining and saving a version of the whole data ingestion workflow.
* Overwriting version of existing (already processed) {{MessageProcessing}}s.

[^SEC-301080-Testing-XS2445835122_TS.pdf]
[^SEC-301080-Testing-XS2445835122_PS.pdf]

Currently, our system relies on passing an {{ocr_type}} configuration to the ML pipeline when processing a document. This configuration is transmitted via the {{/projects/{projectId}/documents/{documentId}/inference-execution}} endpoint, originating from an environment property in the {{start-preprocessing}} lambda, which triggers upon S3 uploads.

This setup presents two main issues:

# Dependency on information from the {{start-preprocessing}} lambda restricts the initiation of the ML processing pipeline.
# The extraction models' behavior is influenced by this configuration, potentially altered without user awareness.

To address this, we propose:

* Implementation of a storage and versioning system for configurations impacting the ML pipeline.
* Collaboration with the ML team to identify other relevant configurations.

Determining the optimal storage location for these configurations, potentially within the {{modelchain_model_versions}} or {{modelchain_versions}} tables, requires careful consideration.

h3. +*Acceptance Criteria:*+

* A new endpoint enabling updates to behavioral configurations for a model.
* Creation of updated configurations as new versioned objects, incrementing the modelchain version upon changes.
* Passage of configurations to the ML pipeline during invocation.

h3. +*Financial Impact:*+

Implementing this solution is anticipated to yield financial benefits through:

* Increased efficiency in ML pipeline initiation, reducing processing delays.
* Enhanced model behavior management, potentially leading to improved accuracy and reduced resource expenditure.

column1: [BE] Have the inference-execution endpoint verify the sha256 value of documents
column43:
The {{/projects/{projectId}/documents/{documentId}/inference-execution}} endpoint is called to kick off the ML pipeline to process a document. We should check the {{sha256}} value of the file to verify that we are about to start execution for the correct document.

Additionally, we should update the status of the {{doc_files}} record to indicate that the file failed sha256 verification. We’ll probably need a new document status for that.

Note: This should not be done until [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-193|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/PILOT-193|smart-link] is complete.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* The {{inference-execution}} endpoint verifies the {{sha256}} value of the file before calling the ML pipeline
** An error should be returned if the sha256 value doesn’t match
* The {{doc_files}} record is updated to indicate that the file failed sha256 verification.

column1: Being able to Communicate With MLFlow from All Environments
column43:
*Context:*

We have several use cases where non-production and production workloads need to be able to communicate with our [mlflow instance|http://mlflow.deepsee.ai] to register models. We currently deploy mlflow into the datascience-lab namespace in production. 

One way to solve this problem, is by creating routes between the production and non-production clusters enabling traffic to mlflow in prod, but this creates potential security or compliance risks allowing traffic to traverse between these systems. We want to have mlflow be in a neutral centralized location to enable the use cases we need to support. 



*AC:*

* MLFlow is deployed into our centralized orchestration cluster
* Routes exist between our various clusters and this orchestration cluster such that we can serve MLFlow from all environments

column1: Categorization of replies and subsequent messages
column43:
For *ACCENTURE USE CASE ONLY* 

* DeepRecon needs to have a different workflow for Accenture 
* Data extraction and Categorization need to consider the history of replies

*SCENARIO 1* 

* DeepRecon defines the category based on the text in [Email]
* DeepRecon needs to execute data extraction on  [Email] 

*SCENARIO 2* 

* DeepRecon defines the category based on the text in [Email] and [Email-1]
* DeepRecon needs to execute data extraction on  [Email] and [Email-1 ]

*SCENARIO 3* 

* DeepRecon defines the category based on the text in  [Email] and [Email-2]. Chasers are excluded.
* DeepRecon needs to execute data extraction on [Email] and [Email-2]. Chasers are excluded

!image-20231013-100915.png|width=75%!



*Assumption* 

Initial logic for categorization and data extraction doesn’t go beyond [Email-2]



----

*Loris brainstorming (it is incomplete - don't focus on it)*

*Categorization - SUGGESTION*

* We need to categorize [EMAIL - 1] first 
* Remove that intent for the categorization of [CURRENT EMAIL]

As a Process Designer of DeepPilot, I want to allow analysts to suggest changes to my processes. This might include Checklists, Lookup Tables, Calendar Overrides, and Equivalency Lists.

I want to be notified of these suggestions and be able to approve and reject them before they take place.

Acceptance Criteria:

* For the components mentioned above:
** Analysts can make suggests.
** A Process Designer can review suggested changes.
** Changes are made to components upon Process Designer approval.

As an executive or administrator using DeepRecon or DeepPilot, I want to be able to view a dashboard in DeepView that provides insights into how DeepSee is being used in my business.

Acceptance Criteria:

* I am able to view analytics data in DeepView
* DeepView has room to grow into an application that supports creating and maintaining dashboards with various views over dynamic time ranges.

The purpose of parking lot workflow is to verify only wrong or potenitally wrong labels by running them through our algorithm, and creating challenges for the user.
Once the Parking Lot Workflow finishes, it will trigger Single Model Workflow which will train a new version of the model. All the messages from a data source, so those from training flow and real time flow will be included there.

Here is a flow chart presenting the process in tab Real Time Classification: [https://lucid.app/lucidchart/25c341db-9843-4dfb-be4a-6150ed3aa7fc/edit?page=.P.AuEmMy8Pp&invitationId=inv_886cba69-8ae7-4b49-bb03-52fe1ac45c5c#|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/25c341db-9843-4dfb-be4a-6150ed3aa7fc/edit?page=.P.AuEmMy8Pp&invitationId=inv_886cba69-8ae7-4b49-bb03-52fe1ac45c5c#|smart-link]

* *Why do we do it (context):*
** The snyk is complaining that the outdated version is a vulnerability
** The pydantic v2 is faster
** The longer we will wait the harder it will be to change
** Other libraries already started to migrate and by not updating our software to this change we may end up with obsolete and vulnerable libraries
* *What we need to do (outcome):*
** The promethia ml workflows uses pydantic version >=2 instead of 1.X.X
* *When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*
** promethia ml workflows uses pydantic version 2
** tests are fixed
* *What is out of scope:*
** updating other projects

h3. +*Why do we do it (context):*+

DeepSee users need to be able to see emails/work items in a dashboard.  We want to be able to help them see trends or problems in their processes via standard dashboards. This view will be limited to one project. The overall product is called DeepView.

DeepView’s mission is to provide industrialized analytics to power observability and transparency across teams and trading counterparties for the most complex, risk-prone, processes in capital markets.

This will help front-middle-back office, LoB managing directors, compliance, and regulators by providing:

* Single pane of glass visibility
* Firm-specified performance KPIs
* People and process management

h3. +*What we need to do (outcome):*+

We would like to build a set of 6 screens of with up to 6 charts each.  There will be slight differences between DeepRecon and DeepPilot to ensure that the proper data is displayed.  However, they should have the same look and feel.

h3. +*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*+

* Provide data for pre-generated dashboards for DeepPilot and DeepRecon from DeepView.

h3. +*Additional Information:*+

column1: Define Query End Points and generate initial data
column43:
As a DeepView user I want to be able to build widgets in a dashboard that display data. This will require me – via the UI – to define the queries that show the data to display.

Although the ability to define my graphs is not going to be used for pre-defined dashboards, we want to build the pre-defined dashboards on the DeepView product. Thus we need to build the Query API that the UI will use to get the data to display in the DeepRecon and DeepPilot predefined dashboards.

When are we done?

* An API is defined that allows the UI to query the data for most of the widgets in the pre-defined dashboards.
** Recognizing that our data model, type of data, or other performance issues may challenge our ability to meet all the widget requirements, we may negotiate with product what is difficult, costly, or not worth the roi to complete.
* An initial data model is created for DeepRecon (emails) and DeepPilot (work items).
* Data models are being populated in the DeepView Datasource from our operational applications.

Try to annotate e.g. text “Actual/365 (fixed)”

Expected Result: Only selected text is extracted

Actual Result: Extracted text has extra characters: “IL Actual/365 (fixed)”

!image-20230914-034331.png|width=1589,height=429!



[https://jpm-prod.deepsee.ai/markets/projects/98cb0b20-688d-4cf8-89b4-02b0f129fb1c/content-maps/43459ed0-2870-447c-b8e3-70a21a2d9dbd/document/b438e34d-ea63-4d2a-92c2-5cead9a5f2e1|https://jpm-prod.deepsee.ai/markets/projects/98cb0b20-688d-4cf8-89b4-02b0f129fb1c/content-maps/43459ed0-2870-447c-b8e3-70a21a2d9dbd/document/b438e34d-ea63-4d2a-92c2-5cead9a5f2e1]

Terms: *Fixed Leg End Accrual Dates, Fixed Leg Day Count Fraction, Floating Rate Day Count Fraction, Interst Accrual Convention*

Right now this is what happens:

# User builds a diagram in Blockly
# User hits Save, at which point the UI converts the diagram into a FEEL expression, then both the diagram XML and the FEEL expression are stored in the BE
# When a work item is created, the BE just grabs those already existing FEEL expressions to execute them

That way of doing it is why we have such an issue when we update the FEEL output of a stencil, because now we have N number of FEEL expressions stored that have the old output and need to be re-saved (which is a pain in the butt).What we really aught to be doing is:

# User builds a diagram in Blockly
# User hits Save, at which point we convert the default XML output into some sort of internal structure that represents the relationships between blocks, then that representation along with the default XML are stored.
# When a work item is created, the BE would take that internal structure, convert it all into a FEEL expression at that time, and then execute it

With that second approach, updating a stencil's output would make it so all future work items automatically get the updated output because the FEEL would be generated at run time rather than at build time. If we had a stencil that points to another calculation's output, this would also address the stale issue because it would grab that other calculation's output at execution time so its always the latest and greatest.This approach also puts way less stress on the UI. There is a ton of trust right now that the UI correctly builds these FEEL expressions, but it makes more sense for that to also be part of the BE so that the UI can focus on making sure we simply grab and store the diagram's relationships correctly.

*As a user,* I want

*So that*,
----
*Extra Details:*
----
*Acceptance Criteria*:
* first_thing

column1: Enforce main/master branch protection for poduction repositories
column43:
Branch protection should be enabled for all code that touches production. This should be coded and enforced (i.e. enforced during every build of the main/master branch, nightly, etc.). Setting must include:

* Require a pull request before merging
* Require approvals
* Dismiss stale pull request approvals when new commits are pushed
* Do not allow bypassing the above settings

A mostly complete list of production repos is [here|https://deepseehq-my.sharepoint.com/:x:/g/personal/shad_oneil_deepsee_ai/EXeuaGKwZ_xMuubmcjrFy_sBeKtpbSmn4i3WaOD0CDTy9g?e=dHZoYy].

*Approach:*

The best approach should be researched but a workflow could be created in the seccom project to enforce this. Ideally, projects should be marked as production either by using a static list in the workflow or by a git marker (i.e. a {{.deepsee/config}} file checked into git with a {{production: true}} setting of some sort). Future path-to-production gates could check for this and enforce standards or disallow production deployment.

*AC:*

* Branch protection is enabled for all repositories that are in scope for SOC/other audit.

column1: Appropriate management of subgroup_index and term_index fields in predictions
column43:
*Context*: The current API allows us to pass in a subgroup_index and term_index under certain circumstances

When using the {{documents/{documentId}/annotations}} If we know the current predictionId the only subgroupIndex adjustment we should be to set it to {{-1}} when the  subgroupTerm has been determined to be {{missing}}

When the predictionId is not part of the API call (adding a term that was not predicted) if it is part of a subgroup and/or an array term, we need a way to indicate that (use the subgroupIndex/termIndex attributes) - all other cases we should never add/change one of these indexes.
 

Neither the ML team or the UI use the term_associations - we can stop managing this table in the extractor service during annotations

Scope of current ticket: 

* Make sure we aren’t manipulating indexes when we shouldn’t
* Stop attempting to manage associations

*As a user,* I want

*So that*,

----

*Extra Details:* 

There are conditions where we could get collisions on the index values when we add new term_prediction records (predictionId is not known) this will need to be managed by another story (PABE-2150)

----

*Acceptance Criteria*:

* We no longer read/write term_associations and term_association_feedback records during the annotation process
* Do not modify indexes when the predictionId is known
* Only update subgroupIndex when the subgroup is missing on a known predictionId
* Add the passed in subgroupIndex/termIndex when the predictionId is NOT known

column1: Mitigate Github 3rd Party Action Security Risks
column43:
*Narrative:*
Review and remediate 3rd party Github Shared Actions with open permissions and unpinned actions.  

*AC:*

* Configure DeepSee workflows with least privileges required to run 3rd Party Shared Actions. 
* Pin DeepSee Workflows and Custom Actions to 3rd Party Shared Actions Commits.
* If possible, isolate actions to separate jobs.

column1: Cognito Gets Invoked Three Times on Login
column43:
*Context:*

There was at some point a feature requirement for JPM whereby whenever a user logs in they wanted to have all that user’s active sessions to be invalidated before that user is logged in. The way we have achieved this in our environment currently is:

# The user gets logged in
# We call a special global logout function that Cognito offers that invalidates the users refresh tokens across all sessions
# The user is logged in one more time

This approach is problematic, because it results in the pre-token lambda generator (the lambda that is used to add role based project scopes to the JWT token).  Currently we have the role mappings hard coded in the pre-token Lambda generator, but ultimately we want to have an RBAC services API that handles all the dynamic role mappings (this approach is [diagrammed here|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/7c1752ad-5621-4b06-b5b1-b95a85065f01/edit?invitationId=inv_745c1456-88ef-4f94-b62c-fdfdd6b3aaf6&page=Fq_fDWkWAhBn#]). Because we will add an API call to the login process the current situation where it gets invoked 3 times will inject undue latency into the system and so we need to figure out and implement a solution.

*AC:*

* We implement a solution that allows for the API call without injecting undue latency into the login process

column1: Update the pre-token lambda generator to leverage the RBAC Services API
column43:
*Context:*

As a part of our overall RBAC implementation and Auth Flow as documented in [this Lucid Chart|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/7c1752ad-5621-4b06-b5b1-b95a85065f01/edit?invitationId=inv_745c1456-88ef-4f94-b62c-fdfdd6b3aaf6&page=Fq_fDWkWAhBn#] we will need to update our [existing implementation |https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/tree/main/aws/lambdas/pretoken-generator]of the pre-token lambda generator to leverage the the RBAC services API implemented in [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-914|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-914|smart-link] rather than with the hard coded role mappings we currently have in place.

*AC:*

* Move the code for the pre-token lambda generator to its own repository
* Ensure we have full build, test, and deploy automation for the lambda all the way to production
* Ensure that the code has 100% code coverage and that this is enforced through the build pipeline
* The lambda generator should have as little logic as possible, with most of the core business logic offloaded to the services API
* The new lambda should be fully deployed to all tenants

*Context:*

As a part of our overall RBAC and auth flow architecture as outlined in this [Lucid Chart|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/7c1752ad-5621-4b06-b5b1-b95a85065f01/edit?invitationId=inv_745c1456-88ef-4f94-b62c-fdfdd6b3aaf6&page=Fq_fDWkWAhBn#], we want to implement an RBAC service to support role mappings between users, products, and services.

We need to implement an API that matches the specification outlined by [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-912|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-912|smart-link]. 

*AC:*

* Implement the service so as to support the service contract as defined in [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-912|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-912|smart-link]
* Leverage the repository and build pipelines defined in [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-913|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-913|smart-link]
* Ensure code is fully tested with 100% unit test coverage
* Ensure the implemented service is deployed all the way to production for all tenants.

column1: Scaffold the RBAC Service API Repository and CI/CD
column43:
*Context:*

As a part of our overall RBAC and auth flow architecture as outlined in this [Lucid Chart|https://lucid.app/lucidchart/7c1752ad-5621-4b06-b5b1-b95a85065f01/edit?invitationId=inv_745c1456-88ef-4f94-b62c-fdfdd6b3aaf6&page=Fq_fDWkWAhBn#], we want to implement an RBAC service to support role mappings between users, products, and services.

Before implementing the service we want to ensure we have scaffolded all the supporting repository requirements to ensure full automation of build, testing, and deployment of the service into production.

*AC:*

* Decide what programming language will be used to implement the service in question.
* Create a separate repository for the RBAC service including automated build, test, and deploy pipelines to deploy the service into production
* Create hello-world implementation of the application
* Implement the Dockerfile to build and push the application to our container registry 
* Implement the ArgoCD manifests to deploy the application into each tenant environment leveraging ArgoCD. The manifests should exist along side application in the same repository
* Leveraging [go-migrate|https://github.com/golang-migrate/migrate] ensure we have automated database migrations including seeding any data needed to bootstrap the application
* Ensure that code has 100% code coverage as a part of the build and test pipeline and restrict merging of PR’s if coverage requirements are not met.
* Make sure the hello-world implementation is deployed all the way to production

column1: Define the API Contract for the RBAC Service API
column43:
*Context:*

To support our RBAC system within our services environment we will need a service that maps users to roles/scopes and resources within our various applications. To facilitate this we currently leverage a [pre-token generation lambda|https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cognito/latest/developerguide/user-pool-lambda-pre-token-generation.html] that maps what are currently hardcoded role mappings to users and services that leverage AWS Cognito to provide credentials for authenticating in our system.

Ultimately we want these role mappings to not be hardcoded, but dynamically generated and updated as a part of the administration of our application. In service to this goal we will want to create an API that can update and read generated role mappings for use in the auth flow to add appropriate scopes to the application.

The first step in building out the RBAC service API is understanding the API contract and what will be needed to support our auth flows across applications.

AC:

* Define the underlying data model to support our RBAC needs within DeepRecon, DeepPilot, DeepGraph, and potential future applications.
* Based on the underlying data-model define the RESTful API contract leveraging Open API

Some of our stencils require another stencil to work properly, but as of yet we have not implemented any validations to make sure a calculation cannot be saved without all the required stencils (subgroup term and for each stencils, for example).  This of course can result in failed calculations and confusion for the user

h2. Context:

As the Security and Compliance Team, we need to capture and maintain logs (evidence) to demonstrate security, confidentiality, and availability throughout the customer data lifecycle. This will become the baseline standard for logging, to be applied to all ‘product.' Objective is traceability and observability, feeding a SIEM console to capture baselines and identify anomalies.

Critical sources for a cloud-native SaaS company to log in a SIEM for incident response include the following:

* *Cloud infrastructure logs:* These logs include information about cloud resources such as virtual machines, containers, and storage. They can be used to track changes to cloud resources, identify unauthorized access, and investigate security incidents.
* *Application logs:* These logs include information about the activities of applications running in the cloud. They can be used to track user activity, identify errors, and troubleshoot performance problems.
* *Network logs:* These logs include information about network traffic, such as source and destination IP addresses, ports, and protocols. They can be used to identify malicious traffic, track lateral movement, and investigate data exfiltration.
* *Security logs:* These logs include information about security events, such as authentication failures, unauthorized access attempts, and malware detections. They can be used to detect and respond to security incidents.
* *Audit logs:* These logs include information about system changes, such as user account creation and modification, file access, and software installation. They can be used to track changes to the system and investigate security incidents.

In addition to these critical sources, there are other logs that may be useful for incident response, such as logs from identity and access management (IAM) systems, email servers, and endpoint protection systems. The specific logs that are most important will vary depending on the specific cloud-native environment.

It is important to collect and store all of these logs in a SIEM so that they can be analyzed for signs of malicious activity. The SIEM can also be used to generate alerts when suspicious activity is detected, which can help to speed up the investigation and response to security incidents.

Here are some additional tips for logging in a cloud-native environment:

* Use a centralized logging solution to collect and store logs from all of your cloud resources.
* Use standardized log formats to make it easier to analyze logs.
* Encrypt logs to protect them from unauthorized access.
* Configure retention policies for logs so that they are not deleted too soon.
* Regularly review logs for signs of malicious activity.

===

column1: Create Prediction API to support Predictions from multiple sources
column43:
As a DeepPilot user, I may need to provide predictions from multiple sources to include in my process models. These sources may include:

# The MLP extraction pipeline
# The DeepRecon Classification Extraction
# Textract, as was used for the PPI Document demo
# A customer owned extraction tool whose predictions the customer would like included in the Process Model

The immediate need is to support use cases 1 and 2, however, this solution will enable more flexible prediction sources moving forward.

In order to support multiple prediction sources, I need an endpoint that will allow me to add predictions to a document.

The scope should be such that it is only available to internal services, such as MLP or DeepRecon. No User Role should be able to programmatically add predictions.

Once a prediction is added, the prediction record itself cannot be altered. Instead it should be updated via prediction feedback.

The API should support everything needed to populate the {{term_predictions}} table with the information the MLP is currently populating it with.

Big Picture Details:

Currently the extractor service trigger checklist processing when all documents are marked as complete from the MLP Pipeline. By updating the extractor service to receive predictions via an API from multiple sources, we will instead need to trigger checklist processing based on when all expected sources provide their predictions. This will be done as part of another story, however this does affect this story in the following ways:

# The request adding predictions will need to indicate the prediction source the predictions are coming from.
# All predictions from a given source need to be added at the same time. This makes it clear when a source has provided it’s expected predictions.

Acceptance Criteria:

# A Create Predictions API endpoint is created in the DeepPilot API specification and implementation.
# The request to create predictions contains the prediction source.
# All predictions are create as part of a single request.
# Stories are written for the MLP and DeepRecon teams to begin using this API to create predictions.

column43: ┆{color:#707070}Issue is synchronized with a [Trello card|https://trello.com/c/A5Tyfbos] by [Unito|https://www.unito.io]{color}

* *Why do we do it (context):*
** It may happen that the same message ( with exactly the same MESSAGE-ID  header ) will be delivered in multiple different EML files.
In such a situation, we want to process the message only once ( because it is actually a unique message that could have been sent to multiple receivers ), but 'record' the fact that we have processed the file.
** Currently, the processing of the second message would try to create a duplicate in the messages table and fail
* *What we need to do (outcome):*
** Handle the conflicting MESSAGE ID in a way that will save the first message and for the second and next occurrence of that MESSAGE ID it will link the existing entity from {{message}} table to the entry in {{message_processing}} instead of failing
* *When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*
** Conflict logic is implemented
** Test that is proving the case is implemented 
* *What is out of scope:*

----

OLD DESCRIPTION:

* If the preprocessor works on message with MESSAGE-ID ( {{external_unique_id}}) that already exists in {{messages}} table
** if the message comes from the same {{source}} it the {{message_processing}} should {{FAIL}} with message duplicated id
** if the message comes from a different {{source}} then {{message_processing}} should {{SUCCEED}} and the {{message_id}} of the existing message should be set
*** In this case there is no need for data extraction because the existing message has been already processed

**Pentest Recommendations**

Attackers can use these tokens to get credentialed access to your AWS environment. This can greatly increase the attack surface for your application and AWS environment.

*Recommendation*:
The cognito service responds with valid AWS Access, Secret and Session token keys giving access to the AWS environment. Ensure this role is locked down and does not give unnecessary access to the AWS environment.

*Publicly Available Exploits: True*

By reading the application responses an attacker can programmatically discern when they have guessed a valid username.

*Recommendation*:
Provide only a general error message when a correct or incorrect username is entered.

*Publicly Available Exploits: True*

column1: Add Performance Bench Marking to the OPA Policy Workflows
column43:
*Narrative:*

Because RBAC policy enforcement happens on every request to our API’s we want to ensure high performance for the policy evaluation. 

To support this we want to keep our policy enforcement mechanisms under 3 ms. We can [benchmark our performance|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/policy-performance/] when we run the tests. This benchmarking should happen on every PR and every deploy.

*AC:*

* Add policy benchmarking to the [build and test on PR action|https://github.com/deepseeai/opa-policy/blob/main/.github/workflows/build_and_test_rbac_templates_on_pr.yaml]. Fail the build if the performance falls below our benchmark
* Add policy benchmarking [to our deploy job|https://github.com/deepseeai/opa-policy/blob/main/.github/workflows/deploy_template_policies.yaml] and fail the build if the performance is below our benchmark

*Narrative:*

We currently have [a workflow to deploy|https://github.com/deepseeai/opa-policy/blob/main/.github/workflows/deploy_template_policies.yaml] our OPA Policy Bundles. This workflow builds and tests the policy bundles, but it currently does not sign the policy bundle.

The documentation for signing policy bundles can be found [here|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/management-bundles/]

*AC:*

* We create a signing key for policy bundles and store it securely in bitwarden.
* Our build job signs the bundles
* The OPA agent verifies the signature
column250:
30/Aug/23 10:08 AM;6256f917cdc24000704b6536;I looked over the documentation yesterday. 

*According to the Documentation:*  

* We will use the {{opa sign}} command to sign the bundle. 
** It defaults to RS256 for its signing encryption, which uses a public/private key pair. 
** We need to generate a key pair. 
** Store key pair in Bitwarden 
** Store pem key in a Github secret.
** Signing command will generate a new {{.signatures.json}} file and place it in the OPA Policy Bundle. 
* The {{opa sign}} command will need to be placed in the build workflow. 
** The command will need to have the Github OPA key secret variable to interpolate the key when the command is ran.  
* If OPA encounters a bundle that’s not configured for signatures and is therefore missing the {{.signatures.json}} file, it will skip the signature verification and activate the bundle as is. 


Three questions I have yet to nail down: 

# What kind of key do I actually need, e.g, pub/pem key pair?
# Is there a specific key generation tool/process that I need to use?
# If it does in fact use a public/private (pem) key pair, where do I put the .pub key?

Note: The documentation shows the {{opa sign}} command with a .pem (private key) file.
column251:
30/Aug/23 10:09 AM;6256f917cdc24000704b6536;Next Steps for Today:

* Nail down the key generation specifics.
** Where the public key will live (if a key pair is used as indicated by documentation).
* I will perform some testing locally to flush out the key gen process, and {{opa sign}} command.


Next Steps, if time permits: 

* Generate new key for signing Policy Bundles and place them in:
** Bitwarden
** Github Secret
* Update my copy of the opa repo, branch it and then begin work on the following workflows:
** build_and_test_rbac_templates_on_pr.yaml
** deploy_template_policies.yaml
* Add the the following to each workflow (as needed):
** Add the OPA signing key to a new Github repository secret.
** Add the {{opa sign}} command to sign OPA Policy Bundles.
*** Example: {{opa sign --signing-key /path/private_key.pem --bundle <bundle name>}}
*** If possible, modify {{opa sign}} to pull/interpolate the OPA key Github secrete instead of from a file. Not sure this will work, since the command will expect a file. I don’t want to put a key in the repo. The shared actions for OPA might use another parameter for interpolating the key from a secret. So this example command might be different:
**** {{opa sign --signing-key ${{ secret.opa_key }} --bundle <bundle name>}}

** If time permits, I will try and completed the following today. 


+*OPA Sign:*+

* The ‘sign’ command generates a digital signature for policy bundles. 
* It generates a “.signatures.json” file that dictates which files should be included in the bundle, what their SHA hashes are, and is cryptographically secure.
* The signatures file is a JSON file with an array containing a single JSON Web Token (JWT) that encapsulates the signature for the bundle.
* The –signing-alg flag can be used to specify the algorithm to sign the token. The ‘sign’ command uses RS256 (by default) as the signing algorithm. See [https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/configuration/#keys|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/configuration/#keys|smart-link]  for a list of supported signing algorithms.
* The key to be used for signing the JWT MUST be provided using the –signing-key flag. 
** For for RSA family of algorithms, the command expects a PEM file containing the private key. 
** For HMAC family of algorithms (eg. HS256), the command expects a secret which can be provided using the –signing-key flag.
* OPA {{sign}} can ONLY be used with the {{--bundle}} flag to load paths that refer to existing bundle files or directories following the bundle structure.


+*OPA Run:*+

* Interactive Shell 
* The ‘run’ command can be used to verify the signature of a signed bundle:
** Example: {{$ opa run --verification-key secret --signing-alg HS256 --bundle bundle.tar.gz}}
** The -scope flag can be used to specify the scope. 



+*OPA Build:*+

* Coming back to this command and reading it again has made me re-think the approach I would take to sign and verify a bundle. 
** The ‘build’ command can be used to verify the signature of a signed bundle and also to generate a signature for the output bundle the command creates.
If the directory path(s) provided to the ‘build’ command contain a “.signatures.json” file, it will attempt to verify the signatures included in that file. The bundle files or directory path(s) to verify must be specified using –bundle.
* The above quot from the OPA Build command documentation, makes me think that I could manually sign the current bundle and check it into the repo. Then just run the {{opa build}} command with the {{--verification-key}} flag to verify incoming previous signature and sign the new bundle it is creating with {{--signing-key}} flags. 
* Testing will verify the best approach.  The shared actions documentation might bring some clarity to this process within a workflow. 
** Questions: 
*** Does the {{opa build}} --signing-key flag create the, ".signatures.json" file like the {{opa sign}} command or is this something different?
*** If I don’t sign the bundle first, but provide the {{--verification-key}} flag, will the opa build command fail or will it skip the verification since there isn’t a signatures file and proceed to build and sing the new bundle? 
*** If either case works, will I need to check the new signature back into the repository? 
* Example: {{$ opa build --verification-key /path/to/public_key.pem --signing-key /path/to/private_key.pem --bundle foo}}
* Reference:  [https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/cli/#opa-build|https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/cli/#opa-build|smart-link]
column252:
30/Aug/23 11:53 AM;6256f917cdc24000704b6536;While working on step: 

Nail down key generating specifics:

* Where the public key will live (if a key pair is used as indicated by documentation).



I went back and and re-read the documentation on signing and building. I realized that there might be more than one approaches to signing and verifying the siging.  There are two general approaches that I see so fare, with some outcomes that could dictate the outcome.  

Plan #1 Approach: 

* My first vision. Add the {{opa sign}} command to the OPA workflow(s) to sign the bundles prior to building a new bundle. 
** Questions to be asnsered with Testing (if possible):
*** If the {{opa build}} can verify existing signatures, and sign new builds, is the {{opa sign}} command even needed in the current workflows or is his something better suited with logic or in another separate workflow?
*** In stead, do we manually run this the {{opa sign}} command, in a new workflow, or with a condition in the existing workflow to generate the signatures file and check it in to the repo (if signed with a workflow). 
*** How likely can the opa shared action check update and check an updated signatures file, without adding another action or logic?

Plan #2 Approach:

* Sign the build with {{opa sign}} either with a new workflow or manually. Then add the verification and signing flags to the {{opa build}} command to verify the signatures pior to building a new bundle and then signing the new bundle. 
** Questions to be asnsered with Testing (if possible):
*** Does the {{opa build}} --signing-key flag create the, ".signatures.json" file like the {{opa sign}} command or is this something different?
*** If the files weren’t signed piror to a new build, but I still  pass the {{--verification-key}} flag, will the opa build fail or will it just skip the verification and build and sign the new build? Docs talk about the OPA being able to automatically verify a build if a signatures file exits and its been configured for signing. But it doesn’t specify if this is the {{opa build}}, {{opa run}}, or some {{opa client/service}} that does this. 
*** If either case works, will I need to check the new signature file back into the repository or will the {{opa build}} command update it and the shared action will commit it (automatically or specified). 


Then there is this AC I still don’t fully understand and needs verifying:

* The OPA agent verifies the signature
** If I use a key pair/secret pending signing algorithm used for signing where would the secret/public key live for verifying the OPA Policy Bundle? 
** Where is using OPA Agent living (or uses said agent) and how do I go about adding the secret/public key for verifying the OPA Policy Bundle? 

Its time to move to the next step and begin testing the {{opa}} commands to better understand how they work.
column253:
30/Aug/23 5:30 PM;6256f917cdc24000704b6536;*Testing Results So Far:* 

* The {{opa build}} command without without a pre-existing signing .signature.json file and consequently omitting the relative --verification-key flag from the build command doesn't error.
* The opa build skips the verification instead just signs the new bundle being create. This require me to pass the flags
** --signing-alg
** --signing-key
* The build will create a new {{.signature.json}} file at the root of the bundle.tar.gz. 
* Using the --signing-agl I can set the algorithm to {{HS256}} which allows me to use a secret (string) to sign the files with instead of using a key pair pem file. 
** This simplifies things by:
*** Reducing the number of steps needed to sign a bundle.
*** No extra steps to create key pem files.
*** No need to store a signatures file in the repo or check in one when we update the secret. 
** Instead:
*** We just sign the new bundle and put it in S3. 
*** But this does leave a gap. Do we want the source files signed first? I am not sure how the others on the team will feel about not having the source already signed prior to build time. 
*** We could sign the source files with one secret and then build and resign them with a a different secret. That way we have a signature in git created with one secret that is only used to verify the source prior to build. The would reduce risk if either secret was exposed. 


*Commands Used:*

* opa sign --signing-key secret --signing-alg HS256 --bundle ./policy
* opa build --verification-key secret --signing-alg HS256 --signing-key ItsASuperFakeSecret --bundle ./policy
* opa run --verification-key secret --signing-alg HS256 --bundle bundle.tar.gz
column254:

To determine:

** If so we may need a way to automate re-signing the files in git or skip this and only sign the bundle. Maybe we do this with a workflow that runs when a commit is made to a branch. 
* It occured to me that we may not need to re-sign on deployment and instead we just verify the signature based on the signature in Git.
** This may require automation that re-signs new policies or updated ones. This may require a workflow that runs when a feature branch is updated. The signatures file would need to be updated to be checked into the branch. 


This has been shelved for a higher priority task.

column1: Turn on Kyverno Image Policy Enforcement
column43:
*Narrative:*

In order to ensure our environment is fully compliant with SOC and ISO we want to ensure that all images are properly signed before they are deployed into our K8s clusters. Predicated on the completion of [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-875|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-875|smart-link] and [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-876|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-876|smart-link] we need to switch on Kyverno policy enforcement, by switching from “Audit“ mode to “Enforce” mode.

*AC:*

* All images in the non kube-system namespace are properly signed
* No new images can be deployed into our clusters without being properly signed

*Narrative:*

We need to coordinate across the organization to ensure that all images are properly signed. We have a ticket: [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-875|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-875|smart-link] that should have been completed before this one and consequently [Kyverno|https://kyverno.io/docs/policy-reports/], should be creating policy reports indicating, which images are in violation of the image signing policy.

*AC:*

* Generate a policy report from Kyverno showing all workloads that are in violation of the images signing protocol (excluding kube-system)
* Based on this report we need to work with the teams responsible for the images in violation of the policy to create stories to resolve the violations
* A plan/roadmap to have all images properly signed is drafted and shared

column1: Deploy Kyverno In Audit Mode to K8s
column43:
*Narrative:*

[Kyverno|https://kyverno.io/] is an open source policy engine that allows k8s administrators to enforce policy on new deployments into a k8s environment.  Initially we will be using Kyverno to enforce an image signing policy. 

We leverage Notation and AWS signer to implement signing as outlined in [this blog post|https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/containers/announcing-container-image-signing-with-aws-signer-and-amazon-eks/]. Similarly that same blog post indicates how to structure the various Kyverno Policies. 

*AC:*

* Kyverno is added to ArgoCD manifests using the official [Kyverno helm chart|https://github.com/kyverno/kyverno/blob/main/charts/kyverno/values.yaml]. 
* Kyverno is deployed in [Audit mode|https://kyverno.io/docs/policy-reports/], meaning it will report of policy violations, but not enforce them. 
* Add policies to the cluster that require all images outside of the kube-system namespace to be signed using our AWS signing profiles ([us-east-1|https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/signer/home?region=us-east-1#/signing-profiles/deepsee_container_image] & [eu-west-1|https://eu-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/signer/home?region=eu-west-1#/signing-profiles/deepsee_container_image]) for our respective regional k8s deployments
* Exclude [the kube-system|https://github.com/kyverno/kyverno/blob/26e5bd76c7b28868629f44d19f65917aa35fa309/charts/kyverno/values.yaml#L194] namespace

column43:
Findings from Mossadams Pentest:

Threat Level: Medium

*Results*:
Clickjacking is possible on pages within the web application.

*Issues*:
Attackers use clickjacking to have authenticated users unknowingly interact with website functionality, which can allow compromise of authentication details and allow the attacker to interact with the application as an authenticated user.

*Recommendations*:
Ensure all pages employ “frame-busting” techniques or, more preferably, the server-side “X-Frame- Options” HTTP header directive.

*Publicly Available Exploits: True*

Findings from Mossadams Pentest:

Threat Level: Medium

*Description:* 

The server’s X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be broken, as stated below:

First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the server might not be descended from a known public certificate authority. This can occur either when the top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed certificate, or when intermediate certificates are missing that would connect the top of the certificate chain to a known public certificate authority.

Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can occur either when the scan occurs before one of the certificate’s ‘notBefore’ dates, or after one of the certificate’s ‘notAfter’ dates.

Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature that either didn’t match the certificate’s information or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by getting the certificate with the bad signature to be re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be verified are the result of the certificate’s issuer using a signing algorithm that The Tester either does not support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.

*Recommendations*:

Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

*Additional Info:*

[https://www.itu.int/rec/T-REC-X.509/en|https://www.itu.int/rec/T-REC-X.509/en|smart-link]

column43:
*Narrative:*

Per communication from AWS, they will no longer be supporting version 11.x of Aurora Postgresql databases.  See the content of the email below.

We are currently using Aurora for legacy JPM.

Email communication here:

{noformat}Hello,

We are reaching out to let you know that newer versions of Aurora PostgreSQL are now available and that as of January 31, 2024, Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL-compatible edition will no longer support major version 11.x. Per the Aurora Version Policy [1], we have provided 12 months notice and additionally 6 months notice, to give you time to upgrade your database cluster(s). We recommend that you proactively upgrade your databases running Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL major version 11.x to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL 12 or higher at your convenience before January 31, 2024. We will send you updates and reminders throughout the year prior to the end of support deadline.

Starting on or after 12:00 PM PST on January 31, 2024, if your Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL cluster has not been upgraded, Amazon Aurora will automatically upgrade your Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x databases to the appropriate Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL version during your next scheduled maintenance window.

How to Determine Which Instances are Running Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x:

In the Amazon RDS console, you can see details about a database cluster, including the Aurora PostgreSQL version of instances in the cluster, by choosing Databases from the console's navigation pane. To view DB cluster information by using the AWS CLI, use the describe-db-clusters command. To view DB cluster information using the Amazon RDS API, use the DescribeDBClusters operation. [2] You can also query a database directly to get the version number by querying the aurora_version() system function i.e., "SELECT * FROM aurora_version();".

How to Upgrade to a New Major Version:

You can initiate an upgrade of your database instance either immediately or during your next maintenance window to a newer major version of Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL using the AWS Management Console or the AWS Command Line Interface (CLI). The upgrade process will shut down the database instance, perform the upgrade, and restart the database instance. The database instance may be restarted multiple times during the upgrade process. While major version upgrades typically complete within the standard maintenance window, the duration of the upgrade depends on the number of objects within the database. To avoid any unplanned unavailability outside your maintenance window, we recommend that you first take a snapshot [3] or a fast database clone [4] of your database and test the upgrade to get an estimate of the duration. To learn more about upgrading PostgreSQL major versions in Aurora, review the Upgrading Database Versions page [5].

Please be aware of the following timeline:
- Now through January 31, 2024 - You can initiate upgrades of Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x instances to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL 12 or higher at any time.
- Starting August 1, 2023, you will no longer be able to create new Aurora clusters or instances with Aurora PostgreSQL major version 11.x from either the AWS Console or the CLI. You can still add read replicas to existing Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x clusters and continue to apply changes to existing Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x instances, such as migrating to a Graviton2 R6g instance or changing instance configuration, until January 31, 2024.
- Starting January 31, 2024 Amazon Aurora will upgrade your Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x databases to the appropriate Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL major version during a scheduled maintenance window after January 31, 2024. Restoration of Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL 11.x database snapshots will result in an automatic upgrade of the restored database to a supported version at the time.

If you have any questions or concerns, the AWS Support Team is available on AWS re:Post [6] and via Premium Support [7].{noformat}

column1: Modify Work Items API to only accept and return a single comment in feedback
column43:
Currently our API for comments on Work Items handles the creation and management of multiple comments:

[https://curly-adventure-5egm47j.pages.github.io/#/work-items/patchWorkItemTask|https://curly-adventure-5egm47j.pages.github.io/#/work-items/patchWorkItemTask]

{noformat}{ 
  "status": "PASS",
  "comments": [
    {
      "comment": "Trade amount seemed off, I reported it to my manager who is investigating",
      "id": "1fdfb35b-8405-4874-956a-76ad09219a93"
    },
    {
      "comment": "Something is wrong with this trade"
    },
    {
      "comment": "I'm editing this comment",
      "id": "779d0c12-131c-4034-a30b-76840fb5139b"
    }
  ],
  "isFlagged": true
}{noformat}

*>> This is not AC, this is just an example of current behavior*


However, it appears the UI isn’t using the API this way. Instead, they only display a single comment at a time, which is the most recent based on the time created, with no ability to modify an existing comment. This way of treating comments seems to be more desirable to product since it essentially preserves an audit history.

If this is the case, then we should update our API to match this behavior. 

----

*Acceptance Criteria*

* When updating the status of a work item task then only accept a single comment in the request.
* Each comment is treated as immutable; it cannot be modified after creation.
* When work items are returned from the API and if they contain feedback with comments then only return the latest comment based on time created.

column1: deepseeai/mlp:pyproject.toml - Remote Code Execution (RCE) in reportlab
column43:
[reportlab|https://pypi.org/project/reportlab/] is a Python library for generating PDFs and graphics.

Affected versions of this package are vulnerable to Remote Code Execution (RCE) due to insufficient checks in the ‘rl_safe_eval’ function. Attackers can inject malicious code into an HTML file that will later be converted to PDF using software that relies on the ReportLab library. To exploit the vulnerability, the entire malicious code must be executed with eval in a single expression.

*Note:*

This exploit is possible only if users allow hostile input to be passed into {{colors}} - for example if accepting the URL of an HTML page someone else had written, with a generic conversion routine.

[More about this issue|https://app.snyk.io/vuln/SNYK-PYTHON-REPORTLAB-5664897]

[Vulnerability in deepseeai/mlp:pyproject.toml|https://app.snyk.io/org/deepsee-ai-pilot-org/project/db26c07e-0fdb-42ae-b8f9-19407448e149#issue-SNYK-PYTHON-REPORTLAB-5664897]

Introduced through: reportlab

CVSS Vector: CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H/E:P
CVSS Score: 9.8

*Why do we do it (context):*

There are lots of things that can go wrong when routing data to and in DeepSee. Users' systems may not always send data as intended to DeepRecon and/or DeepPilot. Deals may be sent multiple times incorrectly as duplicates. The wrong deals may be sent.

Or I could send deals and they fail to generate the desired output in DeepRecon.

Emails could get incorrectly routed to the wrong category and then create the wrong work item.

*What we need to do (outcome):*

As a user of DeepRecon, I want to be able to reroute an email or attachment if it is sent to the wrong category or content map to ensure I get the right information in my work item and the correct categorization in the future.

We need a way to reconcile what was sent versus what was processes and/or categorized.

If incorrect data is sent, we need the way to easily pause it being processed, the ability to purge it, and to purge data that has already been processed.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Ability to route a work item to a different process model
* Recategorize emails, which creates a new work item and purges the old one
* Models learn from these updates
* Can pause feeds if bad data is being sent
* Ability to reconcile what was sent versus what was processed
