*Why do we do it (context):*

As a DeepSee user, I want to be able to connect emails directly to DeepPilot for extraction and work items creation. Not all users will need or want to classify emails via DeepRecon.

*What we need to do (outcome):*

DeepPilot will need to be able to ingest an email directly and be able to extract data from the email and from the attachment without it being separated beforehand. This will allow for user to use these sources together or separately in the process model. The user will need to tell DeepPilot how to map these inputs to the correct process model.  

h3. *When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*
* The template needs to be able to recognize the format of the attachment and extract from it using the right training and/or tool.
* The template should be able to support attachments of emails, word docs, PDFs, Excel Spreadsheets, JSON Files, and XML Files.
* Dynamic number of sources
* Inputs routed to the correct process based on user rules 
* Note Eventually I want to support images and PowerPoint slides.

DeepRecon and A4A needs  access to a variety of sampling and decoding techniques, so that I can improve the quality and diversity of the outputs generated by my language models.

‌

The platform should provide access to a range of sampling and decoding techniques, including greedy search, beam search, top-k sampling, and nucleus sampling. Each technique should be configurable, with options to adjust hyperparameters such as temperature, beam size, and sampling cutoffs. The platform should also support a variety of language models, including recurrent neural networks (RNNs), transformers, and GPT models.

‌

The platform should provide a unified interface for managing and deploying different sampling and decoding techniques, with a focus on usability and flexibility. The platform should also provide tools for monitoring and evaluating the outputs generated by different techniques, with the ability to track metrics such as perplexity, coherence, and diversity.

‌

The platform should be platform-independent, allowing for use with a variety of programming languages and machine learning libraries. The platform should also be compatible with a range of data formats, including text, audio, and image data.

‌

The platform should encourage experimentation with different sampling and decoding techniques, and provide tools for visualizing and interpreting the outputs generated by different models. The platform should also allow for the integration of external datasets and models to improve the diversity and relevance of the generated outputs. Finally, the platform should support the development of new sampling and decoding techniques, and allow for the customization of existing techniques to suit specific use cases.

‌

As a user of DeepRecon powered by FILBert, I want to have a platform that supports the integration of multiple machine learning models so that I can combine the strengths of different models to improve the accuracy and effectiveness of the results that we push to our users through DeepRecon or templates.

‌

The platform should allow for the easy integration of multiple machine learning models, including both supervised and unsupervised learning models, such as decision trees, neural networks, support vector machines, and clustering algorithms. The platform should provide a unified interface for managing and deploying multiple models, with a focus on flexibility and ease of use.

‌

The platform should provide tools for monitoring and managing the performance of multiple models, with a dashboard that provides real-time feedback on model accuracy and effectiveness. The platform should also provide tools for version control and collaboration, allowing multiple data scientists to work together to integrate and optimize models.

‌

The platform should be platform-independent, allowing for use with a wide range of programming languages and machine learning libraries. The platform should also be compatible with various data sources and storage systems, including both structured and unstructured data.

‌

The platform should support the exploration and experimentation of different model combinations and configurations, allowing data scientists to test and refine models in a flexible and scalable way. The platform should provide tools for data visualization and interpretation, allowing data scientists to gain insights into the behavior and performance of multiple models. The platform should also support the integration of emerging machine learning techniques and models, allowing data scientists to stay up-to-date with the latest advances in the field.

The input prompts should cover a wide range of financial operations, including but not limited to budgeting, forecasting, financial statement analysis, risk management, and investment analysis. They should be written in clear and concise language that is specific to financial use cases within capital market customers, with a focus on providing accurate and actionable information. The input prompts should be easily updated so that we can reflect changing financial trends and regulations.

The input prompts should be organized in a logical and intuitive way, with categories and tags that allow users to quickly find the prompts they need. They should be accessible through a user-friendly interface that allows for easy browsing and searching. The input prompts should be exportable to various formats, including CSV and Excel, to facilitate integration with other financial analysis tools.

‌

The input prompts should be platform-independent, allowing for use with a wide range of generative language models and other financial analysis software systems. They should be compatible with various financial data sources, including public financial data, internal financial data, and industry-specific financial data.

‌

The input prompts should be designed to encourage creativity and innovation in financial analysis and reporting. They should be curated and organized in a way that allows users to generate new and unique insights and ideas. The input prompts should be scalable, allowing for the addition of new prompts as needed to reflect changing financial needs and priorities.

column43:
*Why do we do it (context):*

It’s about “Trust.” 

The term "trust services" is used in ISO 27001 and SOC 2 to refer to the controls and processes that an organization puts in place to protect its information assets. These controls can be technical, such as firewalls and intrusion detection systems, or they can be procedural, such as employee training and security policies.

By implementing trust services, an organization can demonstrate to its customers, partners, and regulators that it is committed to protecting their information. This can help to build trust and confidence in the organization, and it can also help to reduce the risk of data breaches and other security incidents.

*What we need to do (outcome):*

Review and define (automated) technical controls for the following “Trust Services” for [DeepSee.ai|http://DeepSee.ai] internal and customer delivery operations.

* Observability
** Logging and monitoring (security and baselining)
*** Root cause analysis/troubleshooting
**** Incident response and forensics
*** Correlate all logging events 
*** Significant events need to be logged
**** Customer usage patterns
**** Data in/out, person accesses
* Change management controls
** 100% CD by EOY
** Don’t ever touch Production without a Jira ticket
*** No changes without:
**** Request
***** Change implementation details/type/risk-level
**** Peer review  
**** Approval / Change Board (ops/sec/infra/app)
* Vulnerability management
** SLA management/enforcement (critical/high…)
*** Code- GitHub, Snyk
*** Cloud- CrowdStrike in all environments
**** Penetration testing 

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* Observability
** Logging is able to support root-cause analysis for:
*** Infrastructure security and forensics
*** Application troubleshooting to the customer level
*** Customer data accounting
* Change management
** All changes to PROD are documented, tracked, and approved
** Security review process is implemented and enforced
* Vulnerability management
** Vulnerability management process is implemented and enforced
** Vulnerabilities are remediated within the SLA for Production

*Why do we do it (context):*

Almost all checks are double checked in banks to decrease the chance of a mistake.  In order to get customers more comfortable with the manual aspects of their process in DeepSee, they would like to implement a double check. We want to enable our platform to allow for these checks as required.  

*What we need to do (outcome):*

As a DeepSee user, I want the ability to implement an approval process in particular situations:

* When the annotation is changed as part of a work item task
** We want to flag that annotation to be second checked by process manager/process designer before it is used in model training
* When work item task is flagged as incorrect extraction but not correct
** This should be flagged to a process manager/process designer to review until it is used in model training
* When a work item task outcome (pass or fail) is changed
* Users should be able to propose additions to lists
** When the comment of “These values should be added to the equivalence list” those should be routed for approval before adding to lists
* Users could propose changes to structured mapping

All data needs to be retained to support audit.

h3. *When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

h3. *Context:*
* DeepPilot processes and stores text-based data and stores the raw text in the graph and the embedding vectors in a vector database. 
* When a user types a text search into the search box in DeepPilot, a text embedding is created and a distance calculation is run against the search text embedding and all vectors in the vector database. 
* The initial search string may contain additional points of metadata which will refine or filter the search that may include data classes, start date times, end date times. The search string will be parsed and the important points of metadata will be extracted to further refine the semantic search. 
** Example: If the search phrase contains the phrase: 
*** “All emails from BlackRock and Millenium this Month about DK Trades that involved the NY FI MO Mailbox”
** The search parsing function would extract “Blackrock” and “Millenium” as counterparties, “this month” as the first and last days of June 2023 and “NY FI MO Mailbox” as a mailbox.
* Once the string has been correctly parsed and metadata is separated from the rest of the search string, the metadata point will be included as parameters in the search function and the rest of the string will become an embedding and used in the distance calculation to retrieve the top matching results from the semantic search. 

h3. Acceptance Criteria:
* Type in text related to the fields captured in DeepGraph.
* Translates that into sorted query to pre-populate the bubble chart navigation.
** e.g., “All emails from BlackRock and Millenium this Month about DK Trades that involved the NY FI MO Mailbox”
* Results in a bubble picture of emails:
** only from BlackRock and Millenium
** Only with NY FI MO mailbox in TO: or FROM:
** Process must be DK Trades

‌

Note: this needs to work for both Process Automation and Process Discovery

column1: Update Rules for how Feedback is used for Training
column43:
As a Process Designer who approves data to be used for training the modes that are used in my templating processes, I only want validated feedback to be sent back to the model for training.

Feedback is considered valid under one of the following conditions:

# In the Content Map Screen, I explicitly mark an annotation as correct.
# An annotation is used in a Work Item and the Work Item has been completed (indicating that the user has reviewed the output).

If neither of these conditions are met, the annotation should be considered unverified and should not be used for training the next iteration of the model.

Why are we doing this?

Two reasons:

# This helps ensure that only validated data is used for training. If a Work Item does not use all the terms in a content map (which SHOULD NOT happen, but reportedly does), then we can be sure we are not sending data back to the model for training that has not actually ever been reviewed.
# While #1 is considered a nice to have, the primary reason for doing this is for multi-issuance. In multi-issuance a Term Sheet has multiple assets that each have their own XML document. That means the term sheet is uploaded to reconcile against each XML. However only the data in the term sheet that is associated with each corresponding XML will be validated, as shown in the diagram below:


!mi (1118de66-c0c7-4d2f-b81a-b42e9839d0a7).png|width=80.35935563816605%!

Note that the amount value for trade 222 is incorrect. However, since trade 111 and trade 333 do not explicitly use that value, by defaulting the unused trade value as valid feedback, this multi-issuance use case will instead provide two instances of positive feedback for a back use case to the training model. Same for the trade date of 333.

Acceptance Criteria:

* Feedback is only marked as valid when it is explicitly verified by the user or used in a Work Item and passed, as stated above.
* ML Needs to be able to aggregate data by similar documents (256 hash?)

As an Analyst using Templates, I want to be able to Archive (soft delete) a Work Item that I do not intend to complete. Archived Work Items will not longer be returned when calling `GET /workItems`, but will still exist in the database for auditing purposes.

Acceptance Criteria

* I can Archive a Work Item that has not been completed and it will no longer be returned by the `GET /workitems` API.
* Content Maps associated with a Archived Work Item are still visible in the Content Map Screen.

*As a user,* I want

*So that*,

column1: Add safeguards to prevent dangerous calculation expressions
column43:
A document collection with the collection id {{384f80df-6b39-4538-8ccf-e75fa63eec7a}} was uploaded for a checklist with id {{01a3036f-1a8e-4b49-8916-9af07662a3df}} which included a checklist item with this calculation:

{noformat}flatten([(if ((if (`xml`.`notional-amount`.VALUE != null) then `xml`.`notional-amount`.VALUE else `xml`.`notional-amount`.RAW) + 3 = 0) then ([]) else (for i in 1..((if (`xml`.`notional-amount`.VALUE != null) then `xml`.`notional-amount`.VALUE else `xml`.`notional-amount`.RAW) + 3) return (if (`xml`.`trade-date`.VALUE != null) then `xml`.`trade-date`.VALUE else `xml`.`trade-date`.RAW)))]){noformat}

The value of {{`xml`.`notional-amount`.RAW}} was 2000000, which means the formula ended up trying to create an array with 2,000,003 elements. Checklist processing never finished, although it didn’t error out either.

But, it would be possible to create equations that produce massive amounts of data that would slow things down, or run an infinite loop, or other bad things, either through accident or malicious intent. We need to add some safeguards to prevent the calculation expressions from causing problems for the system.

Acceptance Criteria

* Prevent long running feel expressions from running too long.
* Ensure when this happens that the error is recorded.

column1: Trigger Pre-Processing and Training Pipelines From Automation
column43:
*Narrative:*

Currently the entire training pipeline is triggered from local engineer’s machines where they run a script [+called pipeline.py+|https://github.com/deepseeai/mlrig-mlops-pipeline/blob/861fd5d0631d0340f154f952540823855c6aedb0/src/pipelines/mlops_pipelines/bros_token_classifier/pipeline.py#L4] this pipeline triggers the pre-processing step and then subsequently triggers the training pipeline in sage maker. In order to support training with multiple tenants with federated learning we need to ensure that each tenant’s pre-processing step is completed before the training steps are begun. 

We also want to move away from manually triggering these jobs from developer machines to triggering these jobs in a deterministic way.

*AC:*

* A job is created that allows for an ml engineer to trigger the training process across all the tenants in our environment
* The job created should ensure that all pre-processing steps are finished before any training steps are triggered
* The steps in the job include:
** pre-processing 
** training
** eval
* The pipeline should be synchronous and linear, meaning that no training jobs are started until all pre-processing steps are complete.

column1: Technical Enablement and Technical Debt Bucket for Process Automation Back End Team
column43:
This epic is a catch all bucket for Technical Debt and Technical Enablement stories for Process Automation Back End. The stories added to this bucket may be small stories, or may need to be broken out into their own epics. The purpose of this bucket is to ensure these stories are captured so that as Engineering is enabled to work on these stories they can be pulled from this bucket.

Technical Debt is a term used to describe the shortcuts made by engineering during the development process that slow down engineering's ability to maintain, troubleshoot, extend, or add features to a product, system, or process over time. It is named such because – like financial debt – it tends to compound over time, making it harder to improve the code base the longer the debt is “worked around” by the engineers.

If Technical Debt is like financial debt, then Technical Enablement is like an investment. Technical Enablement is a term used to describe work performed by engineering that will speed up their development process.

Technical Debt and Technical Enablement are generally categorized together as the value they provide to the customer is indirect. The outcome of Technical Debt and Technical Enablement is faster and higher quality delivery times to the customer.

column1: Broken Pipe on "long running" API calls
column43:
Initially noticed this error in the extractor service logs relative to when there was a large number or work_item_tasks being calculated to populate the header data
It appears that once this error occurs, we don’t seem to recover from it, or all API endpoints seem to throw the exception.
The error itself indicates that the connection was closed by the client - and in this case we believe the client is Istio - which has a 90 second timeout
We need to investigate, probably with input from infra, if this is a condition that we can recover from more gracefully or if it is an indicator of the pod becoming unhealthy and needs to be evicted and reloaded, or something else entirely

Some additional info on how we may want/need to handle this error in Spring is available here:
[https://mtyurt.net/post/spring-how-to-handle-ioexception-broken-pipe.html|https://mtyurt.net/post/spring-how-to-handle-ioexception-broken-pipe.html|smart-link]

column1: Override Pass/Fail if Term confidence is below a certain threshold
column43:
As a manager using DeepRecon, I want to make sure that I don’t get any “false passes” due to an incorrect extraction with low confidence that makes it seem like something is correct when it’s not.

I only expect my users to actively investigate any checklist items with a “fail” or “null” result - if the result is “pass”, they will assume that everything is okay. I want to make sure that if the term going into the checklist item has low confidence, it still gets reviewed.

If the predicted result is “fail”, confidence doesn’t matter

If the predicted result is “null”, confidence doesn’t matter

If the predicted result is “pass” but the confidence for any term is low, the result should be “null” instead of “pass” due to low confidence

There should be some indicator that it needs to be reviewed due to low confidence

Once the user updates the low-confidence term, then the result is whatever the result would be with re-execution (no more override, “pass” is permitted)

Acceptance Criteria:

# In a given work item, if a term extraction confidence is less than x%, all checklist items that use that term have a NULL or FAIL result even if the result of the FEEL is PASS
# If a user corrects the term extraction, the confidence is considered as 100% for the corrected term and PASS can be returned
# The PASS result based on low-confidence extractions is returned as well as the “low-confidence override” NULL result (in the UI, I would want the predicted result to say PASS but the icon to be the amber exclamation point)
# User (process designer/process manager) can set the confidence threshold at the Process Model level (configuration of the process model as a whole)



Nice to have:

* Extra extra bonus - it only takes into account terms that were actually used based on the execution tracing. So if my checklist item logic is If A is found then A else B, and A is found with high confidence, then the confidence of B does not need to be considered. But if A is not found and it returns B, then the confidence of both A and B should be considered.
column265: Use confidence level in Process Model

column1: Store date terms as String in Context
column43:
As a Process Designer, I need to be able to test my calculations with fake data to ensure they are working correctly. There is a screen on the UI that allows me to provide fake values in a JSON context to send to the backend to execute a calculation.

Unfortunately, this context cannot accept all data types supported by FEEL, namely dates. This means that instead of adding {{date("2023-01-01")}} to the context, we instead have to add the String {{"2023-01-01"}} to the context and the calculation must wrap the value with the {{date}} function in the expression itself.

The Backend needs to be updated to store Terms of type Date in the Factor Resolver context as Strings instead of dates so that the UI does not need to generate different expressions for testing vs execution.



Acceptance Criteria:

* The UI does not have to provide a different FEEL expression for testing with a context vs executing a checklist item calculation when using dates. i.e. The expression {{date(some-date-term)}} should be testable from the {{/feel}} endpoint and be executable to generate a work item task.
column250: 12/Jun/23 9:27 AM;62320e211dcf800070e976c5;A consequence of storing all the dates as strings is that the final result of calculations will be strings instead of dates. Which means that when doing comparisons for reconciliations, validations and subgroup matching, we need to handle string to date comparisons. Alternatively, I think it would also work if we checked the result of all calculations and tried converting it to a date if possible.

column43:
h2. Details

A cross-site scripting attack occurs when the attacker tricks a legitimate web-based application or site to accept a request as originating from a trusted source.

This is done by escaping the context of the web application; the web application then delivers that data to its users along with other trusted dynamic content, without validating it. The browser unknowingly executes malicious script on the client side (through client-side languages; usually JavaScript or HTML)  in order to perform actions that are otherwise typically blocked by the browser's Same Origin Policy.

Injecting malicious code is the most prevalent manner by which XSS is exploited; for this reason, escaping characters in order to prevent this manipulation is the top method for securing code against this vulnerability.

Escaping means that the application is coded to mark key characters, and particularly key characters included in user input, to prevent those characters from being interpreted in a dangerous context. For example, in HTML, {{<}} can be coded as  {{&lt}}; and {{>}} can be coded as {{&gt}}; in order to be interpreted and displayed as themselves in text, while within the code itself, they are used for HTML tags. If malicious content is injected into an application that escapes special characters and that malicious content uses {{<}} and {{>}} as HTML tags, those characters are nonetheless not interpreted as HTML tags by the browser if they've been correctly escaped in the application code and in this way the attempted attack is diverted.

The most prominent use of XSS is to steal cookies (source: OWASP HttpOnly) and hijack user sessions, but XSS exploits have been used to expose sensitive information, enable access to privileged services and functionality and deliver malware.

h3. Types of attacks

There are a few methods by which XSS can be manipulated:

||Type||Origin||Description||
|_Stored_|Server|The malicious code is inserted in the application (usually as a link) by the attacker. The code is activated every time a user clicks the link.|
|_Reflected_|Server|The attacker delivers a malicious link externally from the vulnerable web site application to a user. When clicked, malicious code is sent to the vulnerable web site, which reflects the attack back to the user's browser.|
|_DOM-based_|Client|The attacker forces the user's browser to render a malicious page. The data in the page itself delivers the cross-site scripting data.|
|_Mutated_||The attacker injects code that appears safe, but is then rewritten and modified by the browser, while parsing the markup. An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted parameters.|

h3. Affected environments

The following environments are susceptible to an XSS attack:

* Web servers
* Application servers
* Web application environments

h3. How to prevent

This section describes the top best practices designed to specifically protect your code:

* Sanitize data input in an HTTP request before reflecting it back, ensuring all data is validated, filtered or escaped before echoing anything back to the user, such as the values of query parameters during searches.
* Convert special characters such as {{?}}, {{&}}, {{/}}, {{<}}, {{>}} and spaces to their respective HTML or URL encoded equivalents.
* Give users the option to disable client-side scripts.
* Redirect invalid requests.
* Detect simultaneous logins, including those from two separate IP addresses, and invalidate those sessions.
* Use and enforce a Content Security Policy (source: Wikipedia) to disable any features that might be manipulated for an XSS attack.
* Read the documentation for any of the libraries referenced in your code to understand which elements allow for embedded HTML.

column250:
13/Mar/23 11:23 AM;6256f917cdc24000704b6536;h2. AWS Managed Rule Group that are free of charge:


+*Amazon IP Reputation List*+
This group contains rules that are based on Amazon threat intelligence. This is useful if you would like to block sources associated with bots or other threats.

+*Anonymous IP List*+
This group contains rules that allow you to block requests from services that allow obfuscation of viewer identity. This can include request originating from VPN, proxies, Tor nodes, and hosting providers. This is useful if you want to filter out viewers that may be trying to hide their identity from your application.

+*Known Bad Inputs*+
Contains rules that allow you to block request patterns that are known to be invalid and are associated with exploitation or discovery of vulnerabilities. This can help reduce the risk of a malicious actor discovering a vulnerable application.

+*Linux Operating System*+
Contains rules that block request patterns associated with exploitation of vulnerabilities specific to Linux, including LFI attacks. This can help prevent attacks that expose file contents or execute code for which the attacker should not have had access.

+*SQL Database*+
Contains rules that allow you to block request patterns associated with exploitation of SQL databases, like SQL injection attacks. This can help prevent remote injection of unauthorized queries.

column1: Failure to receive Acknowledgement of Receipt from Destination
column43: User should be made aware of Failure to Receive Acknowledgement of Receipt from intended desination.

DeepSee support should be made aware of failure to Authenticate security keys so they can resolve, User should be made aware of the error and be given an indication that DeepSee has been notified to look into the issue.

column1: Failure to Process and when reprocessing not creating a duplicate record
column43: System should not create duplicate records when attempting to process data again after a failure of process error
User should be made aware of a failure to process transmission of data
User should be made aware of a failure to receive transmission of data
User should have subtle notification of succesful transmission of data

*Why do we do it (Context):*

We need both internal and external error handling for the data integration gateway. SME’s should be notified of errors when using DIG with options to escalate to DeepSee team in the event a retry doesn’t fix the issue.

*What we need to do (Outcome):*

Error Handling supported will consist of errors for Identifying succesful transmission, failure to receive, failure to process, failure to process and when reprocessing not creating duplicate record, failure to authenticate, and failure to receive acknowledgement of receipt from destination.

*When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*

DIG should identify successful transmissions, failure to receive, failure to process, not create duplicate records when reprocessing, failure to authenticate, and failure to receive acknowledgement of receipt from destination. Users should be clearly notified of what errors were thrown.

column1: Exporting Data - Transmit the data as defined
column43: Add API Export. Include a method to verify message was received/processed (ACK/NAK). Include a method to mark input data as 'Process success" as not to re-process (2x records). Include a "circuit-breaker" to identify connectivity, misconfiguration, or possible attack.
Ensure that the security keys are validated and maintainable by the customer. This will be executed by a separate technology RBAC entitlement and not the normal SME user.
Transform/Package the data into the pre-defined format (API, Structured Message, .CSV, etc.). This must conform to the connector being used and could be constraints defined per connector.
Identify what data will be transmitted from the what the executed template has created (e.g. Completed trade reconciliation from Post-Trade OTC Confirmation)

*Why do we do it (Context):*

The Dig should allow for secure and flexible transmission of customer and required 3rd party data to and from the DeepSee DataRig. This includes ingesting all data required for a template to be completed and then being able to export the results to another system to drive workflow or to capture results. Ingesting data can be both files used for single template executions or files of data used for many template executions.

*What we need to do (Outcome):*

Export ‘templates’ should be independent of the process/app templates. Export templates should be reusable across process app templates (e.g., JPM ingress sFTP applies to OTC confirmation and OTC affirmation templates).When Exporting Data there are four main steps: 

1) Identify what data will be transmitted 

2) Transform/Package data 

3) Verify Security 

4) Transmit Data
Saved in a _Temporary_ place, where the data is inspected to ensure it is safe (no viruses or malware), complete, and in the expected format.

column1: Address Developer Direct Access to Production Data
column43:
*Narrative:* 


Sometimes developers need access to production databases, and currently we only have one set of credentials for each database that gives full root privileges on the database. This is obviously not ideal as it creates the potential for data loss



*AC:*

* Have an endpoint in Hashicorp’s database backend that allows for provisioning users that can be granted access on various tables
* Create a separate user for Hashicorp to be able to provision users in the database and grant privileges on tables
* The credentials should not have a time to live longer than two days
* The credentials that are issued should be read-only access to the data 
* Restrict Developer access in Production Vault
* Enable audit logging to track access





Recent Scenario: 

* Margret came to me recently asking me to validate the DeepRecon Markets Database creds stored in our production Vault. She needed access to JPMs production data to troubleshoot and fix a bug. We don’t currently have a solution for this scenario. This a placeholder to go back and address this access issue. Developers should not have direct access to production or have system user credentials, e.g., mlp_db user.

column1: Deleting Incomplete Multipart Uploads to Lower Amazon S3 Costs
column43:
Incomplete multipart uploads to S3 buckets are not automatically deleted.  Currently we have around 20 gig worth of incomplete uploads that will stick around until we manually delete.

As part of setting up S3 backups, bucket versioning and lifecycle was setup on the ‘output' and 'assets’ buckets, which will automatically delete failed multipart uploads after 7 days.  but for the other buckets this is not setup.

We need to figure out what buckets need to be cleaned up.  Here is an aws article showing how to do this.

[https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws-cloud-financial-management/discovering-and-deleting-incomplete-multipart-uploads-to-lower-amazon-s3-costs/|https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws-cloud-financial-management/discovering-and-deleting-incomplete-multipart-uploads-to-lower-amazon-s3-costs/]

column1: Update Term Definitions to Download Correct Form
column43:
We are experiencing a problem where the term_definitions.csv is pulling in inaccurate data from the DB. For example, in the DB some terms are “Units” (Column B in CSV), but appear as “Array” within the actual CSV after the query. 

We need to explore why this is happening and remediate it. We believe that when it queries the DB, if it's a subgroup, it will automatically pull it as an array and that is incorrect.

column1: [Placeholder] Training Pipelines are Moved into Kubernetes
column43:
*Narrative:*

We currently leverage AWS native solutions in Sagemaker to train our ML models. In order to support full vendor cloud agnosticism we need to move these training processes into a Kubernetes native solution like KubeFlow or ArgoWorkflows
column265: Machine Learning Components are Moved Into Kubernetes

column1: Machine Learning Components are Moved Into Kubernetes
column43:
+*Context*+

Moving all components into Kubernetes will involve porting over services related to our machine learning processes into our Kubernetes cluster.

+*Outcomes*+

* Standardizing all ML  components into Kubernetes will enable faster cycles for the ML team
* We will have fully vendor agnostic machine learning capabilities giving us the greatest flexibility for cloud portability

+*Definition of Done*+

* ML models can be trained outside of Sagemaker
* Deploying ML models per tenant involves deploying into the tenant namespace in kubernetes
* No components in AWS are required for training machine learning models

column1: Add Automated Backups to RDS in PROD
column43:
h3. +*Context:*+

Currently automated backups are disabled for all RDS databases in the production aws account. This is bad.

h3. +*Acceptance Criteria:*+

* All RDS databases in the production aws account (612311616130) have back ups enabled via [terraform|https://github.com/deepseeai/infra-platform/blob/0105de0a0beedb215cd68c8698b4a914462adad8/aws/tenant/modules/deeprecon/rds.tf]
* Retention period is 7 days
* Backups are encrypted
* If applicable, time window for backups should be between 5 UTC and 7 UTC

column1: [Datascience Laboratory] We need to create read only access users for relevant data inside of production systems for the purposes of model training
column43:
*Narrative:*

Currently inside of the Datascience Laboratory the datascience team has access to a read/write user in production, which presents an intolerable risk to our data integrity. For the purposes of training the data science team should only have read access to a narrow subset of the database.

*AC:*

* We have a readonly access user created in the database
* A secret is created for the user in AWS on a standard rotational basis
* Identify which database tables are absolutely necessary for the ML team to be able to limit read access to those databases
column265: A sandbox environment for the ML team to train and test their models with production data

column1: Update the Inference Pipeline To Leverage the New Endpoint Proxy
column43:
*Narrative:*

As a part of our overall work to move the pipelines [inference|https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/states/home?region=us-east-1#/statemachines/view/arn:aws:states:us-east-1:138097994451:stateMachine:dev-mlp-inference] and [pre-processing|https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/states/home?region=us-east-1#/statemachines/view/arn:aws:states:us-east-1:138097994451:stateMachine:dev-mlp-preprocessing-pipeline] we have a story [https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-640|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/browse/IR-640|smart-link] to move that proxy layer into a service in Kubernetes. Once we have moved this endpoint proxy into Kubernetes we will need to update the inference pipeline to consume that endpoint rather than directly invoking the [lambda|https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/lambda/home?region=us-east-1#/functions/dev-prediction-middleware?tab=code] that exists today.



*AC:*

* The existing inference pipeline is changed to call out to the new service that is deployed into Kubernetes
* The existing inference pipeline has this change promoted throughout the environments
column265: Achieving cloud agnostic infrastructure will require we port over Step Functions out of AWS

column1: Move The Endpoint Proxy Out Of Lambda And Into Kubernetes
column43:
*Narrative:*

We have [a lambda|https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/lambda/home?region=us-east-1#/functions/dev-prediction-middleware?tab=code] that proxies requests to our Sagemaker endpoints for the purposes of performing data post processing on predictions returned from Sagemaker. This lambda [executes the code found here|https://github.com/deepseeai/mlrig-mlops-pipeline/blob/master/src/apps/mlrig_lambdas/prediction_middleware/app.py] In order to complete the porting over of our inference and pre-processing pipelines into Argo Workflows and Kubernetes we will need this proxy to be a service in Kubernetes for each Tenant. 

*AC:*

* This proxy updated to be a Kubernetes deployment
* The proxy is available at a relevant domain for each tenant
* The proxy can be ran locally using Tilt pointing at an endpoint in Sagemaker Dev
* The proxy is deployed through an automated processes leveraging ArgoCD and Github Workflows
column265: Achieving cloud agnostic infrastructure will require we port over Step Functions out of AWS

column1: Update data_validation function to not implement MDLZ read_validation_csv() functionality
column43:
{{validation_csv_bytes = read_from_s3(assets_bucket, validation_csv_key)}} was saying there is NoSuchKey error. This is called by {{validate_terms()}} which in turn calls {{self._validate_term_with_csv}} passing the {{validation_dict.get("default_value")}} and {{validation_dict.get("validation_csv_key")}} from {{self.config["terms"]}} for {{assets_bucket}} and {{validation_csv_key}} in the above function; line 194 in {{mlp_lambda_helpers/inference/data_validation/data_validation.py}}



In discussions with Seth, we determined this functionality was in place for MDLZ aspects that is no longer needed in current workflows. We have made it work with our current codebase by making small tweaks, but those are difficult to maintain (as shown in the above error with a config file not being copied over into PROD), so we want to get rid of it.

column43:
h3. Context

Messaging is the general name for a paradigm that allows for services to communicate over a message bus. This allows for a decoupled architecture and the sharing of data in a way that is independent from where or how it is consumed. Messaging is a critical part of most modern application ecosystems.

We currently leverage [Amazon’s SQS|https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/welcome.html] for the predominance of our messaging. This is a proprietary solution that is not portable between cloud vendors. In order to become fully cloud agnostic we will need to implement solutions that can easily be ported between major cloud vendors.

h3. Outcome

* Another component of our infrastructure will be moved into toolchain that is cloud agnostic
* Testing data flows with a messaging solution can more easily be done locally, thereby reducing costs associated with development and testing in the cloud

h3. Definition of Done

* All messaging is implemented using a cloud agnostic solution like [Kafka|https://kafka.apache.org/]
* Messaging infrastructure can be provisioned locally on a Kubernetes cluster using Tilt and Kind
* Changes to messaging infrastructure can be deployed using a standard set of tools including Github Workflows and ArgoCD

column1: To achieve full cloud agnosticism we should replace sagemaker with an open source solutin
column43:
h3. Context

We currently leverage [Amazon’s Sagemaker|https://aws.amazon.com/pm/sagemaker/?trk=8987dd52-6f33-407a-b89b-a7ba025c913c&sc_channel=ps&s_kwcid=AL!4422!3!532502995192!e!!g!!amazon%20sagemaker&ef_id=Cj0KCQiA14WdBhD8ARIsANao07hPg0LaQUUF3chVKJfG1evyTM6yJ9BsizNySdhK4v58ImeWJACX5tYaAplEEALw_wcB:G:s&s_kwcid=AL!4422!3!532502995192!e!!g!!amazon%20sagemaker] for our ML pipelines. Because Sagemaker is not portable between clouds in order to be fully cloud agnostic we will need a solution that allows for training of models without a vendor specific solution. 

Through a combination of open source technologies including MLFlow, ArgoWorkflows, and Kubeflow we can  replace sagemaker to be fully cloud agnostic and portable between cloud providers

h3. Outcome

* Machine learning processes will no longer be reliant on proprietary services 
* End to end ML models will can be run in a Kubernetes native environment

h3. Definition of Done

* All machine learning processes and workflows are done in a cloud agnostic way leveraging open source technologies
* Standardized build and deploy processes using a combination of open source cloud native solutions
column166: Replace Sagemaker With Cloud Native Solution

column1: Create shared function libraries for tilt
column43: Tilt supports writing functions and putting them in a file that can be loaded by other Tiltfiles. It would be good to refactor some of our current logic into functions and have it be loaded as a shared library e.g. have the base data objects (psql, mongodb, etc) be loaded by a shared function and then the datalab Tiltfile could just load that

column1: Remove resources controlled by operators on a tilt down
column43: On a {{tilt down}} is doesn’t look like tilt is operator aware meaning that tilt will delete the custom resource after the operator has been removed. This puts the custom resource in a state of “deleting” but there isn’t any finalizer to actually delete it. This causes issues the next time a {{tilt up}} is run, because once the operator is back up and running, the resource does get deleted and tilt doesn’t know to reapply it

column1: Deeprecon UI Is Fully Running In Our Clusters
column43:
h3. *Context*

The Deeprecon UI is currently running in AWS and being served out of an S3 bucket. In order to achieve fully cloud agnostic infrastructure we will want to run the UI out of our Kubernetes clusters

h3. Outcomes

* Running the UI from Kubernetes will allow for easier local development of the application in a production like setting locally
* Build and deployment processes will be standardized to be consistent with other components in our environment
* One more service will be ported over to a cloud agnostic platform allowing for services to be run across multiple cloud providers

h3. *Definition of Done*

* All UI services are served out of a Kubernetes cluster in each of the respective environments: local, dev, stage, and production
* The build and deployment process for the UI is consistent with other services and is completed using a combination of Github Workflows and ArgoCD
* The UI is ran locally leveraging Tilt and a Kubernetes Kind Cluster
column166: Port Over Remaining DeepRecon UI Components

column1: Achieving cloud agnostic infrastructure will require we port over Step Functions out of AWS
column43:
*Context*

We currently leverage [step functions|https://aws.amazon.com/step-functions/] in AWS to build processing pipelines. Step functions are AWS native components and will need to be replaced in order to achieve cloud agnosticism. We currently have a pattern leveraging [Argo Workflows|https://argoproj.github.io/argo-workflows/] to achieve a cloud native solution in Kubernetes

Aside from achieving cloud agnostic infrastructure porting over step functions to Argo Workflows will allow developers to fully develop and test pipelines locally.

*Outcomes*

* Faster developer cycles by minimizing transitions into the cloud and eliminating context switching
* Reduced cloud costs by enabling developers to build and test solutions on their local machines rather than using the 'dev' cloud environment
* Reduced costs of integration by allowing continuous integration, not just of the code but also of the infrastructure
* One of the larger pieces of our infrastructure will no longer be reliant on AWS for deployment 

h3. Definition of Done:

* All step functions are ported over into Argo Workflows syntax
* Workflows can be built and developed locally leveraging Tilt and a Kind Kubernetes cluster
* All new development on workflows happens through Argo Workflows
column166: Port Over Step Functions To Argo Workflows

[BE] Validate document sources when documents are provisioned for a checklist
column43:
When documents are provisioned to be uploaded to a checklist and be converted to a work item, we need to verify that each document is using a content map that is defined as a valid source for the checklist. If documents are uploaded using other sources it causes problems when they are used to create work items.

We may also want to modify the checklist API so that checklist item definitions use source_ids rather than content_map_ids, this would help enforce the association.

*Acceptance Criteria:*

* When provisioning documents for a checklist, verify that all content maps are valid checklist sources
* Return a 400 error if any of the documents are using a content map that isn’t a source for the checklist

🧐 {color:#0747a6}*Why do we do it (context)*{color}{color:#0747a6}:{color}

This is a requirement for compliance. All internal departments, processes, or any independent client business elements that are considered critical and whose extended loss would have a significant impact on DeepSee operations have a Business Continuity Plan (BCP) and/or Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) for its operations.

DeepSee Leadership and GRC must regularly assess the impact of potential disasters on business operations as part of the required annual risk assessment. This includes our ability to:

* Effectively manage any incident that may cause a business disruption to DeepSee
* Provide continuity of critical business processes and services managed by DeepSee
* Minimize the potential impact that any business disruption would have on DeepSee and its reputation

Contracts with third-party suppliers that provide critical services to DeepSee include:

* Communication and understanding of the relevant plans for the respective supplier’s role
* Adequate contingency or recovery strategies over the lifecycle of the product and service

🤔 {color:#0747a6}*What we need to do (outcome):*{color}

Business continuity and Disaster Recovery (BCDR) planning is documented and approved by management for processes and business units (as applicable) that are identified as critical for operational resiliency.

h3. *Business Continuity Plan*

The BCP shall include the activities to be performed in case of an incident/disaster which can occur due to internal or external events. The BCP consists of activities to be followed to protect personnel and assets following a disaster and resume services quickly. 

||*As a SaaS, We Must*||*So That*||
|Define strategies to ensure the safety of personnel|We ensure the safety and wellbeing of our personnel|
|Perform analysis of potential threats|We have a clear understanding of potential threats|
|Define/Review alternate strategies to continue business operations (alternate site of operations) in a defined time frame|Have a defined backup plan to maintain operations|
|Produce a list of the primary tasks required to continue the operations along with assigned responsibilities (recovery team)|We know who’s running point on the recovery event|
|Have easy to locate management contact information|We can reach anyone required to regain operations|
|Communicate explanation of where personnel should go if there is a disastrous event|We Minimize any confusion, know what to do prior|
|Define information on data backups and organization site backup|We define/know how we will recover data and sites|
|Define communication strategies|We define an update and inform cadence|
|Get buy-in from everyone in the organization|We agree to agree|

h3. *Disaster Recovery Plan*

DeepSee has established a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) that addresses the step-by-step process of recovering and reinstating the business operations to a pre-disaster state, which may include assessing the damage, estimating recovery costs, working with insurance companies, monitoring the progress of the recovery process and transitioning the management of the business operations from the recovery team back to the regular managers.

A dedicated disaster recovery functional team may be established for the management and implementation of the DRP.

||*As a SaaS, We Must*||*So That*||
|Maximize the effectiveness of contingency operations through an established plan that consists of the following phases:
* *_Activation and Notification_* to activate the plan and determine the extent of damage
* *_Recovery_* to restore SaaS availability and business operations
* *_Reconstitution_* to ensure that SaaS availability is validated through testing and that normal operations are resumed|We are can execute our DRP and track the efficiency and effectiveness of the plan at all phases|
|Identify the activities, resources, and procedures to carry out SaaS processing requirements during prolonged interruptions to normal operations|Dependencies and procedures are well-defined and up to date|
|Assign responsibilities to designated DeepSee personnel and provide guidance for recovering SaaS during prolonged periods of interruption to normal operations.|Roles and responsibilities are well-defined and up to date|
|Ensure coordination with other personnel responsible for DeepSee contingency planning strategies, including coordination with external points of contact and vendors associated with SaaS and execution of this plan|All internal and external lines of communications are captured|

h3. *Exercising and Testing*

Tests are *performed at least annually* by designated personnel authorized by DeepSee’s management to test the execution of business continuity and disaster recovery plans. Testing involves collaboration with critical third parties to ensure vendor-dependent services and/or system(s) can be recovered to meet DeepSee’s Recovery Time Objective (RTO) and Recovery Point Objective (RPO).

*** Records of the test results indicate such information as whether the test was successful or requires corrective actions. In addition, DeepSee’s BCP and DRPs are updated based on the results of the tests performed and lessons learned.*

h3. +Context+
As we onboard new customers an inevitable component of any customer contract will be a Service Level Agreement (SLA) that specifies specific uptime requirements for services delivered to customers. Often times service level agreements come with financial penalties if they are not met consistently. Accordingly it is paramount that we properly identify service level agreements and have the infrastructure in place to effectively measure adherence to those agreements.

In addition to ensuring we are meeting our contractual SLA’s monitoring and reporting on SLA’s enables the use of [error budgets|https://www.atlassian.com/incident-management/kpis/error-budget]. Error budgets are a useful tool to identify processes that are out of control and allow for steps to remediate issues. This is a useful tool to manage by exception. 

h3. +Outcome+
* Monitoring of SLA’s for services delivered to customers mitigates financial and reputational risks associated with violating SLA’s
* Leveraging error budgets we can determine which teams/services need improved processes related to development and deployment
* Monitoring of services enables us to respond quickly to incidents before they are recognized by the customers and ultimately drives down mean time to recovery

h3. +Definition of Done+
* Target SLA’s for uptime are identified for each service in each environment
* Metrics that define 'uptime' are defined for each core service
** Mean api response time
** Number of error responses from services and API
* A dashboard is created for each service in production that displays the average uptime for a  given mont
* A dashboard that includes a rolling average uptime is available that includes a target line so that we can easily see at a glance our uptime trend

┆{color:#707070}Issue is synchronized with a [Trello card|https://trello.com/c/EMl9wwBc] by [Unito|https://www.unito.io]{color}

h3. +Context:+
Automating processes to build our services and deploy them into production is a crucial component for accelerating value creation from development teams. Currently most of our services have at least some automation for deployments into our various environments, but there is currently no standardization around:

* Test Coverage Requirements
* Linting standards 
* Repository structures
* Code scanning 
* Supply chain validation

Standardizing the structure of builds and the creating uniform structure for each of our various service modalities is an important aspect of creating standardized processes. Standardized processes and structures allow for developers to focus on the core domain problem rather than on the structure of code and other [“boilerplate“|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boilerplate_text] considerations. 

h3. +Outcome:+
* Standardized builds and deploy processes will lead to faster cycle times which will enable more throughput for delivery teams.
* Uniform coding standards around test coverage and linting will enable new developers and teams to ramp up more quickly and therefore begin adding value more quickly
* Automated repository templating tools will enable new services to be developed more rapidly for rapid prototyping and more quickly responding to market conditions to facilitate the sales process
* Shifting non functional concerns like security scanning left will encourage teams to fix potential issues as they are introduced and minimize the addition of technical debt to new services. 

h3. +*Definition of Done:*+
* All services that are actively developed have a standard repository structure
* Linting is enforced through the build process and before the code is pushed using pre-commit hooks
* Test coverage is enforced across all relevant repositories
** New code should have 100% test coverage
** If a particular pull request does not meet specific code coverage requirements then the build will fail and merging will be blocked
** Coverage reports are included in each of the README’s using coveralls
* Standard linting tools are used across each of the different languages: Python, Java, and Go
* Each of the actively developed services are deployed in a uniform way
** Docker images are built using Github Workflows
** Deployment is done through ArgoCD and automatically triggers to development
** One click promotion of deployment artifacts into each higher order environment
* Failed builds alert through appropriate slack channels

┆{color:#707070}Issue is synchronized with a [Trello card|https://trello.com/c/pqA90FmZ] by [Unito|https://www.unito.io]{color}

column1: Cloud Agnostic - Build Once Run Anywhere
column43:
h3. +*Context*+
Building out systems that do not tightly couple our product offerings to a single cloud vendor, is a strategic objective in pursuit of the following objectives:

* Operational Agility
* Faster Time To Market
* Expanding our Total Addressable Market
* Protecting the Unit Economics of our Product Offerings

A detailed explanation of the Why? What? and How? can be found [on confluence here]([https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/IN/pages/1937047709/Transitioning+to+Cloud+Native+and+Vendor+Agnostic+Infrastructure|https://deepsee.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/IN/pages/1937047709/Transitioning+to+Cloud+Native+and+Vendor+Agnostic+Infrastructure|smart-link]).

h3. +*Outcomes*+
* Faster developer cycle times through local development of full stack implementations leads to overall increased throughput
* Total addressable market is expanded by enabling deployment of our services into any major cloud provider
* Costs of environments is reduced as the need for development environments in the cloud are minimized

h3. +Definition of Done+
* Development of all services can be done locally using a local Kubernetes cluster in combination with Tilt
* Full stack Deeprecon services can be deployed into a cloud provider other than AWS

🧐 {color:#0747a6}*Why do we do it (context)*{color}{color:#0747a6}:{color}

 User access to information systems and IT assets is authorized based on job roles and responsibilities and according to business requirements.

Access control to information systems and services covers all stages of the user access life-cycle from granting and modifying user access to terminating access. Access to systems and IT assets is granted based on:

🤔 {color:#0747a6}*What we need to do (outcome):*{color}

||*As a SaaS, We Must*||*So That*||
|Ensure access to the DeepSee information systems is controlled using password authentication or a public/private key system with a strong passphrase|We keep record of access to our system and its dependencies|
|Enforce users are assigned a unique user ID whenever possible and generic accounts are avoided
* The initial password provided by the administrator must be changed at first login|We can track/correlate activity down to the individual user|
|Capture common device identifiers like Media Access Control (MAC), Internet Protocol (IP) addresses, or device-unique token identifiers, are used to uniquely identify users in a group account|We can track/correlate activity down to the device or service|
|Enforce users must not share their passwords with others or reveal the same to others under any circumstances
* Passwords for user and administrator accounts must be changed periodically|We can manage identity against action|
|Enable account lockout (temporary or unlimited) should be applied, whenever possible, after a defined number of unsuccessful login attempts|Protect ourselves from certain attacks|
|Enable users are automatically logged off from the information systems after a defined period of inactivity|Prevent inadvertent system access|
|Enforce a minimum password must be at least eight (8) characters long
* For improved security, longer passwords should be used|Prevent or protect against certain types of attacks|
|Require passwords must contain alphanumeric and special characters (i.e., use passwords containing both upper- and lower-case characters (e.g., a-z, A-Z), have digits and punctuation characters as well as letters, e.g., 0-9, !@#$%^&*()_+|~-=\`{}[]:";'<>?,./)|Make it challenging for dictionary-based attacks|
|Enforce passwords may not be repeated/reused when required to be reset|Implement best practices for password usage|
|Require users use multi-factor authentication|Support a zero-trust architecture|
|Limit to appropriate IT personnel administer and manage administrator and system account passwords|Implement least-privileges|
|Enforce user identity must be verified before resetting any authentication credentials|Support a zero-trust architecture|
|Enforce passwords for default system accounts must be modified or disabled before installing a system on the network|Don’t make it easy for would-be attackers|

h3. +Ensure supporting documentation is included (e.g. UX designs)+ 

Evidence of DeepSee’s Access Authentication controls are required to gain SOC 2 Type 2 approval. This is focused around two controls:

* [AA1 - Unique IDs, Strong Passwords, and MFA - Infrastructure|https://my.tugboatlogic.com/org/12481/controls/525165]
* [AA2 - Unique IDs and Strong Passwords - Applications|https://my.tugboatlogic.com/org/12481/controls/525133]

+Collection interval+: yearly

h3. +*Acceptance Criteria:*+

* All evidence is automatically submitted to tugboat on an annual basis
* Provide password configuration for all in-scope infrastructure (see below) i.e. active directory, servers and databases supporting the in-scope application.
* Provide evidence of a documented, reviewed and communicated Access control policy.
* Provide screenshot(s) of password configuration for all in-scope applications (see below) that show at least:
** The min/max length.
** The defined password complexity.
** The password change frequency (e.g. every 90 days).
** Account lock-out threshold (e.g. six failed attempts).
** Account lock-out duration (e.g. 30 minutes or until an administrator enables the user id).
** The number of generations during which a password cannot be re-used.
** That an immediate change to a permanent password is required when a temporary password is used.

h3. +Context:+
A SOC 2 Type 2 accreditation is an internal controls audit capturing how a company safeguards customer data and how well those controls are operating over time. It is third-party verification that we are executing against our identified GRC policies and procedures.

The control families and associated evidence tasks are:

* *Access Authentication (*3)*
* *Access Control (*12)*
* Awareness Training (*2)
* *Change Management (*5)*
* *Continuity and Resilience (*6)*
* *Data Security (*4)*
* Human Resources (*4)
* Incident Management (*5)
* Organization and Management (*11)
* Risk Management (*3)
* *Security Operations (*14)*
* Vendor Management (*2)
* *Workstation Security (*3)*

h3. +Outcome:+
* If evidence collection can be automated then it should be automated
* All evidence for the controls are implemented and able to be collected (prefer automation)
* A way to monitor that evidence is produced and delivered, alert on failure and retry

🧐 *Why do we do it (context)*: 

We need an enhanced document flow in DeepRecon to both enable user workflow as well as human in the loop learning from the users. These statuses are visible in the content map and process model UI pages. These statuses are likely also different from the BE/ML statuses which speak to the technical statuses. We may want to add another there for “Deal Processing” which would happen before “not started”, but in a way that is different (user has no influence on that status unlike what is outlined below). Would like to discuss with team.



🤔 {color:#0747a6}*What we need to do (outcome):*{color} 

!image-20230217-200016.png|width=100%!

🛑{color:#0747a6} *When do we stop (acceptance criteria):*{color}

Below design shows where the status belongs in work items (both for each work item and the filters)

* Delete button actually archives instead of deletes so can be auditable even though not visible in the UI at that point

!image-20221221-214751.png|width=100%!

Below built content map screen has the status built in. Need to uplift with new field for Test vs Train

!image-20221221-215127.png|width=100%!

there are three things that this is intended to enable

* Human-In-The-Loop model learning for unstructured documents. As users manage their workflows in the DeepRecon Work Items, the feedback from users is consumed and applied for future work items
** enable users to make corrections to documents that were completed in the work items from the content map (training and testing repo). This is because work items, at least for now, are one and done. We don't uncomplete, change, and recomplete. But users need to be able to maintain all annotations over time
** this does not apply for structured documents
** discussion with ML needed to determine how to manage BKR/KNO (and other multi-issuance) products where users don't review all predictions and therefore may unintentionally used to reinforce inaccurate predictions
* Give users statuses to help support their workflow (not started, in progress, completed, and archive for documents incorrectly loaded or that have failed and clogging the queue)
* Give users the ability to define “test” documents that are used by model version candidates to measure performance without allowing those same docs to be put into the training set (artificially inflating performance scores)
** this further enables users (and us) to create candidates and test without interruption to the production flow and not need a separate environment that would have to migrate to production.
* Enable us (and end users in the future) to assess model performance and drift

column252: 21/Dec/22 9:08 AM;603965d725b84e006969d999;those are underpinnings to why we had to leave Atlas behind. First, it doesn’t have HITL learning from users. The model predictions never get better with use. Maybe there is another way to manage that? Next, Atlas has a production and a sandbox environment. That means users make changes in sandbox, create and assess tests, and when happy make us move all the work from sandbox into production. Migrating data across environments is bad design and workflow, while violating our data isolation controls. not to mention many times we try it it doesn’t work anyway. So the above flow is also intended to enable users to makes and test changes within their production environment without interrupting their production flow until what they are working with is fully tested and deemed ready to be promoted as the next production version

column1: [tech debt] modify the behavior of term_group_terms to always populate the term_group_id
column43:
Currently, for term_group_terms records that represent terms that are part of a subgroup we DO NOT populate the term_group_id column - it is currently mutually exclusive between term_group_id and term_subgroup_id - even though the term_group_id will always be the same for a given term_subgroup_id

This results in some pretty complex queries - particularly on the ML side of things.

I’d like to start populating the term_group_id column on all term_group_term records which means some changes across a lot of elements of the extractor service and then simplifying the ML queries. This additionally includes a change to the data via a SQL Delta.

All operations for adding terms to the group/subgroup, retrieving term lists, etc. need to account for this behavior change

column1: Implement capability to control data traversal while supporting customer requirements (support)
column43:
h3. Why:

Customer requires DeepSee to implement auditable controls to ensure their data does not ‘leak’. There are four immediate requirements (see linked issues). We will see similar requirements from prospects and new customers in BFS. This approach satisfies the customer requirement without impacting staff not interacting with customer data.

h3. What:

The following high-level architecture was discussed/shared with the customer:

!Customer Data Protection.png|width=75%!
